blocks.text: I thought it went pretty well, Houston, although I expect I used more gas than I've been using in the simulator. During the course of that, we drifted slightly further away from the S-IVB than I expected. I expected to be out about 6 feet. My guess would be I was around 100 or so; and therefore, I expect I used a bit more coming back in. But, except for using a little more gas - And I'd be interested in your numbers on that - everything went nominally.

blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We see your middle gimbal angle getting pretty big. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, it was, Charlie, but in going from one AUTO maneuver to another, we took over control and have gone around gimbal lock; and we're about to give control back to the DAP.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We see it increasing now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, maybe you better call Lou and tell him we might be a little bit late for dinner.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Sure will. We'd like for you to turn on - the fan on in O2 tank number 2, Buzz. And, 11, did you - On your optics calibrations, did you proceed or recall the program? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We recalled the program.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And O2 fan number 2 is on.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. I've got a CRYO pressure light and a MASTER ALARM. It's reset.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We expected that. That's why we had you turn the fan on. We were getting pretty
close to the caution and warning limits. We were trying to prevent that.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. You're looking at our DELTA-DELTA-Ve. It looks like DELTA-Re is pretty large, there. We wanted to talk to you about it before we incorporate it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Mike. We don't have anything on our downlink here, I don't think, on the DSKY. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Our NOUN 49 is reading: register 1, plus 08793; register 2, all balls.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Guidance is looking at the NOUN 40 - 49 stuff. We'll be back with you momentarily. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. Thank you. We'll just hold right here in the program.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We got the downlink now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to reject the NOUN 49 stuff on the DSKY right now, Mike, and try it again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Will do.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. Apollo 11. Here's another 49 for you. Are you getting it on the downlink?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We see it. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We recommend you accept the NOUN 49 display on the DSKY now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. It looks like an awful big one. We noticed that you'd moved star number 2 to the
tail end of the listing, and we should be marking first on star 40. Did that have anything to do with it?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative. We don't believe so, Apollo 11. We think that this is possibly due to some TLI dispersions, and it's probably satisfactory. So go ahead and accept this. It fits our criteria anyway that if you repeat the mark and you get an equivalent size to go ahead and accept it. And this is an equivalent size error. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We'll do it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And 11, Houston. Your state vector in the LM slots are - is good. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. If you like this, we'll accept it as well.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We recommend you accept the NOUN 49. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. Thank you. We'll do that now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And we're going to proceed on this one, too, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Another NOUN 49 for you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to recycle and do this one over again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.
Houston, Apollo 11.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, Apollo 11. Over.
Roger. Why don't you sing out when you think we've done enough battery charging on B.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by, Buzz. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'll be charging battery B up until the sleep period. We'll discontinue charging at that time. Also, at about 12 25 in the flight plan, we have battery A charge. That has been deleted. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand. We'll charge until the sleep period on B and delete the battery A charge.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And, Houston, Apollo 11. These AUTO optics maneuvers or P23's, AUTO maneuvers, don't seem to be going to the substellar point. Can you come up with the roll, pitch, and yaw angle for the substellar point on this star? It's our second star.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Your angles in the flight plan we feel are still good. 198.6 130.7, 340.0. Just slightly off than those in the flight plan. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We'll try that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, state those three angles one more time. I'd like to confirm them before I maneuver.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Roll and pitch are slightly off than what's in the flight plan, 11. Roll is now 198.6, pitch is 1307. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Roll 198.6, pitch 130.7, and yaw 34000.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. I think the problem here is that that attitude just is not too close to the substellar point. I'm having to maneuver quite a bit, and that's in progress now, so stand by for some marks.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy it all.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We've run the angles given in the flight plan for the P23

attitude through the machines down here, and they come up the same thing every time. We think everything's going correctly, Mike, and we're wondering if the nonsymmetrical horizon might by giving a problem. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, I'd say - It could be, Charlie. Stand by here. We'll get another mark for you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. NOUN 49 for you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We recommend you accept the NOUN 49. Continue through your sequence of sightings, and then we'll analyze the data afterwards. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Star 40 has just disappeared now in the sextant. Could the trunnion angle 47 - something be a little high?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to press on to star 44. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Roger. All right. How many marks have you recorded on star 40?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We copied two good marks. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Forty-four is just not bright enough for this. There's a reddish glow filling the black area of the sextant, and the star is lost somewhere in there, and I cannot see it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by. We'll come up with another star. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. I'd appreciate that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to go on to star 45. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, Mike, we think these large DELTA-rcs, NOUN 49, you're getting is really meaningful since it's been way before TLI since we had a state vector update, and we think it's normal. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Could be, Charlie. Some of the early markings, I might not have had precisely the substellar point. I think as time goes by they've been coming more accurate but old Enif here is just flat invisible.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And, Houston, Apollo 11. Understand that the same three gimbal angles you gave me should be valid for star 45 as well. Is that affirmative?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I'm believe that's right. Stand by one. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That is negative. Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Because there's quite a difference between the gimbal angles you have and the gimbal angles the program wants, but with inaccurate state vector, I'm inclined not to believe the program.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. LMP is back on the line.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Read you five-boy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Same, Buzz. And, 11, the angles for you are 1978 for roll, 1285 pitch, 3400 yaw.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Just as a matter of comparison, P23 for this star would like to go to 235.66, 154.31, and 31365. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy, 11. We understand that the program can give you almost an infinite combination of angles in P23, and it's not too unreasonable. If you'll stand by, we'll look at these that we see on the DSKY. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Then in the meantime I'll just go ahead and maneuver to yours. 197.8, 128.5, and 340.0.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. If the attitude you gave me on star number 45 - The reticle is off, I'd say, a good 30 degrees in roll, and the star is not in sight. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I think something's wrong with those attitudes.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. I wondered if you have AUTO optics selected. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Looks like to us we need a PROCEED, Mike, to get the sextant pointed at the star. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Those shaft and trunnion angles were exactly what we were computing on the ground. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I'm going to trim up the attitude here and give it another try.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I have this star loud and clear now, Charlie, so I might as well do a bunch of marks on this one to get a good horizon count.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It still looks like I'm far from the substellar point. However, I'm off quite a bit in roll.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'd like you to mark right where it is now, Mike, and we'd like two sets of marks on this. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine. But the reticle is not parallel to the horizon. I'd have to move off quite a bit in order to get it parallel to that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Our procedures guys are saying that the reticle does not have to be parallel. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, then we're not at the substellar point if we're not.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, you copy that NOUN 49?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We see it, 11. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We would like you to accept this one and every mark thereafter. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Do you need me to wait in the NOUN 49 display for any length of time?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. I'll be glad to give you as many of these as you like.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'd like six marks on star 45, Mike, and then we'll probably go back to star 2 again. Stand by. We'll have further word on that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: They seem to be getting smaller, Charlie.. Are you sure you wouldn't like some more?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's no trouble.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like you to do two more on star 45. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. There's your two more marks. Where do you want to go from here?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like you to go back to star number 2 with an attitude as follows: roll 1952, pitch 1239, yaw 3400. Mike, that'll give you a trunnion angle of about 31.4. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I understand star number 2 and roll 195.2, pitch 123.9, and yaw 340.0. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. I'm there, and I've got a trunnion angle of 30.5 degrees. Again, misaligned considerably in roll and I do believe that's important to getting good marks.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: See, if my reticle's not parallel, then I'm not marking normal to the horizon and I'm not marking at the substellar point. I'm marking off somewhere else.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by one. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. The ground-computed values for your shaft and trunnion are just what you're getting on the DSKY there, Mike. The horizon looks cocked off to you - You look like you're off in roll because the angles that we gave you to maneuver to, to prevent IM reflection from fouling up your optics, we feel like a - You should go ahead and mark on the stars just as is. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'll bet you a cup of coffee on it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.
VERB - NOUN 49 for you, Charlie.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like to accept this one and give us two more and that will be enough. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We see your termination on P23. Thank you very much. Mike, we'll have a - We're trying to work up a story here for you; we'll be with you momentarily on an explanation of what's happening. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. It just appears to me that you have to have a reticle tangent to the horizon at the point at which you mark or else you're not at the substellar point; you're off laterally, and therefore you're measuring a larger trunnion angle than you should.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Seems so to me. Our procedures people are working on this, and we'll be back with you momentarily. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you, sir.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to go POOR in ACCEPT. We'll have a PTC REFSMMAT for you momentarily. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Going POOR in ACCEPT.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We're through with the load. You can go back to BLOCK.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You're BLOCK. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to do a P52, option 1 preferred, and establish PTC as listed in the flight plan at 12 hours. We'd like you to commence that right now, Mike. And we have some stars recommended for you. For stars 26, 30, and 24, when you get to attitude 000. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. He's off the wick right now. Understand you're ready for us to do a P52, option 1?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, it's a P52, option 1 preferred. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. And, let's see, that is Spica, Menkent, and what else?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stars - Codes are stars 26, 30, and 24. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: 24. Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We notice your PRO- GUAM ALARM, Mike, was due to using these stars in the P23 attitude. If you'll go to 000, the stars we gave you will work. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Understand.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Prior to you starting your P52, we'd like to give you a new CSM state vector. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Wait till we finish the maneuver and we'll give you the DSKY.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're standing by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. The DSKY is yours.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. The DSKY is yours.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. You can do the VERB 66. The computer is yours, and then the P52, option 1 preferred. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Do you read? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. If you read, this attitude 000 is pretty bad for our COMM. In fact, we've lost all data with you, and unreadable on the voice. We recommend you do the P52, option 1 preferred ...

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: ... not a very good attitude at all for COMM, and as soon as we finish our alignment, we'll maneuver it to a different attitude. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We copy. Recommend you go to this P52, option 1 preferred, and then go to PTC attitude. Over. Then we'll get some COMM. When you get there to PTC attitude, it'll be pitch 90, yaw 0 on the high gain. Over.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. You're about one-boy. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. You're about one-boy. Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Read you about four-boy. How me? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You're loud and clear, Charlie. We pitched down some to get a better COMM attitude.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Did you copy our recommendation on proceeding with the P52, Mike? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Negative. We didn't. I've got that in work. I'm starting on P52.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Copy our torquing angles. We're about to torque them.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. The reason for delay, Charlie, is that - difficult to find two stars that are not occulted by the IM and also are not in the midst of a manmade star field up here with dumps.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. You can torque the NOUN 93. Over

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. That completes the P52. We verified the third star with Antares, and AUTO optics are pointing at it pretty closely. How do our platform drift angles look so far, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We didn't have a chance to get a good check for you. We're going to run a drift check from this alignment until the next one, approximately 12 hours, and we'll have something for you later. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to establish your PTC. We recommend you select quads Alfa and Delta. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Understand Alfa and Delta quads.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Would you verify that the ATTITUDE SET switch is in GDC? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: The SET switch. Stand by one, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It is now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It was on IMU.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How many miles out do you have us now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We have you - Stand by, Buzz. Roughly about 50 000. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It's a beautiful sight.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Charlie, on that PTC, we're just waiting our 20 minutes here for all thruster activity to damp out. You might let us know how that's coming.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Will do. We have you about 48 000 miles now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We still have our oxygen fan on for tank 2. Is that what you want?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, Charlie, I can see the snow on the mountain out in California, and it looks like LA doesn't have much of a smog problem today.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. Copy. Looks like there's a good view out there then.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like you to keep the O2 fan on. It will give you an ECS configuration prior to sleep. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thanks.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Charlie, with the monocular, I can discern a definite green cast to the San Fernando Valley.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How's Baja California look, Buzz?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, it's got some clouds up and down it, and there's a pretty good circulation system a couple of hundred miles off the west coast of California.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. 11, we'd like you to close the waste storage vent valve right now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Waste storage vent valves closed.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like - The rates are looking pretty good right now on the PTC, but we'd like you to continue holding. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Your rates look really great, now. You can start your PTC.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thanks, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, you read 11?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead, 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. If you'd like to delay PTC after - for 10 minutes or so, we can shoot you some TV of seven-eights earth. That's - We'll leave that up to you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'll have our answer for you on the TV in about 1 minute. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We're ready at Goldstone for the TV. It'll be recorded at Goldstone and then replayed back over here. Neil, any time you want to turn her on, we're ready. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. It'll take us about 5 minutes to get rigged.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Could you verify the reading on your O2 flow indicator? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're still on 0.2. We just inadvertently touched the RAPID REPRESS button. That made a temporary glitch in the flow.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. During that glitch there, did it go almost a peg high? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I'd believe that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Could you tell us if the O2 flow indicator was pegged high prior to closing the waste storage vent valve? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No, it was not.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. While ago we tracked into the scan limits and disabled the AUTO drive on the high gain. We'd like you to position the antenna at pitch 30, yaw 270, go to REACQ and that will give us narrow beamwidth. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That yaw 270 and pitch 3 - What was the pitch?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Pitch 30, Neil.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. I think we've got you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We've got a good signal there. Thank you much.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. We are sending picture of Earth down right now, so you can - Let us know if they're receiving at Goldstone.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Goldstone is receiving the TV. Stand by. We'll let you know on the quality. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Goldstone says that the TV looks great. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We're zooming in on the Earth now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Did you copy? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We copied, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Your transmissions the last couple of times have been about two-boy. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. How do you read me now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. You're five-boy now.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We're zooming the lens on in until it will just about fill the monitor.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. It's in full zoom, now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And how about the of-stop? Is 22 going to be accurate?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. We'll get with the Goldstone TV guy. We don't have anything here at Houston. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It looks good on the monitor, as far as the of-stop goes. Therefore, we just assumed it's okay at Goldstone.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Goldstone says it - TV looks really great, five-boy, we don't - The AGC looks like it's working fine. The f:22 is good, we have no real white spots. They're real pleased with it. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. You just cut out, Charlie. We understand that it's looking great. We'll leave it the way it is and wait for you to come back on.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. How do you read me now? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Five-boy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. My comments were - My comments were from Goldstone that they see no white spots as we saw in 10. Looks like the AGC's working real well. The f.22 looks good. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Very good. Well, we shut out the Sun coming in from the other windows into the space-craft, so it's looking through a - the number 1 window, and there isn't any reflected light now. So, it ought to be a pretty good picture.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to keep the TV on for about 10 minutes or so, so we can get come good comparison on the camera. You can do anything your heart desires on the TV interior, exterior, pan in and out, anything you'd like. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, I'm sorry, you keep cutting out. We heard up to "you can do anything," and then after that we didn't hear anything, and we knew that wasn't right anyhow because we can't. But what do you want us to do?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll check this uplink on our voice. That transmission on the TV was - We'd like to get about 10 minutes worth of signal at Old-stone so we can look at the camera quality back here at Houston for about 10 minutes or so when they patch it back into us. What we were saying was that you can go interior or exterior on the camera. On the exterior shots, we'd like to look -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You cut out again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Start over with, "we were saying."

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. You suppose you could turn the Earth a little bit so we can get a little bit more than just water?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. I don't think we got much control over that. Looks like you'll have to settle for the water.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We're going to change - thinking about changing our voice uplink to another site. If you'll stand by, we'll see if we can improve the quality. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We'll stand by for your call.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We'll try once more on this TV request. We'd like 10 minutes worth of TV. And we'd like a narrative, if you could give us one, on the exterior shots. You could also - we also suggest you might try the - an interior position. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We're seeing the center of the Earth as viewed from the spacecraft in the eastern Pacific Ocean. We have not been able to visually pick up the Hawaiian Island chain, but we can clearly see the western coast of North America. The United States, the San Joaquin Valley, the High Sierras, Baja California, and Mexico down as far as Acapulco, and the Yucatan Peninsula; and you can see on through Central America to the northern coast of South America, Venezuela, and Colombia. I'm not sure you'll be able to see all that on your screen down there ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. We just wanted a narrative such that we can - When we get the playback, we can sort of correlate what we're seeing. Thank you very much.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I haven't seen anything but the DSKY so far.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Looks like they're hogging the window.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You're right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. On your CRYO's, we'd like at this time for you to place all four CRYO heaters to AUTO and turn off all four CRYO fans. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. All four CRYO heaters are AUTO. And all four CRYO fans are off. ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's going to be your sleep configuration.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, Buzz, we'll be terminating the battery charge in about a half hour.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. You can terminate the TV at your convenience. We've got enough take. And you can start PTC at your convenience. The rates look super for starting up. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger, Charlie
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We have a flight plan update for you and some P37 block data, if you're ready to copy. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. PTC is started now; locks good to us, and we'll be ready to copy in a minute or two.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Ready to copy the flight plan update and P37.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by one, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Coming at you with the P37 block data. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: COMM
blocks.text: Roger, 11. That was a good readback. That was the block data scheduled for 12 hours. We'd like to just say that on a flight plan update here, just to remind you of some things, and you can do them at your convenience and then go to sleep early if you'd like. We don't have anything else planned, but we'd like to just remind you on the filter change, the O2 fuel cell purge. And we'd like delta-Up and accomplish the presleep checklist.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We've completed the filter change, and we'll get started on the fuel cell purge, and stand by for the IM/CM DELTA-Up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Would you hold off on the fuel cell purge? EECOMM is saying we might not have to do that. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, the IM/CM DELTA-Up is 0.5.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy. 0.5. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We've just decided to delete the O2 fuel cell purge. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Delete the O2 fuel cell purge.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We've been noting some funnies on the O2 flow indicator transducer. We've kind of got a suspicion that the transducer - We expected to see an O2 flow pegged high with the waste stowage vent to VENT. It was not. We also noted some funny indications when you closed the waste stowage vent valve. We're going to continue to take a look at this through the night, and we'll be with you in the morning with an assessment of the problem. Also, we'd like to ask specifically, when you place the waste stowage vent valve to VENT, does the detent - correction - Does the arrow line up with the detent? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Stand by one, Charlie. We'll give you something on the detent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Right now it's at CLOSED, and I lined up with CLOSED before I was at VENT, and best I can recall, it was quite accurately lined up with VENT. Would you like me to go to VENT again momentarily and see where it lines up?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's negative. That question's answered. Thank you much.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We have an Is-band configuration for you. Over.
Roger. Go ahead.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. We'd like you to place the Is-band antenna OMNI A switch to the Bravo position. Is-band antenna OMNI switch to the OMNI position, the high gain track to MANUAL, and the high gain angles will be yaw 270, pitch minus 50.0 Over.
Roger. Understand. OMNI to Baker and OMNI, MANUAL. And the angles are yaw 270, pitch minus 50, and was that narrow or wide? Over.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Stand by. Roger. We'd like it in WIDE, and you can set that configuration up now. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It's in work.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. You can terminate battery Bravo charge, and we'd like a crew status report. We're about to tell you good night. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. The battery charging is complete, and the crew status report is as follows: radiation, CDR 11002, CMP 10002, LMP 09003; negative medication; fit as a fiddle. (Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy, 11. Thank you much. We'd like to ask one question. Have you tried the gas separator on the water? How is that working? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. Mike's got a couple of comments on that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's working good so far, Charlie. We've got one installed on the water gun and the other one installed on the spigot down in the LEB, and we - mention one problem with them is that they leak at the junction between the food bag and the water filter. However, with that exception, they seem to be working pretty good. We were getting some gas through initially, and I think that was just getting the system purged out to begin with; and the last tubeful we poured was almost free of bubbles. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Sounds good. We'll check in on that problem with the SPAN guys; and let you know in the morning. If you have to call us tonight, we'd like you to do it on DOWNVOICE BACKUP. We're configuring the MSFN for that mode; and as far as we can see, you're cleared for some z's. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Maybe we'll get around to lunch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How about a peanut butter and jelly?
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Hope you aren't - we aren't disturbing you. We'd like you to terminate the NOUN 65 now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.
Houston, Apollo 11 ...
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. When you stopped - or, correction - When you terminated the NOUN 65, it appears to us, you get a VERB 46 which collapsed the deadband back to 0.5. We're okay as long as you do not turn on any AUTO RCS.SELECT switches. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I thought that was a - better way to clear the DSKY but evidently it isn't. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. VERB 34 would have been a better procedure.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. Thank you.
END OF TAPE
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Good morning, Houston. Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Apollo 11. Good morning.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: When you're ready to copy, 11, I've got a couple of small flight plan updates and your consumables update, and the morning news, I guess. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Apollo 11. ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Standing by for your updates. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. This is Houston. At time approximately 22 30 in the flight plan, in your postsleep checklist, and in all other postsleep checklists, we'd like you to delete the statement that says "AUTO RCS JET SELECT, 16 to ON," and what we're doing here is picking this up in the procedure for exiting PTC that's in your CSM checklist. And in the CSM checklist on page Foxtrot 9-8: if you want to turn to that, we'd like to change the order of the steps in that. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Page F 9-8. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Right now it reads, "To exit G&N PTC," then you've got pen-and-ink change that says, "AUTO RCS SELECT, 12 MAIN A and B." And you come down to the printed step 1. We'd like to take and move the B" down to be the second step, so the procedure would read, "Step 1, MANUAL ATTITUDE 3, ACCEL COMMAND, Step 2 AUTO RCS SELECT, 12 MAIN A B." Step 3 would be, "Verify DAP load," and so on. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. I copy. Is that AUTO RCS SELECT, 12 MAIN A, MAIN B to be the ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It should be the second step in that procedure. At time 22 40, or when you get to it, we'd like to commence a charge on battery A. And at time 24 10, we have an updated attitude for your P52 and optics calibration. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. 24 10. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. P52 and optics calibration attitude: roll 330.5, pitch 086.3, yaw 000.0. The nominal attitude that-and-inked in for the P23 is still good. At time 25 30, approximately, after you complete P23, we're requesting waste-water dump down to a nominal 25 percent. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Did you copy the attitudes and the waste-water dump? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger, Bruce. ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're not reading you at the present time. You're way down in the noise level. Stand by, please.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Standing by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. How do you read? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. Apollo 11. Loud and clear. How me?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Beautiful. Did you copy the attitudes for the P52 and the waste-water dump? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Okay. We note the battery charge as soon as we get around to it, and the attitude for the P52 optics CAL: roll 330.5, pitch 086.3, and yaw all zeros. The attitude for the P23 as in the flight plan is okay, and I copy your battery charge. Crew status report as follows. Sleep CDR 7, CMP 7, LMP 5.5. And we've completed the postsleep checklist. Standing by for a consumable update. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're requesting waste-water dump at GET 25 30 down to a nominal 25 percent, and here we go with the consumables update. At GET of 22 hours, RCS total is minus 3.5 percent. Alfa minus 3.5 percent, Bravo minus 1.5 percent, Charlie minus 5.0 percent, minus 4.0 percent, H2 minus 2 pounds, O2 minus 4 pounds. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I copied those consumables, and I'll read you back our RCS quantities. We got 86 percent in Alfa, 87 in Bravo, 88 in Charlie, and 90 in Delta. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And did you copy the waste-water request?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Waste water at - and we got the time on that, and it will be down to 25 percent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. We've started charging battery A, and voltage started off a lot higher than I expected. It was just a little bit shy of 40. It looks like it's dropping down some now, the battery charge holder. Seemed to me yesterday when we were doing this on battery C, it started out initially, and it went lower, the battery charge holder. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by a second, and I'll get some reading on that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: On charging battery A. now, it's at about 393 and - oh, about 1.5 amps. Looks like it's gradually increasing in the ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. On our CM, we're showing you at 39.11, and your current's about what you reported.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I guess you're happy, then.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I think we're losing you in the noise again, 11. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. On your battery charging question, we feel that it's probably a difference between individual batteries, and it does seem to have gone away as sort of a startup transient here. Other factors that might conceivably have an influence on it would be battery temperature, things of this sort. EECOMM seems to feel that it's operating within the normal design limits. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right. Very good. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. If you are interested in the morning news, I have a summary here from PAO. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We're all listening.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. From Jodrell Bank, England, via AP: Britain's big Jodrell Bank radio telescope stopped receiving signals from the Soviet Union's unmanned Moon shot at 5:49 EDT today. A spokesman said that it appeared the Luna 15 space ship "had gone beyond the Moon." Another quote: "We don't think it has landed," said a spokesman for Sir Bernard Lovell, Director of the Observatory. Washington UPI: Vice President Spiro T. Agnew has called for putting a man on Mars by the year 2000, but Democratic leaders replied that priority must go to needs on Earth. Agnew, ranking government official at the Apollo 11 blastoff Wednesday, apparently was speaking for himself and not necessarily for the Nixon administration when he said, "We should, in my judgment, put a man on Mars by the end of this century." Laredo, Texas, AP: Immigration officials in Nuevo Laredo announced Wednesday that hippies will be refused tourist cards to enter Mexico unless they take a bath and get haircuts. Huberto Cazaras, Chief of Mexican Immigration in Nuevo Laredo, said authorities in Mexico City, Acapulco, and other popular tourist spots have registered complaints about the hippies. By United Press International: Initial reaction to President Nixon's granting of a holiday Monday to Federal employees so they can observe a national day of participation in the Apollo 11 Moon landing mission mostly was one of surprise. Rodney Bidner, Associated Press, London AP: Europe is Moon-struck by the Apollo 11 mission. Newspapers throughout the continent fill their pages with pictures of the Saturn V rocket blasting off to forge Earth's first link with its natural satellite. And the headline writers taxed their imagination for words to hail the feat. "The greatest adventure in the history of humanity has started," declared the French newspaper Le Figaro, which devoted four pages to reports from Cape Kennedy and diagrams of the mission. The tabloid Paris Jour proclaimed, "The whole word tells them bravo." The Communists daily L'Humanite led with the launch picture and devoted its entire back page to an enthusiastic Moon report describing the countdown and launch, the astronauts' wives and families, and background lunar activities.

Hempstead, New York: Joe Namath officially reported to the New York Jets training camp at Hofstra University Wednesday following a closed door meeting with his teammates over his differences with pro football Commissioner Peter Rozelle. London UPI: The House of Lords was assured Wednesday that a midget American submarine would not "damage or assault" the Loch Ness monster. Lord Nomay said he wanted to be sure anyone operating a submarine in the Loch "would not subject any creatures that might inhabit it to damage or assault." He asked that the submarine's plan to take a tissue sample with a retrievable dart from any monster it finds can be done without damage and disturbance. He was told it was impossible to say if the 1876 Cruelty to Animals Act would be violated unless and until the monster was found. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you, Bruce. Another thing on that number 2 item, we all ... before we left, and we hope we get a chance to see him another time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And I understand he was down there and really enjoyed watching the launch. We all think it was pretty magnificent, and you all are doing a great job up there.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Mike, we've got some comments on performance of P23 for today if you've got a minute to talk.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: He's all ears.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. For today, we'd like you on P23 to make a trunnion bias determination, prior to P23 sightings as called out in procedures, and also one afterwards. Our intent here is to check out the possibility that some sort of thermal effect may be giving you errors in the angular read-out in the sextant. The bias that you get beforehand should be incorporated, that is a PROCEED on NOUN 87 after you get two consecutive measurements equal to within 0.003 degrees. And, of course, move the trunnion off a couple of degrees between the measurements. The Earth should be a lot smaller in your field of view today. I'm sure you're a lot more qualified to tell us about that than we are, but to ensure that you're getting a good angle measurement between the star and the Earth horizon, the sextant Lm-line, which is the line that runs through the two hash marks and is perpendicular to the Re-line, should be parallel to the Earth horizon at the substellar point. And then the actual superimposition of the star upon the horizon can be made at any point in the field of view of the sextant: above, below, or on the Lm-line. We recommend the marks be made as rapidly as possible after AUTO maneuver. If you feel that the amount of time between the AUTO maneuver and the time you get ready to mark is excessive, or that you don't like that AUTO maneuver attitude when you get ready to mark, of course, you can use a VERB 94 - VERB 94 to get you back to the flashing 51 position to redo the AUTO maneuvers. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by one. We're going to stop PTC, and then we'll talk about this P23.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We're stopping PTC now and maneuvering to our P52 and optics CAL attitude. In regard to that P23, what I was trying to tell you yesterday was about that. The Lm-line is not anywhere parallel to the horizon at the roll, pitch, and yaw which you gave me to go to for the substellar point, and I was trying to maneuver off to get it parallel to the horizon when you all said that was not necessary.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. I guess in keeping the cups of coffee score, why you get that one.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well - Okay - Well, this morning, let's just see how close it comes to being parallel to the Lm-line. Before we started marking for the first time, it appeared that the computation of - of those three angles was somewhat off, and that I was wasting a lot of gas by going to those three angles and then having to make large attitude changes after that to get the Lm-line parallel. In some cases it appeared to be just an accepted attitude required, and you all said that it wasn't needed. So I was marking in some cases with the Lm-line not parallel. I thought perhaps you had some processor for computing that offset and making sense out of that data, but as far as I know, we've got to have the Lm-line parallel to the horizon.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We don't have that capability. We do require that the Lm-line be parallel to the horizon in order to get a good mark. We feel that possibly the - the state vector information that you were using for your maneuver basis yesterday may have needed to be updated a little. And if you'll stand by a second, we'll give you an evaluation of what we feel you'll get today by the AUTO maneuver.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. I'm getting ready to do an O2 fuel cell purge. Do you have any particulars on this? And I assume you want these one at a time, or can I triple up? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We'd like them one at a time, and stand by. I don't think we have any sequence. You can do them in any order you want.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we're watching you on TM down here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. You want to look at these NOUN 93's before I proceed on?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes, please. Stand by a second.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. On our TM, here, we're only seeing values in two registers. Can you read us out the contents of register 3, please?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Register 3. minus three balls 24.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Minus three balls 24. And you can go ahead and proceed.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Proceeding at this time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. After you've completed P52, we'd like to uplink you a new state vector so we can start out clean on this P23. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, are you observing the higher O2 flow on fuel cell 3?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. It's triggered the MASTER ALARM three times, now. There goes number 4. It goes up to about 1.4, then oscillates back down to about 1.1. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We saw them 1.3 now on TM. Stand by a second.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And we're in P00, now, for a state vector.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Give us ACCEPT, please.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Done.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. On your O2 flow, fuel cell 3: apparently it was flowing a little higher than the other two during purge, but the flow rate is acceptable. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. It seems to be flowing a little bit more, and actually putting out more current than the other two, also. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We've completed the uplink, the computer is yours; you can go back to BLOCK.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, 11. I don't believe we were calling you right then,

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. I'm in a good attitude here to do - I have in the sextant this last P52 star, star 37. Is that all right for the optics calibration to save some gas, or do you want to go over to star 40?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Star 37 will be fine for the optics calibration. And we haven't noticed a VERB 66, yet, after our state vector uplink. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: When you move into P23, we recommend that you use the CMC-computed angles for your AUTO maneuver and see how that works out. If it doesn't bring you up with the Lm-line parallel to the horizon to the substellar point, we will see if we can get you some ground-computed angles. I guess the big thing here is to make sure that the Lm-line is parallel to substellar points so we can get a good angular measurement. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. I believe.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Marking on this star, I get a NOUN 87 twice in a row of five balls, so that's sufficient for a count.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's certainly very sufficient.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Now I want to go to P00, and I am going to take your three angles and do a verify of 49 maneuver to your substellar point. Okay?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We recommend that for the first star, if we gave you a new state vector, we'd like to try the CMC-computed angles for your AUTO maneuver.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And have you hit PROCEED on this display to enter the zero?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Not yet.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Over the past 2 hours we have seen a slight continuing increase in partial pressure of CO2. Have you in fact changed the CO2 canister yet this morning? We don't need to do it right now; we'd just like to confirm it on our instrumentation - is in good shape. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: No. We haven't changed any canisters this morning.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Then you can plan on accomplishing that after P23 is over and you've got the LEB clear.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We're in process of maneuvering to P23 in desired attitude. It likes roll 8.37, pitch 61.33, and yaw 339.87. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. And that is for star 01?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Star 01, right near the horizon. Code 110.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. On this star, the AUTO maneuver works just fine. I am right at the substellar point. Everything looks beautiful except there is no star in sight. It is just not visible.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Is this for star 01?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: That's correct.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You are not getting any reflections or anything like that that would obscure your vision, are you?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, of course, the Earth is pretty bright, and the black sky, instead of being black, has sort of a rosy glow to it. The star, unless it is a very bright one, is probably lost somewhere in that glow, but it is just not visible. I maneuvered the reticle considerably above the horizon to make sure that the star is not lost in the brightness below the horizon. However, even when I get the reticle considerably above the horizon so the star should be seen against the black background, it still is not visible.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. Stand by a minute, please.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Can you read us the shaft and trunnion angle off the counters?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. I will be glad to. Shaft 331.2 and trunnion 35.85.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's really a fantastic sight through that sextant. A minute ago, during that AUTO maneuver, the reticle swept across the Mediterranean. You could see all of North Africa, absolutely clear; all of Portugal, Spain, southern France, all of Italy, absolutely clear. Just a beautiful sight.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We all envy you the view up there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: But still no star.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead, Bruce.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: On our ground computers we confirm the shaft and trunnion angle that you have as being pointed at the star. However, it looks as though that shaft and trunnion angle is also pointing into the structure of the IM, so that while you will be getting the Earth's horizon, the star ... is obscured by the LM. We recommend an AUTO maneuver to the attitudes pen-and-inked into the flight plan. Roll 1772, pitch 2982 and yaw 330.0. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine. Let's try that.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. While you're maneuvering, could we get a LM/CM DELTA-Up reading from you? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Just a tad under 1, Bruce, 0.95.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. 0.95.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Is the Commander aboard?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: This is the Commander.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I was a little worried. This is the backup Commander still standing by. You haven't given me the word yet. Are you GO?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You've lost your chance to take this one, Jim.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. I concede.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Our maneuver is complete, and at this attitude the Lm-line is exactly 90 degrees out of phase. It is exactly pointed along the vector toward the center of the Earth instead of being parallel to the right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'm going to hold right here for your next suggestion.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. It appears to be okay now. We've changed our attitude slightly, and I have a star and I'm maneuvering to get the Lm-line parallel.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. You - Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Are you copying these NOUN 49's that have been going through?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes. We surely are. Let's see: plus 0.1 and a plus 0.2 on nautical miles and feet per second. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes, Mike. We show you in VERB 59 right now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: That's right. I - I haven't entered - I gave the - I gave it back to the computer for a second. I put the mode switch from MANUAL back to CMC while I fooled with the DSKY, and the computer drove the star off out of sight. So the delay here has been in going back to MANUAL and finding the star again, which I've finally done. And - Just a second here, I'll go to ENTER and get a 51 and mark on it. As I say, for some reason the computer drove the star off out of sight.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We show you as a little less than an hour to the midcourse correction number 2 burn. We recommend that you terminate the P23 activities here and press on with the waste-water dump, which we need from you, and get it ready for the burn. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And I have your midcourse correction number 2 PAD when you're ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. Apollo 11, ready to copy MCC 2.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Midcourse correction number 2. SPS/G&N 63059, plus 097, minus 020, GET ignition 02644 5792, plus 00118, minus 00003, plus 00177, roll 277 355 015, NOUN 44 BLOCK 1s NA, DELTA-VENT 00213 003 00168, sextant star 30 2082 370.

Part 77 The rest of the PAD is NA. GDC align: Vega and Deneb. Roll align 007 144 068. No ullage. LM weight: 33302. For your information, your heads will be pointed roughly towards the Earth on this burn. Read back. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Midcourse correction number 2. SPS/G&N: 63059, plus 097, minus 020 02644 5792, plus 00118, minus 00003, plus 00177 277 - Are you still copying?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Still copying. Go ahead. Apollo 11, this is Houston. I copied your transmission about roll 277, and go ahead from roll 277. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. 355 015, NA, 00213 003 00168 30 2082 370. Vega and Deneb 007 144 068. No ullage. LM weight: 33302. Heads towards the Earth. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Readback correct. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston. Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'd like you to terminate battery A at GET 26 hours and reinitiate battery A charge after midcourse correction 2. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Apollo 11. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. If you can give us ACCEPT, we'll send you up a state vector and a target load for the maneuver.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Give us 1 minute to check the P23 damage.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sure thing.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. The DSKY's yours.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Houston. Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We've completed the uplink. The computer's yours.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Wonder if you have a star that might be a little closer to the direction we're burning than the one you gave us.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're going to rework the attitude in the sextant star for you in order to improve the high-gain antenna coverage, and we'll have that for you in a few seconds.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Fine. We're already maneuvering ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Maybe you can make it just the change in roll.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. On your attitude for the burn: we'd like you to use roll 096, pitch 356, yaw 018. That will give you a sextant star of 01, shaft 253.8, trunnion 24.2. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We are having difficulty reading you through the noise. Could you read back again, please? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. Apollo 11. Do you copy?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Very weakly in the noise, but I think I can copy. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Roll 096 356 018 ... star 01 ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I got all of that except trunnion. It's trunnion 242. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How do you read me now on

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Loud and clear, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We'll stay on OMNI A for a while, then.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. I got all your readback except the value for trunnion. If it's 242, confirm, please.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. 242.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Could you give us a couple of high-gain antenna angles, please?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by, 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Pitch minus 35, yaw 0. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We got them.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How do you read high gain?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Read you loud and clear on high gain down here, and everything's looking good from our standpoint for your burn. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Bruce.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, burn completed. You copying our residuals?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And, Houston, looked like we saw about 37 or 88 psi on chamber pressure that time. I'd like you to look at that on the ground.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We'll take a look at that and get back in a few minutes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. On our real-time telemetry we saw 95 to 97 psi on chamber pressure. We'll - We will look at the recordings down here, though, and get back with you again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we've copied your residuals, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. No, we're not going to trim those ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Could we get your DELTA-Ve counter reading, please, from this burn?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That's minus 3.8.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Minus 2.8?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy minus 3.8.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, is there anything else you need on the burn status report?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Negative, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Did you get any usable pictures out of MILA on that first pass?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Not that we've seen. We had word on the voice loop that MILA reported that they had gotten a minute's worth of TV signal, and Goldstone reported that they had gotten about a minute's worth of modulation but that they weren't able to get anything off of it.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thanks.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We have another input here, 11, that the MILA data was recognizable as a picture, but we don't have any evaluation as to the quality of the picture. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And for our information, we've been watching a PCO2 again. Did you change a lithium hydroxide canister this morning? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. We did, and we've been seeing 1.7 percent in the spacecraft ever since.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That agrees with our data.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: 1.7 millimeters.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We're starting our maneuver to PTC attitude.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. From propellant-balancing standpoint, we recommend that you use quads Alfa and Bravo to start the PTC maneuvers. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand Alfa and Bravo.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. For CRYO-balancing purposes, we'd like you to turn the heater and oxygen tank number 1 off at this time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Everything else in the CRYO system remains the same.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We have O2 heater tank 1 off.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Houston. Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How is EECOMM today? Is he happy with all those good things?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, EECOMM is happy, and after you get TC set up, we've got a little procedure from EECOMM here to check out the O2 flow and the O2 flow sensor in your cabin enrichment. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It'll be a while, Bruce. We're just now arriving in PTC attitude, and we're going to our 20 minutes of monitoring thruster activity.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. He'll be here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Are you going to take control of the OMNI's now and switch us between B and D?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Mike, how about selecting Bravo at this time, and I'll give you a COMP configuration here, shortly.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: That PTC sure worked well last night.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Outstanding.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Roll for the COMM situation. have Is-band antenna OMNI A in Bravo, Is-band antenna OMNI to OMNI, high-gain track to MANUAL, and the pitch is minus 50 and yaw is 270.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You may have to repeat some of that, James. We've got a LM guy taking care of the high gain right now.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes, and he is eyeballing the Earth.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: He's got his head out the window.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I understand. I had trouble on 12 with him, too.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Say again what you'd like.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. The Is-band antenna OMNI A switch to Bravo which you have now, and Is-band antenna OMNI to the OMNI position, and the high-gain track to the MANUAL position, and the pitch and yaw angles are minus 50 for pitch and yaw is 270.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Minus 50 and 270.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, Jim, I'm looking through the monocular now, and to coin an expression, the view is just beautiful. It's out of this world. I can see all the islands in the Mediterranean. Some larger and smaller islands of Majorca, Sardinia, and Corsica.

A little haze over the upper Italian peninsula, some cumulus clouds out over Greece. The Sun is setting on the eastern Mediterranean now. The British Isles are definitely greener in color than the brownish green that we have in the islands, in the peninsula of Spain. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I understand that the Northern Africa - Mediterranean area is fairly clear today, huh?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Right.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. We see a bunch of roads with cars driving up and down, too.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Do you find that the monocular is any good to you, Buzz?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. It would be nicer if it had another order of magnitude of power on it. Of course, it has a tendency to jiggle around a little bit, and you might want to have some sort of a bracket. I hate to use that word though.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Got an anticyclone going in the southern hemisphere southeast of Brazil, and some - Well, the diameter of it must be over 2000 miles across.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How does the weather look up in the southern part of the western hemisphere, or up in the United States area?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, you all are just beginning to cone over the limb now. I can see parts of Central America, and it looks to be fairly clear there. The islands in the Caribbean are beginning to come in and rather a few streaming lines of clouds. Looks like there is a system up to the - well, off of Greenland that has some large cloud streamers extending back down to the southwest. The east coast of the U.S. is just coming into view now, and it doesn't look too bad that I can see right now. We may have some pretty good shots later on this afternoon. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I've got a comment about the point on the Earth where the Sun's rays reflect back up toward us. In general, the color of the oceans is mostly uniform and it's bright and darker blue except for that region that's about one-eighth of an Earth's radius in diameter; and in this circular area, the blue of the water turns a grayish color, and I'm sure that's where the Sun's rays are being reflected back on up toward us. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. We noticed the same thing. It's very similar to looking at a light shining on something like a billiard ball or a bowling ball. You get this bright spot in the blue of the water, and that turns it to sort of a grayish color.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. Is there a Navy term for that?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: A lot of gray paint.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: will, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Mike, are you satisfied with P23 now?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, I'm happy with the last updates we got, you know, in terms of what it did to our state vector. Still not altogether happy with the various procedures. If we could pick stars within the smaller range of trunnion angles so that you could allow P23 to pick its own maneuver and go to that substellar point and then have that star visible, that would seem to me to be the simplest and best way to do it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How about the --

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: ... correction on that last ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How about the horizon now? Is it pretty well defined for you and no longer hazy?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. We're far enough out now that the - I think the horizon definition variation is lost in the North.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, Jim.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Looks like the best way to get a steady view through the monocular is just steady it out and let it close when it's in front of your eye, and then you kind of float up next to it so that you're not touching it at all. It has a very slow drift, and you get a better - steadier view that way.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sounds good.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How does it feel to be airborne again, Buzz?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, I'll tell you, I've been having a ball floating around inside here, back and forth up to one place and back to another. It's like being outside, except more comfortable.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It's a lot bigger than our last vehicle.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: ... kept me busy, I'm ...

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Say again about Buzz -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. It sure is nice in here.

blocks.speaker: CC
