blocks.text: I said it's a lot bigger than the last vehicle that Buzz and I were in.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Oh, yes. It's been nice. I've been very busy so far. I'm looking forward to taking the afternoon off. I've been cooking, and sweeping, and almost sewing, and you know, the usual little housekeeping things.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It was very convenient the way they put the food preparation system right next to the NAV station.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Everything is right next to everything in this vehicle.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Not if you're in the ...

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Jim, it's been a little warm in the machine throughout yesterday and last night during the PTC. It cooled off somewhat with the windows buttoned up, and we've seen suit temperatures of about - the high 40's and cabin temperatures in the low 60's. But this seems to be still a little bit on the warm side.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I understand that it got a little warm during the day and cooled down a little bit when you put the shades up, but you're still a little bit warm. Do you have any moisture condensation or anything like that on the wall?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: No, we haven't been able to detect any moisture anyplace in the spacecraft. It seems to be fine.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: One of the hydrogen filters - the one that we've got on the hot water - seems to keep flowing when you remove one of the food bags from it. Its flow rate is quite small, right near the end of one out, and that contributes a little bit of moisture to the atmosphere.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, that hydrogen thing, it's - I'm not sure, but I think it's a backpressure problem. If the thing sees any backpressure at all, like when the bag is attached, well the flow rate will slowly decrease to where it's almost zero, and you wait, and you wait, and you wait for that last ounce. You think you have it, and you remove the bag, and then you very rapidly thereafter see maybe a glob the size of a dime or a quarter come out and just hang there. That appears to be true even though the opening into the bag is not restricted.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Understand.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: In general, I think they do quite a good job, especially on the guns, in removing a lot of the hydrogen bubbles.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: have the water temperatures been good? Are you getting hot water?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. It seems reasonably warm.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We made three cups of coffee today. The last one - you know when all the plumbing was warmed up, the hydrogen gun and everything, was warmest of the three. I don't know who had that one - Neil, did you have that one? How was your coffee? You didn't drink it till later, did you? Anyway, it's pretty good. It's not piping hot, but it sure beats stone-cold coffee.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Jim, we've been sitting here a little over 20 minutes now. How does the thruster firing activity look? Are you ready to go on with this PTC?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We're all set to go, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I'll press on then.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. PTC has started and it looks good.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Roger. This is Houston. Roger. (out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. If you're free for a couple of minutes, we have a procedure here that will let us verify the O2 flow transducer and at the same time get some more of our cabin enrichment out of the way. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston. We're ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. The primary purpose of this is, as I mentioned, to let us check out your O2 flow transducer. However, we still need about 2 hours' worth of cabin enrichment, so we'd like to keep the vent that we're going to set up going for this purpose. Okay. We want you to install the cabin vent quick disconnect which you'll find in compartment R-6, that is Romeo 6, on the urine connector on panel 251. When this is complete, verify that the waste stowage vent valve is closed, and then open or position the waste management overboard drain to the DUMP position. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Understand that. Install the cabin quick disconnect out of R-6 on the 251 urine connector and verify that the waste dump valve is closed, and say again the last part.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And then put the waste management overboard drain valve into the DUMP position. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Put the waste management overboard drain valve to the DUMP position.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Right. That's the one down on panel 251 also. And we'll watch your O2 flow on telemetry down here.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. That configuration is set up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Say again, please.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You do have the O2 flow transducer checkout setup accomplished.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Understand you have opened the drain valve at this time.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's ... It's in DUMP.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're not getting telemetry data from you right due to low signal strength. There it comes back. I expect it'll probably take us anywhere from 15 minutes to half an hour to see an increase in O2 flow due to the size of the cabin and of course of the small size of the drain. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. I've got the world in my window for a change and looking at it through the monocular, it's really something. I wish I could describe it properly. The weather is very good. South America is coming around into view. I can see on the - what appears to me to be upper horizon, a point that must be just about Seattle, Washington, and from there I can see all the way down to the southern tip of Tierra del Fuego and the southern tip of the continent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Sounds like you've got a beautiful view up there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Absolutely fantastic. I hope the pictures come out. We're rotating around where it's going out of view again.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I'm waiting to pick it up in the sextant.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sounds like one of these rotating restaurants.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Do you need some help keeping OMNI's locked on us?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Negative. We had a command computer at the Madrid site go down. We had to switch over to Ascension temporarily. We're now back remoting through Madrid, and the computer is back, and we're ready to resume control of your OMNI's and full communication. Over

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. You've got it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. One thing that we did miss in the dropout in the noise here is your LM/CM DELTA-Up reading for about 28 hours GOT. Over

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. The LM/CM DELTA-Up is 0.98.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. 0.98, and what have you been reading for O2 flow on your onboard gage? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, right now, after we put that gadget in, we've got it back to 0.35. Before that, we were reading on scale level. I think ours is relatively correct, at least when time comes for the water accumulator to kick in at 10 seconds, it goes on up to about , something like that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, 11, this is Houston. A little more information based on our analysis of your last SPS burn it looks like you got a good solid burn there. We show 94 psi chamber pressure and it looks like the SPS is definitely GO. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Good to hear it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We thought you'd feel that way about it.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're right in the middle of - well either ... or salmon salad, or something like that. That's probably why we're not answering you right away.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Well, we don't want -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: My compliments to the chef, that salad salmon is outstanding.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Understand that's the salad salmon. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Something like that, salmon salad.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: There we go, the salmon salad, very good.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Bruce, we're coming up on the water accumulator activity, and it's going on up to 0.85, oh, about 0.95 and it reached a peak there and then gradually dropped back on down to 0.6 now, 0.4, and it looks like it's pretty well - pretty well leveling off back down to 0.35. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're copying that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. On that 20 flow transducer down here on telemetry, our values are agreeing pretty well with what you read out onboard, and the EECOMM's have been noticing this cycle, but it still looks like the indicated rate is lower than what we would expect. We're still working on the problem, and we'll let you have a more complete diagnosis on it in a little while.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. It's a tight fix then.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We run a tight ship.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Is that music I hear in the background?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Buzz in singing.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Pass me the sausage, man.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We've been watching your activity on the DSKY there, and by selecting another major program with a VERB 37 ENTER and all that, we show you collapsing the deadband in PTC and having driven the CMC rate from 0.3 degrees per second down to 0 degrees per second, although of course, with all the AUTO RCS coils shut off, you're not firing any thrusters. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. What do you recommend?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, you can just continue in your present configuration in PTC. However, if you go to turn any thrusters on, the CMC would then try to bring you into an attitude hold position rather than continuing with the PTC. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. I understand.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And, Houston, we're just looking at you out our window here. Looks like there's a circulation of clouds that just moved east of Houston (ver the Gulf and Florida area. Did that have any rain in it this morning?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Our report from outside says that it's raining out here, and looks like you've got a pretty good eye for the weather there.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. Well, it looks like it ought to clear up pretty soon from our viewpoint. The western edge of the weather isn't very far west of you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. As a result of our venting through the waste management drain, we've concluded that your O2 flow rate sensor is, in fact, malfunctioning. I mentioned when you talked us through the cyclic water accumulator dump that even though it was moving, probably indicating a higher flow rate, it didn't seem to be indicating a flow rate that is high enough, and based on that and the flow that we're getting right now, we've concluded that the transducer is malfunctioning. We'd like to continue the O2 flow for about another hour, shutting it off at about 31 hours GET, to get the O2 concentration in the vehicles up to - in the vehicles up to where it will be acceptable for LM checkout. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Does it look to you like it just has a bias on it?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. It does seem to be a bias. Looks like it has a fairly high threshold before it starts indicating. EECOMM seems to think, though, that for high flow rate purposes, it will still give you a relative indication during the mission. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We understand. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. We would like you to terminate charging on battery A at CENT 30 plus 15.0 Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. 30 plus 15 for battery A charge terminate.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. If you're free for a minute, I've got some updates to the P37 PAD's that we passed up to you yesterday afternoon, I guess. As a result of doing midcourse correction number 2, the DELTA-Ve required in the TLI plus 35, 44, and 53 PAD's have changed slightly. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Standing by to copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. TLI plus 35 PAD: the DELTA-VENT should be 7992 instead of 8016. TLI plus 44 - It should be 6112 instead of 6141. And TLI plus 53 - It should be 8172 instead of 8209. Read back. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Understand. 7992, 6112, 8172. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Readback correct. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Goldstone reports they are receiving a TV picture coming down from you all, a little snowy, but a good TV picture. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We're just testing the equipment up here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Ask them if they can read the numbers.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Goldstone, this is Houston CAP COMM. Over.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Houston CAP COMM, Goldstone M&O. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by a minute, Goldstone.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. What numbers are you referring to? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Well, I guess if they can't see any numbers, why, it's kind of a lost cause.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative. Stand by. We wanted to know --

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We wanted to know what numbers before we asked them.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. I'm showing them the DSKY, and I'd like to know whether they can read what's showing on the DSKY, and also whether they can see Up-Re-To-Go, Ve-We-Re-Be, and In-To-You-In. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by a second.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Goldstone M&O, Houston CAP COMM. (over.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: CAP COMM, Goldstone. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Did you copy the spacecraft request?

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: That's affirmative. I am reading the numbers on our monitor here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, that's - Roger. That's both the numbers on the DSKY itself, and the little words like PROGRAM and VERB, NOUN, COMPUTER ACTIVITY, things of this sort?

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Roger. I can read the numbers clearly. We can't distinguish what the words are, because it is a little snowy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Okay. I read VERB, NOUN, and PROGRAM.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Do you see - Over in the lefthand corner, there's a big square one that says COMPUTER ACTION- CITY, COMP ACTIVITY?

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Roger. I see a flash occasionally in that area.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's the one.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Okay. It looks like he's moved the camera at this time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Goldstone M&O reports that they can read the numbers on the DSKY. They can also read VERB, NOUN, PROGRAM, and see the COMP ACTIVITY light flashing. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Very good. Thank you

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And they also report you appear to have panned the camera over to another location now.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes, we're going to work on something else.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Oh, Charlie. That you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's me. How are you there?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Oh, just fine. How's the old White Team today?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, the old White straight-eyed and bushytailed. We're ever alert down here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Ever alert and ... Hey, you got any medics down there watching high grade? I'm trying to do some running in place down here, and I'm wondering just out of curiosity whether it brings my heart rate up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, they will spring into action here momentarily. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, 11. We see your heart beating.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Well - look at the CDR's and the CMP's and see if they go up any. We're all running in place up here. You wouldn't believe it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I'd like to see that sight. Why don't you give us a TV picture of that one.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I think Buzz is trying. You got it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. It's coming in at Goldstone, Buzz. As Bruce said, we don't have it here in the center.
I'm afraid this isn't going to help out the PTC very much.
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: Yes. I don't know if it's a vibration or what it is, but it makes the pitch and yaw rate needles on FDAI number 1 jump up and down a little bit when we jump up and down.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Goldstoners say they see you running there, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Ask him what he's running from.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Mike, we see about a 96 heartbeat now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, that's about all that is reasonable, without getting hot and sweaty.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Goldstone should be getting about the best picture of the Earth we can give them right now, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. Thank you much.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We've got a little distortion in the horizontal direction from banding on our monitor. I wonder if they're getting the same thing?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Buzz. I'll let you know.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I guess it would be more described as a waviness.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Goldstone M&O, Houston CAP COMM.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. The crew is complaining of some horizontal banding on their monitor. Do you see that on the picture?

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: They wouldn't see anything now. We don't have anything in focus, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. He's checking on it. I'll see if they had it earlier. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I guess when we're showing the DSKY or when we're showing the Earth might be the better time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Houston CAP COMM, Goldstone.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Okay. Our TV people confirm they see this horizontal band.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The Goldstone TV people also see the banding when - at the same time you do. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Would they call it a horizontal waviness, instead of banding, maybe?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I'm not talking to them directly. Stand by, Buzz. Let me see how they describe it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Goldstone M&O, Houston CAP COMM. Could you put the TV guy on the loop, please?

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: CAP COMM, Goldstone. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: Houston CAP COMM, Goldstone M&O NET 1.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go.

blocks.speaker: CT
blocks.text: The TV people do not have access to NET 1 in that area. Suggest we use NET 2 for that purpose.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Going to NET 2.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. The Goldstone TV guys say they have some horizontal banding across the upper part of the picture and across the lower part. They would consider the lines just straight, no waviness to them at all. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand. They do seem to distort vertical lines though.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again about the vertical lines, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. When there's a vertical line, these horizontal bands tend to put small waves in it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I copy. He didn't mention that. Stand by. I'll check again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, 11. Houston. The Goldstone TV said that when you get a sharp vertical line on the picture, when the horizontal banding goes across, it does appear to bend it slightly. The same is Apollo 10, they said. Looks okay to them. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Understand. It's not our monitor. It must be the transmitter or the system.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I guess so, Buzz. We'll have them look into it, and see if they can suggest anything.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We've lost our command interface with Goldstone. We'd like you to switch to OMNI Delta. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Going to Delta.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to terminate the O2 purge if you have not done so already, and the TV camera people say that the lines are inherent in the camera, Buzz; and it's something that we expected. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand about the camera. Say again about the O2 purge.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We can terminate the O2 purge at this time. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Oh, okay. Fine. Will do.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Please select OMNI Bravo on card. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Going to Bravo, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How's everything going down there? You guys happy with the spacecraft systems?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Affirmative Everything's looking really good to us. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Same here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, how far out can you pick up TV off the OMNI?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We're just, about to the limits where we can get any kind o' picture at all on the OMNI's on the TV. It - The picture, I guess, would be just almost zero at this point.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Well, for this TV program coming up in a couple of hours, you might give some thought to how you want us to stop PTC, if you do, for the best high gain angle; and also it would be nice if you could stop us at such an attitude that we'd have the Earth out of one of our windows.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We're thinking about that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We got some PIPA biases and general drift updates for you if you give us POOR and ACCEPT. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. The --

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You've got it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you much. Our biggest drift on the GYRO's is 0.03 degrees per hour with - on the Ox-GYRO. On the PIPA's, the You-pipa the biggest and it's 0.006 feet per second so ... trying to tweak it up. The biggest we have is about one sigma on both GYRO's and accelerometers.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Sounds good.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: The system really looks good to us.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Glad to hear it, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, houston. You can go back to BLOCK. We've got the load in.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Roger. END OF TA'F

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Boy, you sure get a different perspective in this thing in zero g. Right now, Neil's got his feet on the forward hatch, and he can with his arms reach - all five windows. He can reach down into - the LEB where the overboard drain is. He can practically reach over in the cockpit.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sounds like Plastic Man to me.
I'm hiding under the left-hand couch trying to stay out of his way.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Be a good idea, Mike.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. You got a cloud over the Houston area right now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We just had a really big thunderstorm here about a hour agc. Couple of storms around the area ... Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. I see one fairly large and isolated one. There are couple of more off to the left, but this one looks fairly good size. It could very well be the one that just passed over you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, and it looks like the Cape has been having a little bit of rain, too.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. The one we had here came in from the west and is moving east - or nearly so, as far as I could tell.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That view through this sextant is fantastic. I can see Alaska right up - right up along the IM, and I'm running the crosshairs right now down the coast of California, the west coast of Mexico, Yucatan Peninsula, up around the Gulf, Florida, Cuba, down Central America, and I'm running into the stop right now, on the sextant.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It sounds like a pretty fantastic view.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The guys in the weather office at Patrick wanted a report on the tops but I guess all we can say is we're above them.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll pass it on to METRO.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Do you see any predominant weather systems as far as frontal type or any buildup of tropical-storm type? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Not any large ones. There are a couple of smaller disturbances. Well, there's one maybe 300 miles north of Cuba, but it doesn't look cyclonic.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We got a TV attitude for you and also an update to your CMC erasable load and your alternate contingency checklist, if you could break that out too. Over. .6 LMP Roger. I'm not sure I caught all of that. Go ahead with what you have.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. If you'll break out your alternate and contingency checklist for the CSM, we got an update to some of the erasable loads on page F2-20. Over.
Okay. Be getting that out, and you can give us the attitude for TV.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Your TV attitude will be roll 261, pitch 090, yaw 000. High gain angle: pitch plus 28, yaw 271. That puts the left-land window pointed at the Earth. We recommend exiting PTC with your updated procedure in the checklist. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. We copy roll 21 - 61, pitch 090, yaw 000, high gain pitch plus 28, yaw 271. And we'll like this with the DELTA-Ve that we have in the book. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, Apollo 11. I have a couple o questions on stopping the PTC. It seems to me the easiest way to stop it would be - we're essentially, of course, at 0 degrees yaw and closing up to 90 degrees pitch, so it's just a question of stopping at 260 roll, roughly, and - How about for a procedure going MANUAL ATTITUDE, three to RATE COMMAND and then, seeing as how our deadband has already collapsed, I'll turn on the panel 8 RCS thrusters, at which time it should stop at whatever attitude it finds itself in. And if I do all of that as it comes up on 261 degrees roll, we should stop right there. Is that sufficient?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sounds pretty good. Stand by one.
Sounds like it might save a little gas.
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. What page do you want in that revision? Over.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. If you'll turn to page F2-20. Over.
Okay, Tim -
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Under column A on page F2-20, line 5, line 05, the new data is 01042; line 07, the new data is 00256.  Skipping down to line 11, 00070; line 12 is 00042; line 13 is 77730.  In column Bravo, lines 3, 4, and 5, which are blank, should be all zeros for line 3; line 4 is 20017, line 5 20616.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Good readback, Buzz. And stand by, Mike, on the coming-out-to-the-PTC recommendation. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston with a recommendation on exiting PTCM.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We'd like to see you go to ACCEL COMMAND on the MANUAL ATTITUDE switches.  Then to turn on the AUTO RCS SELECT switches, and then go RATE COMMAND.  That will prevent us from firing jets uncoupled.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine. And I would guess go RATE COMMAND and roll first and then followed by pitch and yaw.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. That sounds good if - And when you get to the roll attitude desired, just go RATE COMMAND at that time and it'll stop us right on.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. I agree, Charlie. That sounds right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston with some more words on exiting PTC.  Over.
Go ahead, Charlie.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Mike, when you were playing with the P37 a while ago and we collapsed the deadband back down, the DAP assumed that the deadband was centered around the new attitude that we happened to be at, at that time. Since then, we've drifted out a couple of degrees in both pitch and yaw from that attitude such that if we did the procedure as we called it up to you of going ACCEL COMMAND, turning on all of the AUTO RCS SELECT switches and then RATE COMMAND, it would attempt to fly back to the pitch and yaw attitude that it had when the deadband collapsed. We can prevent that ly - just immediately prior to going to RATE COMMAND on the MANUAL ATTITUDE switches, if you cycle the SPACECRAFT CONTROL switch to SCS, then back to CMC. Over.
Sounds like a winner.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Okay.
I'm not going to let these LM guys play with my DSKY anymore.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: You sound like you'd better protect it. It looks like just about anything that you do with that DSKY is going to collapse that deadband back down.
Understand.
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: Charlie, we just STABED to 261 degrees roll, and it looks like whoever figured it city did a good job. It's right there, dab-smack in the middle of window number 1.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Sounds great.
Looks like Houston's still got a little smog over it, Charlie.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: We've got a constant overcast here in the room. We'll be right there. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Of course, a little cloud from up here probably covers 8 or 10 states.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Some of our guys just came in from outside and said it's pretty clear over the center here. It's cleared up completely. All the storms have moved on.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Very good.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Oh, yes, Charlie. I can see it through the sextant now, and I can see the coastline is clear. Those clouds are just inland a few miles.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Looks like the southeast part of the country is all socked in.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: California looks nice. The San Joaquin Valley shows up as a real dark spot with a lighter brown on either side of it. You can't tell that it's green. It looks just sort of dark gray or maybe even real dark blue.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How does the Mojave look? Is it clear?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. As usual.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. The - around -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It looks like there's some clouds just to the west of the Sierras, northeast of Baked'field a little bit; and crossing over into the Mojave from Bakersfield looks clear; and then as you get on further to the southeast of there, there's a few clouds.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Can you pick out Edwards in the sextant? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I can see a 104 taxiing out for takeoff on the runway.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, man. That's super.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: These dang bastards almost always have a 104 taxiing out for takeoff.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Could you pick out anything around Edwards, a dry lake or anything? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Negative, Charlie. I just - I don't have that resolution. But to give you some idea, I can - on the lower Texas coast, I can see - knowing what I'm looking for, I can see Padre Island. I can just barely make out the fact that there's a thin spit of land and then there's a little dark zone which is the Laguna Madre between it and the mainland.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. That's pretty significant. Thank you much, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Right.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: How far out are we, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. I'll give it to you exactly. Looks like around 130 000, but stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The exact range is 125 00 miles, and you're traveling 4486 feet per second.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Pretty far and pretty slow. Just past halfway.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, Charlie, what the latest on Luna 15?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, Buzz? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. What's the latest on Luna 15?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. I'll get the straight story for you.
END OF TAPE
Porch 107

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Latest on Luna 15 - TASS reported this morning that the spacecraft was placed in orbit close to the lunar surface, and everything seems to be functioning normally on the vehicle. Sir Bernard Lovell said the craft appears to be in an orbit of about 62 nautical miles.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And also, President Nixon has reported - or declared a day of participation on Monday for all federal employees to enable everybody to follow your activities on the surface.  Many state and city governments and businesses throughout the country are also giving their employees the day off, so it looks like you're going to have a pretty large audience for the EVA.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Oh, that's very nice, Charlie. I'll tell Neil about it.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We've stopped PTC. We're in the right position; we're setting up for TV.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We have you stopped in the PTC; attitude looks good to us.  Mike, I would like to get a COMM check.  The last couple of the transmissions from the spacecraft has been garbled from especially Buzz.  Could you both give me a COMM check?  Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger, Charlie. Buzz here. How do you read? , , 2, 1.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. You are about four-boy with a slight decrease/increase in volume, sort of a wavy volume to it.  Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I moved my mike around. How about now? Is this any better?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, that's beautiful right there. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. , , 2, 1. How do you read me?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. You're five-boy. Is Neil on? , , 2, 1.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. You're five-boy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We got the network all configured for the TV. You can start any time you want. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. We have a picture. We see the Earth right in the center of the screen. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. Apollo 11 calling in from about 130 000 miles out. And we'll zoom our camera in slowly and get the most magnification we can. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The definition is pretty good on our monitor here. The color is not too ..., at least on this set. Could you describe what you're looking at? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. You're seeing Earth, as we see it, out our left-hand window, just a little more than a half Earth. We're looking at the eastern Pacific Ocean, and the north half of the top half of the screen, we can see North America, Alaska, United States, Canada, Mexico, and Central America. South America become invisible just (ff beyond the terminator or inside the shadow. We can see the oceans with a definite blue cast, see white bands of major cloud formations across the Earth, and can see coastlines, pick out the western U.S., San Joaquin Valley, the Sierra mountain range, the peninsula of Baja California, and we can see some cloud formations over southeastern U.S. There's one definite mild storm south'st of Alaska, looks like about 500 to 1000 miles, and another very minor storm showing the south end of the screen near the - or a long ways off of the equator, probably 45 degrees or more south latitude. Can pick out the browns in the landforms pretty well. Greens do not show up very well. Some greens showing along the northeastern - northwestern coast of the United States and northwestern coast of Canada.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. It's a pretty good picture on clarity here. We're having - can you tell us - It appears to us that there are two distinct cloud. formations
trending east/west, one approximately about along the equator, and one around 30 or so south latitude. Could you tell us exactly where those cross the landmasses? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. They cross just south of the lower part of Mexico, probably through Central America. That is the equatorial band which we assume to be the intertropical convergence zone. The other band, which stands about 30 south, correctly appears to join the equator at the far left, or just beyond the horizon on the left edge of Earth, or at least it looks like it's going to join it We don't have an explanation for that banding.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. Thank you. It also appears that just to the left of the terminator, up in the northern hemisphere, there's a cloud...and trending - a gap in the cloud, trending northwest/ southeast. It appears to us that that comes in about over the northern United States, or perhaps the central United States. Is that about correct? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I can see on the monitor the thing you were talking about, but right now I can't get my eye to the window to pick out just where it crosses the shoreline.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You guys are doing a good job. It's a real steady picture, here. We're - Clarity is excellent. The color, it's - the clouds are - The whites are distinct. The rest of it looks like, to me anyway on the monitor I'm observing, is a fairly greenish blue is the way I'd describe it. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It appears that the --

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Well, we can't observe much green from the spacecraft.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. On this monitor, the landmasses appear to be just a darker grayish color rather than a brown.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Well, it's true that we do not have the depths of color at this range that we enjoyed at 50 000 miles out. However, the oceans still are a definite blue and the continents are generally brownish in cast,
although it is true that they're tending more toward gray now than they were at the closer range.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We've been - I've just been vectored to another monitor and sure enough, the browns are coming in a lot more distinctly on the Eidephor that we have up on our screen in the control center. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, world, hold on to your hat. I'm going to turn you upside-down.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, that's a pretty good roll, there.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Oh, I'd say sloppy, Charlie. Let me try that one again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You'll never beat out the thunderbird.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. That practice did you some good. It's looking - real smooth roll, there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oops! Spoke too soon.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I'm making myself seasick doing it, Charlie. I'll just put you back rightside-cup where you belong.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You don't get to do that every day.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Could you describe, from your view, the polar cloudcap? It appears to us to extend down the western coast of North America. Would you estimate how far it extends down? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Trying to fit everybody into the window.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It appears that the cloudcap comes down a little bit below the southern extremity of Alaska.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We've - 11, we've lost our picture here, now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Apollo 11, Houston. We've got the picture back now.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Unfortunately, we only have one window that has a view of the Earth and it's filled up with the TV camera, so your view now is probably better than ours is.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. If you could comply, we'd like to see a little smiling faces up there, if you could give us some interior views. I'm sure everybody would like to see you. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We'll reconfigure the TV for that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. It appears to us that we're seeing a view from outside plus a little of the inside. It appears you've taken the camera away from the left window now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's correct. We're moving it back and second-figuring for interior lighting.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We can still see the Earth through the left window, and it appears that we can see a floodlight off to the left, either that or some Sun shafting through the hatch window.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It's a floodlight.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Now we're coming in. Can't quite make out who that ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's big Mike Collins, there --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You got a little bit of - Yes, hello there sports fans. me, plus Neil is in the center couch, and Buzz is doing the camera work at this time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It's a little dark now, 11. Maybe a bigger of-stop might help.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, that's in work.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It's getting a lot better now, 11. Mike, you're coming in five-boy. I got a good -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I would have put on a coat and tie if I'd known about this ahead of time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Is Buzz holding your cue cards for you. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Cue cards have a no. We have no intertions of competing with the professionals, believe me. We are very comfortable up here, though. We do have a happy some. There's plenty of room for the three of us and I think we're all learning to find our favorite little corner to sit in. Zero g is very comfortable, but after a while you get to the point where you sort of get tired of rattling around and banging off the ceiling and the floor and the side, so you tend to find a little corner somewhere and put your knees up or something like that to wedge yourself in, and that seems more at home.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Looks like Neil is coming in five-boy there, 11. Mike, see you in the background. The definition is really outstanding. The colors are good. It's a real good picture we're getting here of Commander Armstrong. We - Buzz, when you take the camera over towards the window where the Sun's shafting through, it tends to blank it out, though.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, Neil's standing on his head again.. He's trying to make me nervous.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: He's disappearing up into the tunnel, of course, as he would going into the lunar module, only backwards.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We can see portions of the LEB now.. The systems test meter panel, in the lower part of the picture, or we did have it, anyway.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. And then directly behind his head are our optical instruments, the sextant and the telescope that we use to take sightings with.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. And we see the DSKY flashing with a 651. In fact, we can read registers 1 and 2 quite clearly.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We have the old high gain angles telling us which way the Earth is.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy. That's a beautiful picture. Clarity is outstanding.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We can also give you the time of day in our system of mission elapsed time. Elapsed time: 34 hours 16 minutes and umpteen seconds. Can you see that clearly enough, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Apollo 11. We can see it counting up every - every second. We got 34 17 02 now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Back to the high-gain angles.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Now we have amputated those.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We have a beautiful rainbow there now as you move the camera around. ... That looks like the star charts coming into view, now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Those are Buzz's two star charts that he is using right now as sun shades over the right-hand window, window number 5.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We see the sun shining in through it behind him and plotting out the equatorial - correction, ecliptic plane, and the stars that you're using for the navigation.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. He doesn't really need the charts. He's got them memorized. They're just for show.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: While we're pointing up in this direction, we see out our side windows the Sun going by and, of course, out one of our windows right row we've got the Earth. Now right behind my window, of course, we have the Sun, because the Sun is illuminating the star charts that we see. This line represents the ecliptic plane and these lines, vertical lines, represent our reference system that the spacecraft is using at this time. As we approach the Moon, the Moon will gradually grow larger and larger in size and eventually it will
be in - it will be eclipsing the Sun as we go behind it, as we approach the lunar orbit insertion maneuver.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We've - Could you attempt a little bit better focus there, 11? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That's a lot better on the star chart now. We can make out the ecliptic plane and the planets and the Sun and the Moon as they have gone at various places throughout the ecliptic plane. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: If we can get some of the wires untangled here, we'll give you a demonstration of how easy pushups are up here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Roger. Good view of Buzz, there.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: When it gets pretty hard doing it that way, we just roll over and do it the other way.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. We couldn't figure out whether that was a chinup or a pushup. Just take your choice, I guess.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, it looks like it's probably almost your dinner time down there, Earth. We'll show you our food cabinet here in a second.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We see a box full of goodies there. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We really have them, Charlie. We've got all kinds of good stuff. We've got coffee up here in the upper left and various breakfast items, bacon in little small bites, beverages like fruit drink, and over in the center part we have, all kinds of things. Let me pull one out here and see what it is.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Would you believe you're looking at chicken stew, here? All you have to do is - 3 ounces of hot water for 5 or 10 minutes. Now we get our hot water out of a little spigot up here with a

filter on it that filters any gases that may be in the drinking water out, and we just stick the end of this little tube in the end of the spigot and pull the trigger three times for 3 ounces of hot water and then mush it up and slice the end off it and there you go, beautiful chicken stew.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sounds delicious.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. The food so far has been very good. We couldn't be happier with it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Could I borrow that flashlight a second?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: The surgeons are saying thank you, there, for that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And it is sort of down in a dark corner, so we have a flashlight here to help us see things; and if I can let go of it carefully, it'll just hold itself right where it is.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: As long as it's ..., it will.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. That's a pretty good demonstration. You started off really stable there, Mike. It's -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, the problem is, no matter how carefully you let go, you bump it just a tiny little bit and set it in motion, and once in motion there she goes. Try that again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It looks fairly stable now with slow rotation.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, so much for the food department. I'm going to close up the store down here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Charlie, we checked out the cable lengths, and we're thinking we might want to see if we can take the TV into the LM with us tomorrow for part of the time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Good show. We'd like to see it if it'll reach that far. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We'll give it a try.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And where we sleep is down underneath this couch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Houston. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Slowly sinking into the sack there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's really comfortable.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Forgot to give Buzz his flashlight back.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Could you give the folks a view of your patch on your CWG's? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Stand by one, Charlie, we'll try and give you

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We have the patch. Could you attempt to improve the focus slightly? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The scan on the camera makes the - that's a little bit better now. The flashlight seems to flicker, due to the scan on the TV. We can't see the eagle. Now it's a little bit better. Over. Could you open the of-stop a little bit more? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's open all the way. We're going to have to move Buzz around a little bit.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. The color is better now. It's coming in. We could attempt a little bit better focus on it. There we go; it focuses a lot better now. We see the eagle coming right in on the lunar surface. Over. That's very good now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. That's very good now. We can see the Earth in the background, Apollo 11, and the eagle coming in.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's probably pretty hard to see the olive branch, isn't it?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It is.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, that's what he has in his talons, is an olive branch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We're really impressed with the clarity and the detail that we have in the picture. the DAP - the vehicle will roll - will maneuver, rather, at a rate that is loaded in, which was three-tenths plus four-tenths rate, and it will limit at four-tenths above the desired rate, so - that is if we have a large enough angle between the desired and the actual, which we did. blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We're getting a lot of background noise now, also. If you will stand by a minute or so until we roll a little further in PTC, I think things will get better.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. It's coming around to the number 1 window. We'll get you ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, we're hearing you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. The noise on the COMM seems to have quieted down now. I guess that we've rotated a new antenna into view and probably also the Earth out of view in your window. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. It looks as though the length of the shadow of that cloud is about the same as the width of the Persian Gulf.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We copy the width of the Persian Gulf, and I guess that all I can give you firsthand is a single isolated data point, and that is that it was clear here in Houston this morning. That's a pretty localized observation. As a result of your waste-water dump, it looks like the PTC mode has been disturbed somewhat. We're showing you about 20 degrees out in pitch right now and about 6 degrees in yaw, which is significantly greater, about twice as much - a little more than twice as much as the deviation you had prior to the waste-water dump. We're watching it down here, though, and we'll let you know if we think any corrective action is required. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Maybe we ought to - next time split that in half, and put half of it on one side and half on the other or something like that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes. We could do that. We were actually pretty interested in seeing what the effect on PTC would be of the waste-water dump. We don't recall ever having performed waste-water dump during PTC on previous missions. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, now we know.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. I am looking at that cloud now around Pakistan through the sextant, and it appears to be one single cell in the latter stages of development. There is a smaller, more isolated one -
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. We lost you down in the noise on the COMM link here about the time you were describing the single-cell cloud formation over Afghanistan-Pakistan area through the sextant. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. It came through a lot clearer through the sextant than with the monocular, and you could definitely tell it was one single cell in the latter stages of development. It must have gone up to over 50 000 feet, though. The eastern Mediterranean is phenomenally clear. You can see all the lakes, the Dead Sea stood out quite well. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. What appears to be the limit of resolution through that sextant from your current position? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, I can't see it right now. It's outside the field of view.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And, I don't know how you'd really describe the limit of resolution. I will think about that a little.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. I guess the smallest object that you could pick out looking through it would give us a pretty good hack.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, you can see the Nile River going almost up to its source. The lake is obscured by clouds, but you can trace it all the way on up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I guess that is down though, isn't it?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We have been working under the assumption that it would take about an hour for the interference from waste-water dump to dissipate to the point where you could reasonably take star sightings for platform alignment navigation or something of this sort. If you have a spare minute or two, could you comment on the observation condition, now? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Stand by one, Bruce.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: My guess would be the telescope's probably pretty useless, but you can differentiate in the sextant between water droplets and stars by the difference in their motions.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, Mike. I guess that we've still got - what you are saying is that we've still got a lot of water droplets visible, but you can pick them out and distinguish them in the sextant, then.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Right. I think so. Buzz is looking through it now. Just a second.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.
Houston, Apollo 11. It looks like at this time the sextant would be quite usable for any alignment. There's actually very few ... verticals.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. How about the telescope? Is it useful now?

Well, it's not quite as useful; it never seems to be. Depending on the position of the Sun, it's got that band that seems to go across the center. I don't think it's because of the wastewater particles that it would lack its effectiveness. Over.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. What - Is this band something that's deposited on the outside of the optics? Over.
No. I see the reflection from the Sun.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The Sun bounces off the IM structure. With the IM attached, that telescope is just about useless. Those star charts that MPAD provided us, I think, would be most useful if we had to use the - if for some reason we had to mark through the telescope. We could use those as a guide for what we're looking at and say, "Well, that bright blob over there has got to be that star because that's the position we're in." But so far, we've not been able to pick out any decent star patterns while docked with the IM using the telescope.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. We copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.text: Go ahead, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: -- How do your read? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're reading you loud and clear.

Roger. You're coming back a little scratchy. It looks like our O2 flow transducer's gotten a good bit worse. I just looked at it at the last water accumulator cycling, and it just barely registered - barely crept up above 0.2. Over.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. At the time of your cyclic accumulator stroking, we were on low-bit-rate data, and consequently not receiving the O2 flow parameter. We expect that what you're seeing is probably nominal. That is, it's probably what we would expect from a transducer that's malfunctioning probably in this fashion, and it's just going to keep on getting worse like that. Nothing to worry about. We'll monitor things on the ground here. Over.
Okay. It does look like it's gradually degrading to about zilch.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.text: Apollo 11 CDR, this is Houston. Radio check. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're reading you the same. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC

Okay. You've got it.

CC

11, this is Houston. We're through with the cup-link. You can go back to BLOCK.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Would you like to have both oxygen and hydrogen purge on? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Say again. Both what on? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: On the fuel cell purge: would you like to see both oxygen and hydrogen? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Affirmative. We request hydrogen and an oxygen fuel cell purge. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Any preference which first?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative. As long as you've got the H2 purge line heaters on.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I'll go get - Go ahead with the hydrogen then.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. You copy my NOUN 93?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative. We've got it.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I am going to go ahead and thrust then. Triangle difference is 0.01, but it's sort of difficult at three-tenths rate. I'm required to use medium speed unresolved, and it's difficult to hold the star centered long enough to get a decent mark on it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. It looks okay to us.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I've got the morning news here if you're interested. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, we sure are. We're ready to copy and comment. Isn't that 2:30 there?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Go.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Here we go. The interest in the Flight of Apollo 11 continues at a high level but a competing interest in the Houston area is the easing of watering rules. Mayor Louie Welch promises a lifting of lawn-watering restrictions if the rains continue. Friday is partly cloudy, and there is a 30-percent chance of thunderstorms in the afternoon. In Washington, D.C., the Senate Finance Committee approved extension of the income tax surtax, but a Senate vote on the bill --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You cut out, Houston. You cut out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Where do you hold me cutting out? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. How do you read now? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Loud and clear, Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: : CC Roger. In Washington, the Senate Finance Committee has approved extension of the income tax surtax, but a Senate vote on the bill currently seemed remote. In Austin, State Representative Ray Lemmon of Houston has been nominated as the National Director of the American Society for Oceanography. Lemmon has proposed a study of the possibility of establishing an institute of oceanography in Texas. This would be the first such institute on the western Gulf of Mexico.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. In Washington, the Senate Finance Committee has approved extension of the income tax surtax, but a Senate vote on the bill currently seemed remote. In Austin, State Representative Ray Lemmon of Houston has been nominated as the National Director of the American Society for Oceanography. Lemmon has proposed a study of the possibility of establishing an institute of oceanography in Texas. This would be the first such institute on the western Gulf of Mexico.

In Minneapolis, Minnesota, the weather bureau, after recapping today's weather showing a high of 88 and a low of 72, has noted "snowfall none." From St. Petersburg, Florida, comes a radio report from the Norwegian explorer, Thor Heyerdahl, which said that the crew of his papyrus boat, the Ra, will sail into Bridgetown, Barbados, despite damage from heavy seas. The crew, however, will sleep on an escort vessel. Norman Baker, navigator of the expedition, said the crew was aboard the Ra today repairing damage from storms this past week, which split the footing of the mast. Part of the broken mast was jet-tone overboard, and the vessel was 725 miles east of the Barbados. "It is possible but uncomfortable to sleep aboard the Ra," Baker said in the radio report. "But the purpose of our voyage is not a test of strength or human endurance." That is the reason why the crew was spending nights aboard the escort vessel Shenandoah, which rendezvoused with the Ra on Tuesday.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: In sports, the Houston Oilers are showing plenty of enthusiasm in their early preseason workouts at Kerrville, and Coach Wally Lemm says he is impressed with the fine group of rookies. National League baseball yesterday, Thursday: St. Louis 11, Philadelphia 3; Montreal 5, over Pittsburgh 4, Atlanta 12, Cincinnati 2; San Francisco 14, and Los Angeles 13. American League we have Baltimore 3, over Cleveland 2, Detroit 4 to Washington's 3, Minnesota 8 to Chicago 5. Boston at New York was rained out. And in Corby, England, an Irishman, John Over has won the world's porridge eating championship by consuming 23 bowls of instant oatmeal in a 10-minute time limit from a field of 35 other competitors. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. I assume Houston didn't play yesterday.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's correct.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'd like to enter Aldrin in the oatmeal eating contest next time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Is he pretty good at that?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: He's doing his share up here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Let's see. You all just finished a meal not long ago, too, didn't you?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I'm still eating.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Does that - that - -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: . He's on his - He's on his 19th bowl. . CC Roger. Are you having any difficulties with gas in the food bags like the 10 crew reported?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Are you having any difficulties with gas in the food bags like the 10 crew reported.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, that's intermittently affirmative, Bruce. We have these two hydrogen filters, which work fine as long as you don't hook them up to a food bag. But the entry way into the food bag has enough back pressure to cause the - the filters to start losing their efficiency. A couple of times, I've been tempted to go through that dryout procedure, but we found that simply by leaving the filters alone for a couple of hours, their efficiency seems to be restored.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Their efficiency ranges anywhere from darn near perfect to terrible just depending on the individual characteristics of the food bags we're putting through them. Some of the food bags are so crimped near the entry-way that there's no way we can work them loose to prevent back pressure.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Hello, Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. As you've probably noticed, your coning angle in PTC mode is increased substantially as a result of the waste water dump, the fuel cell purge, and a natural coupling, so it looks like we are going to have to terminate PTC here in a little while. And we'd like to get your feeling as to whether you're still anticipating trying to send back TV signals from inside the LM, and if so, we'll try to provide an attitude that you can hold that'll give us high gain antenna lock on the Earth during the TV and LM activation period. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes, we're still planning that activity if the cord lengths work out all right, and we'll accept those attitudes that you work up for us.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Roger. Out.

AA AA 35 3H When you work up an attitude to get high gain, is there any way that we could get partial Sun in one of the two LM front windows? AA AA 36 1G This is Houston. We'll have a look at it. AA AA 39 1H AA AA 30 AA Go ahead, Houston. AA AA 39 AT Roger. We have a TV attitude for you if you're ready to copy. AA AA 30 32 Go ahead. Ready to copy. AA AA 19 35 Okay. We recommend stopping PTC at GET of

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: When you work up an attitude to get high gain, is there any way that we could get partial sun in one of the two LM front windows?
This is Houston. We'll have a look at it.
blocks.speaker: SC
CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We have a TV attitude for you if you're ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We recommend stopping PTC at GET of 54 45 00, and this should put you at just about the right roll angle. The attitude we recommend is roll 263, pitch 090, yaw 000. This gives you the Earth out of window number 1 in the command module and places the high gain antenna in the CSM window for TV at your convenience. You will also have the Sun shining in - or shining at the hatch on the LM, and if you take down the window shades you should get some sunlight in. We're recommending wide deadband. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you, Houston. We'll look at that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. When we pass the proper roll angle, we're not going to be anywhere near zero degrees yaw. Do you want us to just stop and try until we find ourselves in and then VERB 49 the three angles you gave us?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like you to stop at the proper roll angle, then do a VERB 49 to the roll and pitch. Over. Correction, roll and yaw.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Do you read? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: Roger, 11. Do you read me? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Stand by, Charlie. Yes, we're going to come out of PTC here at 263 roll and then do a OVER HO to the recommended attitude.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That sounds fine to us. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Before you open the pressure equalization valve, we'd like the LM/CM DELTA-Up. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Let me check it again. It was about 155.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I read it 158 right now, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you much.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We're stopping PTC at

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. You're about one-boy on this transmission. Say again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Do you read?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How do you read on the high

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, how do you read me? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Read you loud and clear, Charlie. We just switched to HIGH GAIN, and we stopped PTC at roll 263, pitch 90, yaw 0. How do you read?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. You're five-boy now on the high gain. We're right between the OMNI antennas and pretty horrible COMM on the OMNI's. We got you five-boy on the high gain, and we copy the PTC stoppage. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, fine.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Alright. Can you hear our master alarm in the background? That's O2 FLOW HIGH coming through this amplifier.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: That photoelectric cell is a good device. It's worked very well.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Say again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I say that photoelectric cell amplifier for the master alarm is a good device. It's working very well, and it's a nice pleasing tone.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Makes you almost glad to get master alarms.

blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. As a matter of curiosity, our O2 flow meter is pegged FULL-SCALE HIGH.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We copy that here. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.text: Boy, that transducer's working somewhat.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.text: 11, Houston. We'd like to try to attempt to correlate your O2 flow in transducer with the flow valve that you've got open. How far - How far open would you say you have the REPRESS O2? Over. Correction, the DIRECT O2.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Stand by, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. It's not open very far. It's hard to give you a good reading without shunting it again, but the arrow is at about the one o'clock position. Now I reduce the flow, and I'll let it stabilize here. Right now our onboard reading is about 0.4, and that's with the arrow in the O2 valve at the two o'clock position. Would you rather have comparisons of O2 flow readings or would you rather have valve position comparisons:

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: EECOMM's say they'd like to look at valve positions. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Well, we're holding steady now at 0.3 pound per hour, and our cabin pressure is about 54; and I'll close the valve momentarily and then open it again to this position and tell you how much travel is required.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's about 30 degrees of travel, Charlie, from the closed position, which is with the arrow pointing at about three to three-thirty, four o'clock.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Our flow is stabilized now at 0.6.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. We're reading the same.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, open it back to the one o'clock position.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Is that enough different positions, or you want more, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Mike, that's good - good enough. We're satisfied now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. We figured you would.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, Okay. You're right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
