blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Drogue removal's coming next.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. As we suspected.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Now it's a good view of the storage area under the couch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Looks like you're pretty crowded in there with that drogue. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Oh, it's not really bad.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: This TV cable is getting in the way.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We see lots of arms.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The only problem, Charlie, is these TV stagehands don't know where they stand.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, you got to really have a union card, there. We can't really complain too much, I guess.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Do you have a little white dot in the bottom of your monitor - TV monitor? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. We do.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I guess part of the camera's been burnt out down there. These are really beautiful pictures now, Buzz. Over. Real clear.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We might have got just a little bit of Sun in there. Is it just one small white dot?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We went up in the tunnel checking the roll angle, Charlie, and it's 2.05 degrees.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. 2.05 on the roll CAL.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And that's a plus.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Plus.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The tunnel looks pretty clear to us. Somebody going up there now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It's Mike checking his connectors up there now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The lighting up in there looks very good to us at this time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I think that's mostly the camera. It - it's subdued to say the least.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It's pretty - It's gathering pretty well to us. We see everything quite clearly up in there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, the docking latches look good today just like they did yesterday. Everything up in there looks just fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That sounds fine to us. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We can even read the decals up there on the LM hatch.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, let me zoom it up and see how much you can read.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We can see the LM umbilical connection quite well there, Buzz. We see you zooming in on one of the decals now. It's, "To reset, unlatch handle, latch behind grip and pull back two full strokes." That's about all we can make out.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, you get an At-plus.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thank you very much, sir. At least I passed my eye test.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I'm standing 6 feet from it, Charlie, and you can read it better than I can. There's something wrong with the system.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's a real good view of the LM hatch handle there, 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Looks like we'll be ready to go into the LM early if that's okay with you all down there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It's fine with us, Neil. Go ahead anytime you wish. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. The white spot you see on your monitor, our TV people say it is a burn spot, but they expect it to dissipate after a couple of hours. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, the dump valve is actuated.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy, 11. We see that very clearly. Is that you, Buzz, with your hand on it?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We're really amazed at the quality of the picture up in the tunnel. It's really superb. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It is, considering the amount of light up in there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. We're about to open our hatch now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. There's that same guy that, when you open up the door, why, he's waiting there for you, and he turns the lights on

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: How about that. Just like the refrigerator.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Buzz, the view in through your - by your right - left shoulder there is so good we can see the ascent engine cover, the Velcro on it, and that's about all we can make out right now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Now we can see the helmet stowage bag --

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We don't see anything loose up there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, great. Looks good to us. We see the helmet storage bag.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, 11. Houston. We got a view of the PLSS there, off the right of our screen.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Buzz, you already in? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. I'm halfway in, hanging out. Start turning around, I guess.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like you to read out the LCG reservoir sight level. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, we have a good view of the window there. It looks like the Sun's finally coming through the shade.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, I'm afraid it's - We're just about plus Z toward the Sun.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative. This attitude put both windows right toward the Sun - or the IM. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, that may be good in some respects, but -

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We had a view, Buzz, of the utility light cord. ...

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Now let me show you a view looking the other way.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And we see right now the utility light or either the floodlight up there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I think now I see the utility light still in the stowage bag. Hey, that's a great shot right there. We see you in there. Guess that's Neil and Mike. Better be, anyway.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We see you waving.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That's really a beautiful shot

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We didn't quite decipher that signal that just came from the CMP

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Just saying hello. On the TIG sight gage, you got about - oh, it looks like the white mark that's in the plunger is about a quarter to three-eighths inch out into the green away from the red. Is that what you'd like to see? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. Roger, Buzz. That looks good to us. Thank you much.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It is the white index, is it not, that you're interested in comparing whether it's in the red or green?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. That's affirmative, Buzz. It looks good. That's a good reading for us. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We had a shot moment - a moment ago of the suit disconnect valve.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I'll open up the windows and see what the lighting condition's going to be like.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That's a real good view we have of the AOT. You're back now, Buzz, and notice you're taking down one of the window shades. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: The light is super!.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: How's the Sun coming in? How's the Sun coming in from this direction going to affect what you can see?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It made it really super. The lighting is excellent in the - in the LM right now. We can make out the AOT, the ISA, and the left-hand window - there's a little glare off of that, but the LMP side the - with the shade down it's really excellent. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, let's - I'm turned around, why I took the shade off my side first.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. The light level for the TV is really excellent. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes, the lighting in the LM is very nice now, just like completely daylight; and everything is visible. A good bit lighter than the tunnel was earlier.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We got a good view now, Neil, of the DEDA, and also Buzz's ACA.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Hey, I'm pointing it at the front hatch now. Everything seems to be in place down there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, we got the dump valves in view. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We see you removing the ISA now, folding it up, putting it up on the AOT. The instrument panels are coming into view behind.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, I think it'd probably be best, since we've done SPS burn, to put it back over the instrument panel instead of putting it up over the PLSS on the recharge station. Would you care to comment on that one? We could do either just as easily.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. We'll have an answer for you momentarily.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That's really a super shot of the main display.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The vehicle is surprisingly free of any debris floating around. It's very clean.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. It's pretty hard to describe this view. It's really - really great.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Now you know how we 'feel.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Neil's OPS is about 57, 5800.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And mine's about 5800, also.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That's a good shot of Neil's PLSS, there. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No, that's mine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That moment - a moment ago, we had a good shot of your PLSS, Buzz, and the two helmet stowage bags. Down behind your left shoulder, Buzz, we have the - the DS KY and the ACA.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're going to go ahead and take all the Moon data on back into the command module, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Buzz, it appears that you're intending to put on the Sun filter and view the Sun through the AOT. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, unfortunately it looks like it's down a little bit more towards ... than I can be able to see in the AOT.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We got a beautiful view of the side of the command module out of the AOT looking in the left rear detent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I can see the hatch and all the - all the EVA handrails. First time we've seen the silvery outside of the command module.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I can read the letter, on the hat cover. It's a boost cover release, and the big yellow arrow that points toward the opening - place where the tool B goes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Great shot now back down into the -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And left on the --

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, Buzz. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Say again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I was just saying we got a great shot looking back into the command module.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. And the left detent, I can see the A0 - or the rendezvous radar, and I move to the forward detent and that's about all I've got. I'm looking eyeball to eyeball.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Charlie, is there any concern about the duration that we ought to have the window shades open?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We don't have - We don't have any circulation in here, and it might get a little on the warm side.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We'll - We'll put up a couple of hoses in the command module here and get a little circulation going.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sounds like a good idea. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. As far as the window shades go in this IM, there's nothing except for crew comfort. I don't think we've got any systems problem. Be sure to put them back up when you egress. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That we will do.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Charlie, I'll give you a view out of the overhead window, back looking at the command module right-hand rendezvous window.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, we see it now. Thanks a lot, Buzz. That's a good view through the overhead.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: One washer on -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: One washer's on by the overhead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: There we go. We got it now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: There wasn't very much debris in the command module or the LM. We found very few loose particles of bolts, nuts, and screws and lint and things. Very few in each spacecraft. They were very clean.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Sounds good.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We have a good view out of the rendezvous - correction, the overhead window of the LM. We don't see anybody staring back at us, though. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Charlie, can you see Mike's two eyeballs staring out through the rendezvous window?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Stand by. We haven't picked him up yet.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: You are looking through a lot of layers of glass.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We had a --

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: ... on my monitor.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We had a slight glimpse of Mike in the rendezvous window at that time. It's pretty murky looking into there, though.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Here he is, I've got him. I've got him on the monitor now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We see him staring back at us now. Hello, in there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Our recommendation for the ISA is to stow it back over the instrument panel. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Will do.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We can make out the markings on the panel. We read SYSTEM A ASCENT FUEL, ASCENT OXIDIZER. Quad 1, quad 4. The - It's really unbelievable, the definition we're getting down here off that little camera. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We can even see the barber pole or the talkbacks.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We can read the markings on the instruments for the glycol pressure, quantity, CC. You can even read the scale on the eight ball. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We see the cross-feed barber pole, and we have the Velcro patches back up to the RCS systems now. We can see the markings on the meters, green and red bands, in limits.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We see you raised the cover on the abort stage. We don't recommend that.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. We're going to tape that one over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're going to tape that one over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We concur.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The restraints in here do a pretty good job of pulling my pants down.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We haven't quite got that before the 50 000 000 TV audience, yet.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That's a good view of the eight ball. We see - You can even read the OFF flag, there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You can see the signal strength meter for the radar, read the numbers on it.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, did you want us to test the cameras in the LM and - I was wondering about that. I saw it in the flight plan, but I'm just wondering if you want to do that on CSM power, or do you want us to take both of the 16mm cameras back in the CSM and test them there? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: As an alternative to that, why, we could wait LOI day and do it then when we transfer over to LM power.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by. We'll have an answer.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. On that TV, our commentary - The monitor I was looking at was delayed about 12 seconds, 12 to 15 seconds while it went through our color converter. It was probably - You thought I was crazy, but we were looking at it 15 seconds after you broadcast it. 11, Houston -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We understood that, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. On the LM cameras, we'd like you to do it on LOI day with the LM power. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. That's what we'll do.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, we're showing you something that came out of the Commander's checklist stowage packet. It's got a 16-millimeter camera in it, and it's got this little cylinder, and I guess - I don't understand what it is. Maybe you can tell us.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by. We can't figure it out either.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It's got an arrow on the back, and it says "turn," but I'm afraid to turn it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, your friendly geologist says it's the camera cank - crank, excuse me, for the 16-sequence camera if it jams. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: All very well. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: There's that word again. The ancillary stowage container.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: The shades couldn't quite hack it, there, Buzz. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, 11. Are you still getting high bit rate off the OMNI's at this distance?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. About 50 percent of the time, we're getting high bit rate off the OMNI's when you're in PTC. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You're welcome.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Neil, at this attitude you look like you're about 12 feet long.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It seems like I always find myself upside-down in whatever I'm doing around here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Could you give us a few comments on your crew comfort with the CSM hoses moving the air around? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, it's picking up a little bit on circulation in here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: What do you estimate the temperature is, Buzz? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Oh, I'd say maybe 73, 75.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It's hard to tell at this density and pressure of gas, but comfort level is about the - about the same as the command module.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You probably -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It was a little warmer or stuffier when we first got in, but it seems to be improving.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Houston copies. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: You may be able to see some -

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: - - some particles jumping around on your screen. That's just dust particles that are being illuminated by Sun shafting in the window.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. They're very clear now. Over. And that's a good view of Neil's - correction, of Buzz's circuit breaker panel, there.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I can just barely see the handrail on the front porch from the position on the right-hand window.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Our view of the Panel 11 is - gets brighter, then darker. Are you changing the of-stop at all? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No, what's happening is, we get pretty close to the window now and then, and it drives the automatic light control into the stop, I think.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I think that's right.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, I had the switch on OUTSIDE while I was going through the overhead window. That may be what's contributing to some of it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We seem to be picking up a few more dust particles now. We see them quite clearly in the screen now. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, I'm choking on one every so often.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Your show is going out to the U.S. now. We're about to get the satellite up. It'll be transmitted to some other countries after that. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. I'm checking out this window bracket where I'll be putting it for the EVA pictures of Neil going down the ladder.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We keep marveling about the color and the clarity of the picture. It's really difficult to describe. It's - It's just perfect. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, 11, it doesn't look like you're having too much trouble with that bracket up there, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I'll tell you, those new knobs really make it easy to twist the thing and get it cinched down quite tight.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Buzz, how does the alignment look, there?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It looks pretty good, as well as I can tell without the gear extended. I can't get a real definitive answer, but you couldn't fix it any place to see much more out of the window without hand-holding it for the whole time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Looks like to us it's going to work real well.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Give it enough room to - Yes, I think so.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Buzz, we see you putting your window guard in place there, and back up to the ISA now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, ask FAO if the 90-degree bracket isn't stowed in the Commander's stowage assembly.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Buzz, you still looking for that 90-degree bracket? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes, he is looking for it now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll have a word for you in just a moment.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Our monitor shows pretty good, clear pictures from this angle. I already found the 90-degree bracket.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. It's really a super picture. We've got the ACA, your ACA, the picture of the throttle, the 90-degree bracket. We see your handles, and now over to the bracket.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That's about the position we'll be putting the camera in after the initial descent on the ladder, and it'll be taken 1 frame a second for most of the EVA.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Houston copies. Out. That's a real good view of that camera.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Our monitor is a little bit wavy, so it's hard for us to tell when we're - when we've got a steady picture for you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, we have no complaints at all. We don't see that waviness on our picture. It's just really great. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Do the edges of the window look like straight lines to you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. They don't in our monitor, and that leads us to make some corrections to the camera, which probably aren't required sometimes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Buzz, we have no complaints at all. It's a magnificent picture.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: What was that, Buzz, you're chasing now?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That was - That was me picking up some particles of paint that were floating through the air in front of the camera, there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. We got it. It appears to us that Neil's about to check the Velcro mat, there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, Buzz. We see the card up now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. For those of you that don't know, this is where we log most of our data for each of the LM maneuvers, and we have another card like this that the timeline book that is laid down on the table in front of the data display keyboard, and it's on this timeline that we have all our procedures. But we obviously have to hold these in place in zero g, so we make use of the Velcro patches on the back and on the table so we can attach these down here, and then we just turn the pages over when we go to new sequences in our timeline of procedures.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And we're ready to copy DOI PAD.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll have the FIDO's work that one up for you momentarily.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That was a good shot of Panel 2. Now we got Panel 3 in view with the TEMP MONITOR switch. The stabilization - station and control panel, we see now, with the MODE CONTROL switches. Now over to the rendezvous radar. Real good.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, that's real good camera work.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That'll be the most unusual position a cameraman's ever had, hanging by his toes from a tunnel and taking the picture upside-down.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Well you're doing a super job. We got a good view of the cross pointer, there. Had a good view of the tape meter.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're giving you a picture now of the floor of the cabin. I think you can see the - one of the two portable life support system backpacks here in the center, and on each side, we have the two helmet visors. I'll remove one of them and show you a little closer view of what this looks like.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Inside the helmet visors are the EVA gloves with the blue tips. I'm about to take those out now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. That's a great shot now that we're getting of the helmet, the EVA visor, and also the - the EVA gloves in the background.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. You did say this was going out now, didn't you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. I think so.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, you got a pretty big audience. It's live in the U.S. It's going live to Japan, western Europe, and much of South America. Everybody reports very good color. Appreciate the great show.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Buzz, that was a good demonstration of your EVA visor assembly. Appreciate it.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, I like the good view of Mr. Collins down there. We finally see him again.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Hello there, earthling.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We noticed when you were scanning over Panel 2 a moment ago, 1 and 2, the two eight balls were slightly in disagreement. Control said he'd like a AGS align, there.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. One of them's AGS, one of them's PNGCS. The problem is, we don't know whether to align AGS to PNGCS or PNGCS to AGS.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Chris said he can tell you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We'll cage them both.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Like old home week, Charlie, to get back in the LM again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I can imagine.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: The traverse from the bottom of the LM to the aft bulkhead of the command module must be about 16, 20 feet. It's not a disorienting one at all, but it's most interesting to contemplate just pushing off from one and bounding on into the other vehicle all the way through the tunnel.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Must be some experience. Is Collins going to go in and look around?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We're willing to let him go but he hasn't come up with the price of the ticket yet.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I'd advise him to keep his hands off the switches.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: If I can get him to keep his hands off my DSKY, it'd be a fair swap.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: That's why I've been eating so much today. I haven't had anything to do. He won't let me touch it any more.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. If that's not the Earth, we're in trouble.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's the Earth, and we have a very good view of it today. There are a few more cloud bands on than yesterday when we beamed down to you, but it's a beautiful sight.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We have some horizontal banding in our TV monitor. Are we transmitting that to you, or do you have a clear picture?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Neil, we have a very clear picture. The only thing that we see is a little white dot in the bottom of our screen, which is - our TV guys say is an - apparently a burned out spot in the camera, but it should come back. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We have that in our monitor also.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We do have three lines across our TV. I thought it was just a transmission problem, but everybody's telling me now that it's probably - it's on the downlink. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: No, those are the same three ones that we have.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: How far are - out are we now, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. Give you exact figure.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Did you notice the difference between yesterday and today? This is as large an image we can - we can give you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. If you think we're smaller, you're now 177 000 miles out. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's nautical miles?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative, 11. We -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: ... Hold on.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We see the - still see the banding along the intratropical convergence. I guess the most predominate one now is around the - up in the - around the equator or slightly north of the equator.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes, that's the way it looks, Charlie. Same as yesterday.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Just keep the Pacific Ocean nice and clear and calm on splash day, is all we ask.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And Charlie, I'd like to say hello to all my fellow scouts and scouts at Farragut State Park in Idaho having a National Jamboree there this week, and Apollo 11 would like to send them best wishes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thank you, Apollo 11. I'm sure that, if they didn't hear that, they'll get the word through the news, surely appreciate that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We have you - your subspacecraft point is just off the western coast of South America directly south of about Mexico City. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That - That looks like what we observe from here.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And we're going to turn our TV monitor off now for a short bit while we have some other work to do. Apollo 11 signing off.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Thank you very much. That was one of the greatest shows we've ever seen. We sure appreciate it. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It was a pleasure.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Could you give us an idea of about how long it will be before you start close - closing the LM back up? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We've got a little more work to do up here, Charlie. We're going to make sure that we have everything transferred around and stowed the way we want it and try to get a little bit ahead on tomorrow's timeline. I suppose that we could be out of there in another half hour or so if it was necessary.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. We're not trying to push you. We're just trying to get an idea of - about water dumps and starting up the PTC again. Take your sweet time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We'd like to get a flight plan update from you for the next couple of hours, here. When you think what the various constraints might be and what - what order you might like us to do things.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by. We'll have that to you in a moment.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Mike, we'd like to go ahead and do waste-water dump. We'd like you to dump it all the way down to zero. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. We copy that, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How does that work, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Did you call? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Just noticed that the mast that the EVA light is on is charred brown. It looks as though it took quite a beating during launch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: The EVA light still does work.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll let this - the SPAN guys look at this, and we'll be back with you with what we think. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We were wondering, Neil, with your closing comment on the TV, if you were going to turn it off. It indicated that you might be considering turning it back on. We were wondering whether we want to keep the lines up. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Well, we want your recommendation on that, but I think we would just as soon, ourselves, terminate the TV. But if you have a commitment to keep, we'd be more than willing to turn it back on.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like to terminate the TV. We don't - We think we got a really - a good tape. That hour and a half show was superb. And we'd like to pick up TV - correction - PTC at about 58 hours. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. PTC at 58 hours.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we'll have the remaining functions in the flight plan soon. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Our recommendations on the activities for the next hour or so, as far as flight plan goes, are: Continue your LM familiarization as desired until about 58 hours, then ingress to the CSM, close the hatch, and establish PTC shortly thereafter. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, Apollo 11, Houston. Terminate the --

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: -- the water dump. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Water dump being terminated now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. I'd like to do a P52 option 3 and tweak the platform up prior to starting the PTC. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. That sounds like a good idea to us. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. And the platform's looking pretty good to me. It looks like the worst axis drift is 0.01 something degrees per hour. Is that about what you figure?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Roger. We've had reports all the marks have been good all the - the last couple of times you've run them. Just a moment; I'll get you some
information on the apparent drift rate.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Owen. Thank you. You got the maroons on?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I say you got the maroons on now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Not permanently, Mike. Just have stand-boy here while Charlie's out checking how to use that special tool on the camera. The maroon team will be on tomorrow.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Nice to hear your voice. How's everything going?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Everything's going smoothly here. We sure enjoyed the show this afternoon, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We suggest you go ahead and do the P52 first, and we'll take a look at the angles and give you some new drift rates after taking a look at them. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right. Fair enough.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead. 11, here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. A little information to you there, CDR. We've all taken a momentary brief respite from out work here to have some special - to have a bite of special moon cheese that is - I understand it's been sent to us directly from Wapakoneta, your own hometown. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: No, we can't - we can't pronounce it either I think you'll enjoy that. They make a fine brand of cheese.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, there, and I'll polish up the grammar for the next trip.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, 11. You are looking at the NOUN 93, and I'll proceed when you copy them

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We've got them.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11, Houston. We'd like POOR and ACCEPT. We have delta-The update for you. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right, Charlie. Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. POOR and ACCEPT.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We got the load in. The computer's yours. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, 11. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We'd like for you to stir up the CRYO's now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We're completed in the LM. We're closing up the hatches and the probe and drogue back in.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We're standing by to watch your startup on the PTC at any time. You can start off at the VERB 49. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Wilco. We're just finishing up the probe and about to close up the hatch here. We're going to be a couple of minutes late, probably, getting started in the PTC.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. No sweat, 11. We're standing by. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Mike, there's no wait required. Where rates are steady, you can proceed on. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'm doing it, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The tunnel's all taken care of, the drogue, probe, and hatch all back.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. Out.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We have some new additions to your alternate contingency checklist if you would break that out. Over

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. 11's ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. If you'll turn to page F2-22. Over

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. I have F2-22.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. Under column 1 - that's column line 06. The new data is 00001. Line 07, the new data is 02134. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. I have in F2-22, column Limit, item 6, 00001, item 7, 02134.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's correct. Thank you much. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. For your information, those two entries are an update to your DELTA-The that we have already uplinked into the CMC. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: What was I marking on, Charlie? About an 18-kilometer line, or what?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We - Our update puts you to - the DELTA-The to 35 kilometers, Mike. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We've got some switch positions for you for the high gain. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. Select Bravo, OMNI, HIGH-GAIN TRACK to MANUAL, BEAM, WIDE. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Bravo, OMNI, TRACK, MANUAL, and BEAM, WIDE.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And your high-gain angles are minus 50 on the pitch, 270 on the yaw. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Going there now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We have some updates and some things we'd like to talk to you about, if you aren't in the middle of your meal. If it' convenient anytime for you, we're ready with some updates. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: What - What are the updates going to apply to?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We have a couple of changes on the LM mission rules NOW-GOT for your NOW-GOT card, Neil. One slight change on the APS/DPS fuel and TEMP pressure card, and we have a change to the procedure for the secondary radiator leak check, which is to be formed at - performed at 71 hours tomorrow, and also some indications that we have a couple of landing site obliques stowed in the wrong place. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Is any of those in the flight plan? The secondary radiator, for example?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative. The secondary radiator leak check is called out in the flight plan at 71 20 That procedure is listed in your launch operations book on page . We'd like to change that procedure. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, on the secondary leak check, just read it verbatim like you want, and I'll copy directly into the flight plan and not fool around with the checklist.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's fine. If you're ready to copy, stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Ready to copy on the leak check.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It's monitor secondary accumulator quantity. Step 2 is secondary glycol to radiator valve, NORMAL for 30 seconds, then BYPASS. If no decrease in secondary accumulator quantity - Are you with me?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, I'm with you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. If no decrease in secondary accumulator quantity, secondary glycol to radiator valve to NORMAL. Next step, secondary coolant loop pump,

AC-1 or AC-2. After 3 minutes, verify glycol discharge secondary pressure 39 to 51 psig. Also verify secondary EVAP out TEMP has changed. Next step, secondary coolant loop pump, OFF. Secondary glycol to radiator valve, BYPASS. That ends the procedure. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I read back monitor secondary accumulator quantity; secondary glycol radiator valve, NORMAL for 30 seconds, then to BYPASS. If no decrease in secondary accumulator quantity, secondary glycol to radiator valve to NORMAL. Secondary coolant loop pump, AC-1 or 2. After 3 minutes, verify glycol secondary discharge pressure 39 to 51 psig. Verify secondary evaporator outlet TEMP has changed. Secondary coolant loop pump, OFF. Secondary glycol radiator valve to BYPASS. And what's the reason for the change, Charlie?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stan is concerned that our present procedure as shown in the checklist does not really flow glycol through the radiator, and it - They want to verify that we do not have a plugged secondary radiator. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. They have any abnormal indications in that system, so far?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative. This is the procedure that they came up with. It's just a check, Mike. Everything's looking great to us. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Charlie, we'll get back with you on these other changes in a few minutes. Okay?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. No hurry. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We're wondering who's on horn.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Say again, Houston?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We just had a little music there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We'll keep you entertained.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That was good. You can keep it coming down, 11.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Because it's a special occasion today, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Happy anniversary.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you, sir.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Ready to copy your update.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, Buzz. The first item is that we have indications that your landing site obliques are out in the proper position. If you'll check, we think that the intermediate-scale landing site oblique is stowed in the CSM lunar landmark book. We think that the large-scale back of the IM lunar surface map book Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I think I heard you Charlie, but I'm not sure that I understand.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. According to our stowage list the - the landing site oblique should be in the transfer bag. In - But in the backup set of data, the intermediate-scale oblique is in the CSM lunar landmark book, and the large-scale oblique is in the back of the IM lunar surface map book, and that's the reason we think that they might be not where you think they are. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We've got three obliques. The last one is one I asked for recently. It's just blow-cup of the second one. The first one is one that's got dotted lines on it, indicating horizon view and 50-degree LPD, and all three of those are in the transfer book. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Fine. We were wrong in our - in our backup set. We had those out of place. Looks like the onboard data's good. We just wanted to let you check on that one. We have an update on the APS/DPS fuel card that you place on the panel. It's a typo error. If you'll break out that little card, we've got the - correct that typo error. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I got it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. Under the DPS column on the pressure side, you go down to the fourth item, says pressure greater than 150 PTCA should be greater than 65 percent. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. That's greater than 1.8 but less than 65 and greater than 150 for greater than 65.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we have three items on the mission rules NOW-GOT card, if you're ready to copy those. Over

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I've got the mission rules NOW-GOT

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. First entry's on the EPS under AC bus A. The line extends all the way to high gate. Actually, the line should read - at DOI it would be NOW-GOT AC bus A. After that the NOW-GOT would be both buses. So if you will just pencil in both buses from PDI through high gate, it'll be correct for that line. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I've got that. AC bus A for DOI and both buses NOW-GOT for PDI on.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative up until high gate. You can stop at the line in front of the column "5 minutes to low gate." Now the next line is under the G&C PGNS, pitch and roll GDA's. You can scratch that line completely. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Got it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, Buzz. Last entry is down under RCS, and it's a typo error under the three - in the line "remains attitude control." If you proceed to the right at PDI plus 05, you'll see one axis. The line goes all the way to low gate to touchdown. That's incorrect. The line should stop under "5 minutes to low gate." Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We're stopping that at "5 minutes to low gate."

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative. That completes that card. The rest of the updates are just really for your information based on our 58-hour platform - look at the platform. We are really good shape. Your GYRO's have almost no drift in them since - plotted update we were looking at X of a minus 2.24 ...

Y of point plus 0.87, Z of minus 0.11. Since the update, which was based on the 52-hour P52, I believe, we gave you an X drift of plus 0.79, yaw of plus 1.06, Z of plus 0.02 ... I can see the difference between the 52-hour and the 57-hour alignments were - did not really give us enough time to get a real good or completely valid update on the drift check. So we're real satisfied with the way the GYRO's are looking. The PIPA's are looking great also. We are in real good shape with those, too. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: This is Apollo 11. Radio check

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Reading you five-boy. How me? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Loud and clear. You cut out when you were talking about the platform - something about 52 hours and after that, we never heard you again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Guess we were changing antennas. Stand by That's affirmative, 11. We were swapping antennas on you down here. Basically the word is that we have a real good platform, very small drift on the GYRO's, and very small drift in the PIPA's. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you. And I would like to have a few words of clarification if you will give them to me on the RCS ... what that change of pitch may mean.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy. A few words of clarification on the RCS? Oh. Roger. The update there, Neil, you are speaking of about the one axis down to 5 minutes of low gate?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. That's right. I'm not quite sure what that ... means beyond 5 minutes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by. I'll make sure I got my story straight with Control. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. On the RCS, what we are saying is that if we lose control about one axis prior to low gate, we would recommend an abort. This would require a - a loss of - of two distinct jets which is not very probable, but that is what we are recommending. After low gate we would continue on. We would recommend that we continue on to attempt a landing. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. I think I ..

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Charlie, did you say you had some updates for me from the lunar surface book?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, say again. You were cut out Over

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Did you say you had some updates for us in the lunar surface book. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative. At this time, we do not have an, updates for the lunar surface book. We wanted you to have it just in case. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. You were cut out that time.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. At the present time, we do not have any updates for you on the lunar surface book. We are thinking about some and kicking them around, but they're very minor changes. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Did you copy that transmission?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We swapped antennas on you again. I say again that we do not have any lunar surface update - book updates at this time. We're considering a few minor ones, but we're still kicking them around the MOCR. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Apollo 11. I understand.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, 11. We have a crew status report for you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you, Mike. Could you give us some help? This PTC is strange: it's not like anything we've seen before. We were wondering if you have had any events or any odd data that could help us out. Over.

blocks.text: I didn't understand that. Say again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're looking at a - sort of a funny looking PTC. We've already drifted out to 70 degrees in pitch and we're wondering if you all have had any vents or any such thing as that, that could have caused us to pick up these rates to drive us off. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We have absolutely no idea. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Did, it look like it was all right, then just all of a sudden start diverging?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's negative, Mike. If you'll look at the plot, which we'll save for you and let you see it postflight, it started off immediately on the first REV and just spiraled out to about - oh 20 to - 20 degrees in pitch, and then it seemed to be setting up a spiral around an offset pitch point of about 20 degrees off from 90 degrees, but we didn't want to take a chance that it would become stable at that point. We thought it might diverge, and so we called you and started over again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, no complaints. I was just curious as to what had happened.

blocks.text: Roger, 11. This is Houston. At approximately 71 hours to 72 hours, we have you down for an eat period which I imagine is probably in progress already.  71 hours:  O2 fuel cell purge; 72 hours GET:  CO2 filter change number 6, secondary radiator flow check.  And we'll send you up a P37 block data on a 2 hour pass, pericynthion pass, return mode abort.  At 73 hours 00 minutes:  stop PTC at approximately 0 degrees roll.  That is, when you're coming up on 0 degrees roll angle around 73 hours, we'd like you to stop PTC.  And perform a P52 option 3 remaining in the PTC REFSMMAT for a drift check.  73 hours, 20 minutes:  we'll give you a P27 update to the landing site REFSMMAT, LOI-1 state vector, and target load.  73 hours 30 minutes:  maneuver to 000 roll, pitch, and yaw; high gain antenna angles will be pitch 0, yaw 335; and perform a P52 option 1 using the new landing site REFSMMAT.  Resume the nominal flight plan at 74 hours GET.  Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP REFSSMAT?
blocks.text: Okay. We'll get started on the fuel cell purge while we're eating.  CO2 canister change number 6; secondary radiator flow check; copy some pads. Also at 72 hours, stop PTC 0 roll at 73, do a P52 option 3; we'll get your uplink REFSMMAT for the landing site, and at 000 - let's see, now was this with the old REFSMMAT or the new

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. It turns out that the engine performance during both of your burns so far this mission has been the same as it was on engine acceptance tests. The onboard PC reading is due to a known gage calibration factor between what you've actually got in the chamber and what you're reading out on the gage. We expect single-bank operation to be 90 - that is, 90 psi on the gage with an actual chamber pressure of 95 psi. In dual-bank operation, the chamber pressure is 94 of 99 psi. 80 psi on the gage on board correlates to 83 psi actual. And we recommend that you stick to an LOI termination cue of 80 psi on the gage. That is, no change to the mission rules. Over.

And, of course, I can see the sky is lit all the way around the Moon, even on the limb of it where there's no earthshine or sunshine.

And you're going to have to hand-hold us, I guess. We're recommending an of-stop of 2.8, and we'd like to get a sequence of time exposures. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. You want magazine Uniform instead of magazine Tango? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.speaker: LMP

blocks.speaker: CDR

Just like the nightside of Earth. But all the way here, we have only been able to see stars occasionally and perhaps through the monocular, but not recognize any star patterns.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I guess it has turned into night up there really, hasn't it?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Really has.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. If you have a minute or so free, we can read you up the morning news here.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go right ahead; let's hear it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Hot from the wires of the MSC Public Affairs Office, especially prepared for the crew of Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. First off, it looks like it's going to be impossible to get away from the fact that you guys are dominating all the news back here on Earth. Even Pravda in Russia is headlining the
mission and calls Neil, "The Czar of the Ship." I think maybe they got the wrong mission.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: West Germany has declared Monday to be "Apollo Day." School children in Bavaria have been given the day off. Post Office clerks have been encouraged to bring radios to work and Frankfurt is installing TV sets in public places.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: BBC in London is considering a special radio alarm system to call people to their TV sets in case there is a change in the EVA time on the Moon.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And in Italy, Pope Paul VI has arranged for a special color TV circuit at his summer residence in order to watch you, even though Italian television is still black and white.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Back here in Houston, your three wives and children got together for lunch yesterday at Buzz's house. And according to Pat, it turned out to be a gabfest. The children swam and did some high jumping over at Buzz's bamboo pole.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: In Moscow, space engineer Anatol Koritsky was quoted by TASS as saying that Luna 15 could accomplish everything that has been done by earlier Luna spacecraft. This was taken by the press to mean Luna 15 could investigate the gravitational fields, photograph the Moon, and go down to the surface to scoop up a bit for analysis.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Even the kids at camp got into the news when Mike Jr. was quoted as replying "yeah" when somebody asked him if his daddy was going to be in history. Then after a short pause he asked, "What is history?" In Washington, President Nixon is planning to use his executive power to streamline the Interstate Commerce Commission. According to industry sources, it was reported Nixon would trim the commission from 11 to 7 members by not making new appointments.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And the big news around Houston today concerns the Astros. In the sports world, the Houston Astros rallied in the ninth inning at Cincinnati to dump the Reds 7 to 4. Going into the ninth however, things looked pretty bleak. The Astros were trailing 4 to 3. Then with one out, Jesus Alou stroked a single to right field. John

Edwards hit another single to right, and Sandy Valdespino hit a double to bring in the tying run. Julio Gotay was walked and Joe Morgan dropped a bunt for the game-winning play. A wild throw to the plate allowed another run to score, then a sacrifice fly by Dennis Menke brought in the final run. They really came through in the ninth.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And other games in the National League --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Those Astros have really been catching those flies since they put a roof on the stadium.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Good work.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: In other games in the National League, New York beat Montreal 5 to 2; Pittsburgh beat St. Louis 4 to 1; and Atlanta over San Diego in the first game of a double header 6 to 2.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: In the American League, Detroit beat Cleveland 4 to nothing; New York trounced Washington 5 to nothing; Baltimore outhit - Boston outhit Baltimore to score 6 runs to the Orioles' 2; and Chicago beat Kansas City 6 to 1.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. In golf world, Tommy Jacobs, an infrequent competitor in recent years, took the lead in the Philadelphia Golf Classic yesterday. His second round score was 139.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You might be interested in knowing, since you are already on the way, that a Houston astrologer, Ruby Graham, says that all the signs are right for your trip to the Moon. She says that Neil is clever, Mike has good judgment, and Buzz can work out intricate problems. She also says Neil tends to see the world through rose-colored glasses, but he is always ready to help the afflicted or distressed. Neil, you are also suppose to have "intuition that enables you to interpret life with feeling." Buzz is to be very sociable and cannot bear to be alone in addition to having excellent critical ability. Since she didn't know at what hour Mike was born, she has decided that he either has the same attributes as Neil or he is inventive with an unconventional attitude that might seem eccentric to the unimaginative.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And last but not --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Who said all that?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Ruby Graham, an astrologer here in Houston.  Now we check with Flight Operations for all the signs for the mission, and then we, of course, had to make sure that everything was really all set.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, 11. You're cutting out ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Apollo 11, this is Houston. We're switching OMNI's.  Can you stand by for about 2 minutes?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, 11. Radio check.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. You cut out after Tommy Jacobs. I guess we got into antenna switching problems.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Following Tommy Jacobs, we have the hot smoking word from a local Houston astrologer by the name of Ruby Graham.  She says that all the signs are right for your trip to the Moon.  Neil is clever, Mike has good judgment, and Buzz can work out intricate problems.  She also says Neil tends to see the world through rose-colored glasses but is always ready to help the afflicted or distressed.  Neil, you are also supposed to have "intuition that enables you to interpret life with feeling," Buzz is supposed to be very sociable and cannot bear to be alone in addition to having excellent critical ability.  Since she didn't know at what hour Mike was born, she decided he either has the same attributes as Neil or that he is inventive with an unconventional attitude that might seem eccentric to the unimaginative.  And that's 30 for today.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you much there, Bruce and Fred Show, we appreciate that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Did you hear our comment about the Astros?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: The one about the roof?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, Mike, the game was at Cincinnati there, and we think that they're still using Crosby Field up there. I don't believe it has a roof on it.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You got him on that one.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Right --

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I think they're just getting to be a good team in the clinch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: They certainly seem to be.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, if they can do that well without a roof, think of what they're going to do with a roof.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We're trying.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: An old Oiler fan is trying to comment on an alien game.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You tell Michael Jr., history or no history, he'd better behave himself.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll pass that along, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. If it's convenient with you, we have an LOI-1 PAD that we can pass up to you now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. The next time we pass through roll 0, we're going to stop PTC and that will give us 90 degrees pitch. Now, I understand you want us to move from 90 degrees pitch to 0 degrees pitch for the platform align, option 1. Is that affirmative?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, please.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And we are ready to copy on the LOI-1.

first P52, that is, the P52 option 3, from that attitude. Then we'll uplink you a new REFSMMAT, either before or while you are maneuvering to 000, and then you can torque the platform around and run the second REFSMMAT. Over. Run the second P52. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And I copied you are ready for the LOI-1 pad. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Apparently we missed getting your onboard readouts on battery Charlie and PYRO batteries Alfa and Bravo last night. I wonder if you could give us some fresh numbers. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: You want the readings now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes, please. If it's convenient for you.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. All three of them are still 37.1.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. The P52 option 3 is complete. We're maneuvering to 000.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We observe your maneuvering, and we'll have some uplinks for you in a couple of minutes here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. We observe you're in P00. If you'll give us ACCEPT, we'll start our uplinks.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You've got it, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're on low bit rate at the present time so it's going to take us a little bit longer than normal to get this stuff up to you. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I guess we're in no rush.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We're here if you're there.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: The view of the Moon that we've been having recently is really spectacular. It fills about three-quarters of the hatch window, and of course, we can see the entire circumference, even though part of it is in complete shadow and part of it's in earthshine. It's a view worth the price of the trip.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, there are a lot of us down here that would be willing to come along.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I hope you get your turn, and soon.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: One of these days, we'll be able to bring the whole MOCR along, I hope. Save a lot of antenna switching.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: One of these days, we could bring the whole MOCR along, and then that'll save a lot of antenna switching.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's jolly.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're showing you -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The Czar is brushing his teeth, so I'm filling in for him.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, please.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I said the Czar is brushing his teeth, so I'm filling in for him. What can we do for you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. If you don't get in the way of the Czar while he's brushing his teeth, we'd like you to bring up the primary accumulator quantity a little bit. We're showing the quantity now at 20.6 percent on TM. Seems to have gone down a bit since you've gone into the shadow. We'd like it serviced to bring the quantity up to between 30 and 40 percent, preferable 35 percent. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: The computer is yours, 11. The loads are in and verified. You can go back to BLOCK.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We're in BLOCK.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. On the basis of your last P52 alignment, the platform looks like it's indeed performing very well. No problems there,
no updates required, and no PIPA bias update is required either. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Sounds good.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Radio check.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Loud and clear. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Just checking. Do you want high gain? , CC Roger. If you can give it to us.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How do you read on the high gain?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Loud and clear on the high gain.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Same here. We've completed the P52 option 1.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We've been looking over your shoulder by TM.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Glad to have you.

Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Was that 74 30? You want us to cycle the heaters and turn - cycle the fans and turn all the heaters on.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CDR

blocks.text: Roger. We put the wrong sign in --

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.text: -- for the roll correction to get MSFN high gain, and we're continuing rolling around to get the proper attitude for high gain at this time. We will delete the pitch maneuver that was scheduled subsequent to - subsequent to the TV check since we already have those pictures.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. And we recommend that you go ahead and complete your TVC test on board. If you have problems, we'll talk to you when you get around further into the high gain antenna attitude. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, how do you read on high gain?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, loud and clear on high gain, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We're proceeding.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. We observed your gimbal test down here, and it looked good to us. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. It looked good here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Radio check. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Loud and clear.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And your systems are looking good from down here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Looks good up here too, Bruce.

blocks.speaker: LMP

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.text: If you want to, I'll put it back to high until just before LOS. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative, 11. Low is okay for now. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.text: Houston, do you want to give me a time check, please?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I'll give you a Mark at 13 minutes and 30 seconds to ignition.

blocks.text: Okay. And then a GET, please.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by a minute.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I'll give you a time hack on the GET at 75 hours 37 minutes and I'll try that bias at about a second and a half to allow for the time of flight.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: MARK.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 75 hours 37 minutes GET.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by for a Mark at TIG minus 12.0

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: MARK.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: TIG minus 12.0

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You were right on, Bruce. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Everything looks okay up here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: It was like - like perfect! DELTA-TIG zero, burn time 557, shaft value on the angles, Vgx minus 0.1, Vgy minus 0.1, Vgz plus 0.1, no trim, minus 6.8 on DELTA-TVC, fuel was 38.8, LOX 39.0, plus 50 on balance, and we ran an increase on the PUGS, NOUN 44 showed us in a 60.9 by 169.9.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy your burn status report. And the spacecraft is looking good to us on telemetry.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Everything looks good up here.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Apollo 11 is getting its first view of the landing approach. This time we are going over the Taruntius crater, and the pictures and maps brought back by Apollo 8 and 10 have given us a very good preview of what to look at here. It looks very much like the pictures, but like the difference between watching a real football game and watching it on TV. There's no substitute for actually being here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We concur, and we surely wish we could see it firsthand, also.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're going over the Messier series of craters right at the time, looking vertically down on them, and Messier A we can see good sized blocks in the bottom of the crater. I don't know what our altitude is now, but in any case, those are pretty good size blocks.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Just roughly, it looks like you are about 120 miles or 130 miles right now - make that 127 miles.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We're approaching PDI point now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: There's Secchi in sight.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're going over Mount Marilyn at the present time, and it's ignition point.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you. And our preliminary tracking data for the first few minutes shows you in a 61.6 by 169.5 orbit. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And Jim is smiling.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.text: 11, Houston. During your SPS burn as played back on tape down here, we've observed the nitrogen tank Bravo pressure in the SPS system dropping a little bit more than we anticipated. It's holding steady right now. We'll continue to watch it and keep you posted if anything comes up. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Right. And it has held steady --

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Currently going over Maskelyne Mas - ,

blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And Boothill, Duke Island, Sidewinder, looking at Maskelyne W, that's the yaw round checkpoint, and just coming into the terminator. At the terminator it's ashen and gray. As you get further away from the terminator, it gets to be
a lighter gray, and as you get closer to the subsolar point, you can definitely see browns and tans on the ground, according to the last

blocks.text: Roger, 11. We're recording your comments for posterity.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.text: Did somebody in the background - do they accuse us of being compromisers? Huh!

blocks.speaker: CDR

blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How about coming up with some roll, pitch, and yaw angles in which to stop this son-called ORB RATE that I'm doing.

blocks.text: We'll have them for you in a minute, 1..

blocks.text: Yes, indeed.

blocks.text: Roger. We show you, in the flight plan, staying in orbital rate until about 79 hours 10 minutes. Do you have some particular attitude or reason for wanting to go inertial? Over.
