No, that's fine. I just wanted to confirm that. Until 79 10, then we'll breeze around here in orbit.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. And we've got an observation you can make if you have some time up there. There's been some lunar transient events reported in the vicinity of Aristarchus. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. We just went into spacecraft darkness. Until then, why, we couldn't see a thing down below us. But now, with earthshine, the visibility is pretty fair. Looking back behind me, now, I can see the corona from where the Sun has just set. And we'll get out the map and see what we can find around Aristarchus.
We're coming upon Aristarchus right now --
blocks.speaker: CDR
CC
blocks.text: -- Okay. Aristarchus is at angle Echo 9 on your ATO chart. It's about 394 miles north of track. However, at your present altitude, which is about 167 nautical miles, it ought to be over -- that is within view of your horizon: 23 degrees north, 47 west. Take a look and see if you see anything worth noting up there. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Both looking.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, 11. It might help us a little bit if you could give us a time of crossing of 45 west.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, please, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: You might give us a time of crossing of 45 west, and then we'll know when to start searching for Aristarchus.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. You'll be crossing or about 40 seconds from now. Over. Thirty seconds from now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, when we lose the Is-band, we'd like to get OMNI Charlie from you. And update my last, that 77 04 was the time when Aristarchus should
become visible over your horizon. 77 12 is point of closest approach south of it. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. That sounds better because we just went by Copernicus a little bit ago.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We show you at about 27 degrees longitude right now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Righto.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, when a star sets up here, there's no doubt about it. One instant it's there, and the next instant it's just completely gone

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. We request you use OMNI Charlie at this time. Over.
Okay. Going to OMNI Charlie.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.
Houston, Apollo 11.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Go ahead.

Roger. Seems to me since we know orbits so precisely, and know where the stars are so precisely, and the time of setting of a star or a planet to so very fine a degree, that this might be a pretty good means of measuring the altitude of the horizon ...
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger.

Hey, Houston. I'm looking north up toward Aristarchus now, and I can't really tell at that distance whether I am really looking at Aristarchus, but there's an area that is considerably more illuminated than the surrounding area. It just has - seems to have a slight amount of fluorescence to it. A crater can be seen, and the area around the crater is quite bright.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Looking up at the same area now and it does seem to be reflecting some of the earthshine. I'm not sure whether it was worked

out to be about zero phase to - Well, at least there is one wall of the crater that seems to be more illuminated than the others, and that one - if we are lining up with the Earth correctly, does seem to put it about at zero phase. That area is definitely lighter than anything else that I could see out this window. I am not sure that I am really identifying any phosphorescence, but that definitely is lighter than anything else in the neighborhood.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Can you discern any difference in color of the illumination, and is that an inner or an outer wall from the crater? Over.
Roger. That's an inner wall of the crater.
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: No, there doesn't appear to be any color involved in it, Bruce.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. You said inner wall. Would that be the inner edge of the northern surface?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I guess it would be the inner edge of the westnorthwest part, the part that would be more nearly normal if you were looking at it from the Earth.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Have you used the monocular on this? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Like you to know this quest for science has caused me to lose my We-memory program, it's in here somewhere, but I can't find it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're - we're hearing only a partial COMM. Say again please.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I think ...

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, we will give it a try if we have the opportunity on next - when we are not in the middle of lunch, and trying to find the monocular.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copied you that time. Expect in the next REV you will probably be getting ready for LOI-2.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: So, let's wind this up, and since we've got some other things to talk to you about in a few minutes. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're targeting - planning to make the LOI-2 burn now using bank A only. We'll have the PAD and everything for you next time around. Just trying to economise a little on bank B. Bank B is holding, though.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. In order to improve the communications a little bit here, we'd like to try to get you on the high-gain antenna. We're recommending a pitch angle of 0, yaw 355 - I say again 355, the track switch to MANUAL, and wide beamwidth. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. You ready to switch to high gain now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Do you read?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We read you. It seems to be rather marginal on the high gain.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We concur.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Could you give us a time of crossing the prime meridian 150 west? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by about a half a second, here. Okay. Your time of crossing the 150 west meridian will be 77 50 05. Over.
Thank you.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We have about 6 minutes remaining until LOS, and in order that we may configure our ground lines, we'd like to know if you're still planning to have the TV up with the beginning of the next pass. Over.
Roger, Houston. We'll try to have it ready.
blocks.speaker: CDR
CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. We are inquiring if it is your plan to. Over.
It never was our plan to; but it's in the flight plan, so I guess we'll do it.
blocks.speaker: CDR
CC
blocks.text: Houston. Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston.
Roger. Go ahead.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: For use in connection with the prime meridian crossing, you have an orbital period now of 2 hours 8 minutes and 37 seconds. Over.
Thank you.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. A little over 2 minutes to LOS. All your systems parameters and orbit are looking good from the ground. We have AOS on the other side at 78 23 31. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That was 31 on the end.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.
BEGIN LUNAR REV 2

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: This is Apollo 11. Are you picking up our signals okay?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Affirmative. We are reading you loud and clear on voice and we have a good clear TV picture, a little bright crater in the --
-- No, no, no --
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: -- the bottom of the picture. I guess that's the spot on the tube.
I'm sorry about that one.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: And if you give us POOR and ACCEPT, we will uplink our new state vector and target load to you.
Okay.
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. One of the larger craters on the back side - I noticed a small, dark speck on the outer wall and I put the monocular on it. I was able to see - oh, an area maybe a quarter of a mile in diameter. It was really a freshlooking dark-colored pit, and that seems to be in contrast with all the other fresh little craters or holes that you can perceive on the walls of any of these craters. Around this particular one there seems to be two or three of these - especially the one that caught my attention. Quite remarkable. Over.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. Do you have a location on that one?
No, not a precise one. I've got several pictures of it, though.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We're getting a beautiful picture in down there now, 11. The color's coming in quite clearly, and we can see the horizon and the relative blackness of space, and without getting into the question of grays and browns, it looks, at least on our monitor, sort of brownish-gray.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That's a good, reasonable way of describing it. It appears to me as though it made a difference just sitting back in the tunnel and gazing at all windows; it makes a difference which one you're looking out of. For example, the camera
right now is looking out the number 5 window, and it definitely gives a rosier or tanner tinge, especially when you look straight through it and not at an angle. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
And if you rear back 95 or 100 degrees ...
blocks.speaker: LMP
MS
blocks.text: ... Still holding ... Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, 11?
I'd say we're about 95 degrees east, coming up on Smyth's Sea.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. And for your information, we snow you at an altitude of about 92 miles above the surface right now.
Okay.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Could you observe a difference in the N2 pressures before LOI? It seems to me as though the two were not equal on the ... B tank was a little low on pressure. Over.

I'm flying it in SPS minimum impulse, Houston, and it's rather difficult to keep it on a constant data. The LM wants to wander up and down. I'm not sure if it's in response to MASSCON's or what, but I can get it completely stabilized in DATA and let it alone, and in another couple of minutes it will have developed its own rate.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Roger.
Houston, we'll be moving shortly from the side window to the hatch window, and we'll try and pick up some of the landmarks that we'll be looking at as we approach the powered descent. Over.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Roger. And we're through with the uplinks; the computer is yours. You can go to BLOCK and we'll have the information on nitrogen for you shortly. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. Several minutes ago I was exactly steady on data, and since then I have been moving
toward the LM, pointed straight down toward the radius vector, and that's been despite a number of down minimum-pitch impulses.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're over Smyth's Sea right now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We're about 88 degrees east, I would estimate.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We show you about south of the - southwest of the crater Jansky right now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Smyth Sea doesn't look much like a sea. It - The area which is devoid of craters, of which there's not very much, is sort of a hilly looking area. It's not like the maria at all.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy that about the sea, and it looks like you were just giving us a view of the crater Neper, the large crater on the left, and Jansky on the right.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We think you're close, but no cigar

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: will, this is Houston. Would you care tc comment on some of these craters as we go by?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We're approaching the approach path to ignition.  This is equivalent to 13 minutes before ignition, and we're at about 83 degrees, I guess - 83 degrees east.  That correspond to location you're holding there presently?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're showing your present position as about 77 - 76 degrees east looking back towards the east.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Hey, you should be looking back at Smyth Sea now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, what you're seeing in the middle of the screen now is the crater Schubert and Gilbert U is in the center right now; and this comes up at about - a little over 12 minutes before power decent:  Instead of me looking - Instead of looking back at it, we'd be looking straight down at it in descent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we show you at an altitude now of about 110 miles, and, of course, you'll be considerably lower at the initiation of powered descent.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay, Houston. Look at register 3 on the data. This data is increasing toward my desired of 315, and I'll let the hand controller alone here, and I'll bet you it reverses itself.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We're watching the DSKY now, and it's still coming in beautifully on the TV.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. There's - on the right side of the screen at the present time, there's a triple crater with - with a small crater between the first and second, and the one at the bottom of the screen is Schubert Y. Zoom in, it does have a central peak in Schubert Y. Actually, several of them, and you can observe those plus the rim craters at the bottom of your screen.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're seeing the central peak quite clearly now.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We're zooming in now on a crater called Schubert N. Schubert N, very conical inside walls and the bottom appears to be nearly flat.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Look at data on the DSKY. It's stabilized and is holding steady now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Looking out the window I can see a number of small craters on the bottom of Schubert N.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We're coming up on the Foaming Sea where I'll be doing some P22 marking on a crater of my choice, name of crater, Camp.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. We'll be watching for Neper.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And notice register 3 has reversed itself, and it's heading back the other way now without any pitch thruster firing.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We confirm that you've changed the direction of your pitch rate.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Generally speaking -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The crater -

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: - - The tendency seems to be to pull the LM down toward the center of the Moon there as in a gravity gradient experiment.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We copy --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It may have something to do with MASSCON's or it may --

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy ...
It may have something to do with MASSCON's or it may just be the peculiarity of the DSKY display.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Okay. We've observed the behavior of your DSKY, and I think we've got the data here to work on it. Let us grind around a little while on it, and we'll report back to you, probably in a REV or two.
Okay. Well, in the meantime, I'm going to pitch down toward 315.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Three craters - three horizontal craters that you now have in the field of view are immediately underneath the ground track. The right-hand is the largest crater that you see, Dubiago P.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We concur on the identification of that crater.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we show you coming up on landmark Alfa 1 here shortly.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Mike's having his first look a Alfa 1 at the present time.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. It's a very bright crater. It's not a large one but an extremely bright one. It looks like a very recent and, I would guess, impact crater with rays streaming out in all directions which should make my - Correction - the Foaming Sea easy to see coming up on it now. Crater Camp is one of the smaller ones out on the - on the floor of the Foaming Sea.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Here we show you over the Sea of Fertility now, and we ought to have Langrenus down south of track a few degrees, about 9 degrees south of track.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Now the crater that's in the center of the screen now is Webb. We'd be looking straight down on it at about 6 minutes before power descent. It has a relatively flat bottom to the crater, and you can see maybe two or three craters that are in the bottom of it on the western wall, the wall that's now nearest the - the camera. Near the bottom of the screen, we can see a dimple crater, just on the outside. And then coming back toward the bottom of the screen and to the left, you can see a series of depressions. It's this type of connected craters that give us most interest to discover why they're in the particular pattern that they're in. I'll zoom the camera in now and try and give you a closer look at it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're observing the dimple crater now. The central peak we can see on the Orbiter photos doesn't seem to stand out very well here.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, they're not central peaks. They're depressions in the center.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
And you'll notice on the pitch thruster activity, I've still - I've put in a dozen minimum impulses in pitchdown, and I'm still far from correcting back to 315.
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: We're moving the camera over to the right window now to give you Langrenus, its - its several central peaks and -
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. We got Langrenus in our screen now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. This is Houston. We're getting a beautiful picture of Langrenus now with its rather conspicuous central peak.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The Sea of Fertility doesn't look very fertile to me. I don't know who named it.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Well, it may have been named by a gentleman whom this crater was named after, Langrenus. Langrenus was a cartographer to the King of Spain and made one of the - one of the early reasonably accurate maps of the Moon.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's very interesting --

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: ... at least it sounds better for our purposes than the Sea of Crises.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Amen to that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. It looks like you're coming inside now on the camera.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Well, I can't get behind to see the monitor. I'll bring the focus in, but we're going to be looking down past one of the LM quads and one of the antennas almost straight down at the ground track that we'll be seeing coming in now. I guess there's maybe 2 or 3 minutes before power descent.
All right, that should put the LM structure about in focus, and I'm going to move it out to infinity and then expand the field of view.
blocks.speaker: LMP
LMP
blocks.text: Crater Secchi is out my window now, window number 2.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. This is Houston. We show you coming up on the terminator at 78 53, about 7 minutes from now, and we've also got the LOI-2 and TEI-5 PAD's ready for you after the TV whenever you want to terminate. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we're getting a good view of the track leading into the landing site now and -

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. And it looks like we got Secchi K, went by about 10 seconds ago, coming up on Apollo Ridge.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And in the right-hand portion of our screen right now, we can see Messier Alfa and Bravo with the light-colored rays streaming off in one direction.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I don't know if you can make out, but in the Sea of Fertility there are a number of craters that are just barely discernible, old, old craters whose outlines are just barely able to be seen.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I think we can make them out. The color really enhances our ability to discern features and craters over what we see in real time on our black and white monitor.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Right. The - At these low Sun angles, there's no trace of brown. It's now returned to a very gray appearance and, like the 8 crew says, it has a look of plaster of paris to it at this Sun angle, which is completely lacking in ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. This is very close to ignition point for power descent. Just passing Mount Marilyn that - that triangular-shaped mountain that you see in the center of the screen at the present time with crater Secchi Theta on top of the far northern edge of the mountain.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're getting a good view of Mount Marilyn and the Secchi Theta.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And now we're looking at what we call Boot Hill; occurs 20 seconds into the descent.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The bright, sharp-rimmed crater at the very right edge of the screen, Censorinus T. Now passing the - the 1-minute point in power descent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And for your information, your current altitude is 148 nautical miles above the surface.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Don't you think?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'm unable to determine altitude at all looking out the window. I couldn't tell whether we were down at 60 or up at 170.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I bet you could tell if you were down at 50 000 feet.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I wouldn't be surprised.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We're passing some steep ridges here. The edge of some old craters that were photographed by Apollo 10; and those - the crew of Apollo 10 was very impressed with the steepness of these ridges when they came over them at about 50 000 feet.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We can observe they're also steep even from this altitude. You got quite a shadow being cast by the Sun at these low angles.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The entire surface is getting considerably darker than the surface that we looked at previously when the Sun was quite high above us. The crater in the - bright crater in the center cf the screen, - well, the smaller one is Censorinus.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And we show you low over 1 minute from the terminator at the present time.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: How's the brightness of the picture you're receiving? You think we ought to open of-stop some as we approach the terminator?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes. The brightness is still doing quite well. You can go ahead and open it up a stop or two. The automatic light level compensation seems to be working beautifully.
There's a good picture of Boot Hill.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're --

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Three minutes and 15 seconds into the descent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're seeing Boot Hill now.

The next crater coming into the bottom, that's Duke Island right there, and to the left, the crater - the largest of the craters near the center of the picture right now is Ma'keyed W. This is a position check during descent at about 3 minutes and 39 seconds, and it's our downrange position check and cross-range position check prior to yawing over face up to acquire the landing radar. Past this point, we would be unable to see the surface below us until getting very near the landing area.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. I imagine you'll get a - you'll get a real good look at that tomorrow afternoon.
Sinuous Rille is the one that was referred to in Apollo 10 as Sidewinder.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CMP
blocks.text: That's a good name, too: Sidewinder and Diamondback. It looks like a couple of snakes down there in a lake bed.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And we're approaching the terminator now. See the -

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Contrast has increased and only the sunlit side of these ridges remain illuminated, while the dark sides and the shadow will become completely black.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. The picture's getting a little grainy now. You might go ahead and open up the of-stop.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Landing point is just barely in the darkness. That one crater, the upper part of which you see, lower part completely in darkness. The small, well-defined crater is Moltke, which is about abeam of the landing sight.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We can just see; it looks like a little less than half of its rim right now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we can make out just barely some features on the surface, maybe from earthshine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Are you wide open on the of-stop at this time?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes, we are.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. And it looks like we're just about to get the Sun coming into the lens, so we'll have to move the camera away.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We can't see any earthshine or any surface features at all in earthshine now due to the fact that the IM is very bright and is causing our pupils to contract. It's a very fantastic view to see the terminator as you look along the edge of it. I think you'll agree that some of these craters that you're seeing in the picture now are really accentuated by the lengthening of the shadows as they come close to the terminator.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes. It's a very beautiful and a rugged sight that we've got on the screen now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And I think you've got some interesting data on thruster firing versus pitch angle. It looks
like that LM just wants to head down towards the surface, is all.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I have a comment here that says that's
I believe!
blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.text: And as the Moon sinks slowly in the west, Apollo 11 bids good day to you.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. We sort of thought it was the Sun setting in the east.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, it depends on your point of view.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. When you're ready to copy, I have an LOI-2 PAD and a TEI-5 PAD. Over.
Okay. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'm in REACQ and NARROW now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Also, that water that you got on the aft bulkhead, we - If it's not too much, we just recommend sopping it up and then throwing the sponges away in the waste stowage area. If it's too much, then we recommend using the procedure in the checklist on page F10-14. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Would you have Buzz make sure he gives us the OPS pressure readings before you close up? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Will do.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, 11. The OPS read 5750, both bottles.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
BEGIN LUNAR REV 5

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Roger. Reading you fine, and it looks like the automatic REACQ went very well just as soon as you came around the limb. We have several small items to discuss with you here just before you go to sleep. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. First of all, on our IM systems checks, everything went fine. I would like to remind you, though, tomorrow you may see an ascent pressure light when you activate the MC&W. There should be no problem, however. You did note that the APS AUX tank pressure was only reading 111 psi, which is normal at this point, but below the level which will trigger your light due to the helium which has been dissolved into the propellant. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand that. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And next item, the supercritical helium rise rate is nominal, and you also had that question for us about your thruster activity during the P22 on the last REV. Believe we understand that now, as you reported that your pitch was in ACCEL COMMAND and your yaw and roll were in RATE COMMAND. You were firing your pitch thrusters. This will couple rates into your yaw and roll axes, and the - You were at that time holding only half a degree dead-band and coupling rates into yaw and roll produced the extra firings about the yaw and roll axes. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. That may be true. It's very peculiar coupling, in that it waits longer than you would think and its reaction is greater than you would think. We were getting yaw rates of around four-tenths of a degree per second, for example.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We did play the data back, and that's the way it looked upon analysis of the chart recordings back here. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: They've also looked at the results of your landmark tracking. The marks all apparently were very good, and we've got a full page of data here relative to the altitudes of the various site locations, which I won't read up to you, but I did want to let you know that the marks apparently went very well. I also have your consumable budgets, particularly your RCS propellant quantities. They're Deltas from nominal if you should want them. Your worst quad is quad Charlie, which is 9 percent low. I'll not read up the others unless you want them. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. How about the O2 fuel cell purge? You want that now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I'll have to stand by just a moment.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. And then the other one is, we're still charging battery A.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We would like to delay the fuel cell purge until the backside of the Moon, and you go ahead and - should terminate your battery charge at this time. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Understand. I knew we had another O2 and H2 purge coming up in the morning; I wasn't sure whether you wanted to go through with this one or not. I'll wait until the next side and then do it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's fine, Buzz.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Terminate battery charging now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's right, and one other systems item here - in order to balance your CRYO tanks, would you get your heaters off? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I have

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's right, Mike, and we believe you have your quad Bravo and quad Charlie turned off in your DAP at this time, and a 5-degree deadband. We'd prefer a 10-degree deadband for your sleep period overnight here. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: One other item relative to a malfunction procedure. It's unlikely that you'll have to worry about this

tomorrow, but in your malfunction list under docking a high O2 flow rate at the top of - under tunnel at use that malfunction procedure should you encounter the high O2 flow rate, and instead, check back with Houston for a revised procedure should you find that situation. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Understand, and note has been made in my checklist.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Roger. That just about takes care of all the items we have here on the ground before time to hit the sack, and I guess you will have a presleep check for us before you go to bed.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. We're in the midst of cycling the O2 and H2 fans now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And the radiation is as follows: CDR 11012, CMP 10013, LMP 09015. Negative medication. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy, 11.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. We're thinking about taking the monocular with us on into the IM. We think it m got prove to be of some use. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. It sounds like a good idea for some of your surveying work there inside the cockpit. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. You want to run that by with whoever might be concerned?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I sure will.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We have apparently lost the high gain lock. We would appreciate it if you would give us a help manually to try to relock up on the high gain. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Reading you very weak, still too far down in the noise to complete the full transmission. If you'd give us a hand on a manual relock, we'd appreciate it.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We're still unable to pick you up on the high gain antenna. Request you go to MANUAL, and wide beamwidth. The pitch and yaw angles in your checklist are good ones. You should be able to find us there. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How do you read now?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Loud and clear this time. How me?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Loud and clear. You faded out on your last transmission. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Are you in wide beam now?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Negative. I got you locked back on again REACQ and narrow.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's all we want. We want to stay in narrow, and we're a little puzzled about why we lost you here a few minutes ago. Do you have any ideas?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No, we sure don't (cough) - sure don't. We're showing - we're showing about 15 degrees plus pitch and about 270. That ought to be good and clear.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We concur there. We still don't have any good ideas on why we were lost then.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Would you confirm that we did acquire automatically when you came around the limb for this passage. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That's confirmed.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. On your AUTO RCS SELECT switches, we show quad Bravo disabled but quad Charlie only partially disabled. Charlie 3, I believe, is the only one you have selected off. Is that correct?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. Roger. That's correct.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How do they look to you now, Houston?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We see them all disabled at this time. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We're going to try to check out this ability to automatically reacquire on the Is-band, and what we want to do is to secure our uplink carrier for about 30 seconds. Then we will turn it back on and see if the spacecraft equipment will automatically reacquire. So if you do not get a call from us within about 3 minutes, that means we have not been able to reacquire and request your assistance on a manual acquisition. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We understand.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We also would appreciate - if you will note the angles that the antenna tracks through in its attempt to reacquire. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. We'll do that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. It looks like we're locked back up again with no delay. How does it look on board? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. The signal strength dropped very rapidly to zero, and the pitch and yaw, in about 3 seconds, moved toward 40 degrees pitch and 240 degrees yaw. Right now, they're sitting on about 15 degrees pitch and about 265 degrees yaw. So they didn't move very far, about 50 degrees apiece; and then they picked right back on up again. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Some of "The Luckiest People" in the background there. We copied your pitch and yaw angles.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Could you give us the location of your - pitch and yaw location of your position indicators? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. They're in the same position as the antenna right now; plus 15 degrees pitch and - no, now wait a minute. I got them - got it at about 275 instead of 265.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We'd like to try the same procedure once more. We'll leave the carrier a little longer and be back up for a call within 4 minutes. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We're locked back up again. Can you give us a report on how the antenna behaved?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. It was essentially identical as before. The pitch went to 45, 40 to 45 and the yaw went to about - to about 255, 245 to 255; and then it rather quickly locked up at 15 degrees pitch and 270 yaw. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Roger. Your angles are 45 and 255. Do I understand that as soon as the carrier dropped, it went to these angles, or did it only go to these angles after the uplink carrier was reenabled and the antenna began to reacquire? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No. As soon as the carrier dropped off, why, it drifted over into those angles and stayed there. Then when it came back up again, why, it hunted around for a while, but it didn't get any further off. Gradually brought it on in to the angles where it is right now; and then the signal strength would take several jumps as evidently it goes from wide to medium to narrow. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Understand. And on another subject, request you zero your optics for the night. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Zeroed.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Can you confirm that you have changed the CO2 filter as per flight plan in the last hour? Over?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: No. We're still eating. We're about to do it. We'll let you know.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. And we've got about 14 minutes until LOS. AOS is 86 30, an hour away. We're wondering whether or not you plan to have one man up at that time or would you all like to be asleep inside the next hour? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Somebody will be up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. The thing that we're still puzzling on is the antenna, and if - as long as there will be somebody up, why, we would like to have somebody check the automatic REACQ on the next AOS.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We'll do that. We haven't chlorinated the water yet, and we haven't changed the lithium hydroxide. We're just still finishing up dinner.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We have LOS coming up in 2 minutes now, and AOS will be at 86 plus 28 plus 15.0 Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We'll see you on the other side, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Loud and clear here. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We just appeared to get a solid lock for the last - oh, about a minute. The ... needle's been wandering up and down, and the pitch and yaw needles have been wandering around, but it appears to have reacquired by itself solidly now. We're just finishing up our fuel cell purge. Hydrogen on number 3 is the last to go off. It'll be coming off in just a second.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. We believe we've tracked down the reacquisition problem we had on the previous REV. It looks like it was a receiver power supply here on the ground and no problems in the spacecraft at all. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Glad to hear it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, that really winds things up as far as we're concerned on the ground, for the evening. We're ready to go to bed and get a little sleep. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. We're about to join you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
END OF TAPE

blocks.text: Roger. The "Black Bugle" just arrived with some morning news briefs if you're ready.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Church services around the world today are mentioning Apollo 11 in their prayers. President Nixon's worship service at the White House is also dedicated to the mission, and our fellow astronaut, Frank Borman, is still in there pitching and will read the passage from Genesis which was read on Apollo 8 last Christmas. The Cabinet and members of Congress, with emphasis on the Senate and House space committees, have been invited, along with a number of other guests. Buzz, your son, Andy, got a tour of MSC yesterday. Your Uncle Bob Moon accompanied him on the visit which included the LRL. Among the --

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: -- Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Among the large headlines concerning Apollo this morning, there's one asking that you watch for a lovely girl with a big rabbit. An ancient legend says a beautiful Chinese girl called Chang-to has been living there for 4000 years. It seems she was banished to the Moon because she stole the pill of immortality from her husband. You might also look for her companion, a large Chinese rabbit, who is easy to spot since he is always standing on his hind feet in the shade of a cinnamon tree. The name of the rabbit is not reported.
Okay. We'll keep a close eye out for the bunny girl.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. You residents of the spacecraft Columbia may be interested in knowing that today is Independence Day in the country of Colombia. Gloria Diaz of the Philippines was crowned Miss Universe last night. She defeated 60 other girls for the global beauty title. Miss Diaz is 18, with black hair and eyes, and measures , 34-1/2. First runner-cup was Miss Australia, followed by Miss Israel, and Miss Japan. While you're on your way back Tuesday night, the American and

National League Allstars will be playing ball in Washington. Mel Stottlemyre of the Yankees is expected to be the American League's first pitcher. No one is predicting who will be first pitcher for the National League yet. They have nine on the roster. Even though research has certainly paid off in the space program, research doesn't always pay off, it seems. The Woodstream Corporation, parent company of the Animal Trap Company of America which has made more than a billion wooden spring mousetraps, reports that it built a better mousetrap but the world didn't beat a door to its path - didn't beat a path to its door. As a matter of fact, the company had to go back to the oldfashioned kind. They said, "We should have spent more time researching housewives and less time researching mice". And the "Black Beag - Bugle" is all completed for the morning.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you very much. We appreciate the news.
Black Team, we'll be looking for an interesting day with you all tomorrow.
blocks.speaker: LMP
CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll be going off here shortly, and we'll pick you up in the morning for sure.

blocks.text: Roger. I guess that takes care of the news for today, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right. Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You might be interested in knowing, Mike, that we have gotten reflections back from the laser reflector ray they deployed, and we may be able to get some information out of that a little later.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. I need a very precise position, because I can only do a decent job of scanning maybe one
of those grid squares at a time. The area that we've been sweeping covers 10's and 20's and 30's of them.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We understand. This is intended to be your last P22. We don't want to use up too much fuel in this effort. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. How's the fuel coming?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. There's no problem fuel-wise. It's just that there seems to be a limit to the number of P22's and the number of grid squares you can search over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Well, I'll continue this maneuver then to roll 82, pitch 218, yaw zero, if that's okay with you, and do a P52 in that attitude. And that'll be a sleep ...

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's fine with us. And P52 in that attitude.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. A P52 and then the sleep attitude.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility Base. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. When you all have a free moment, I have your T8 through P12 block data. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility Base. Ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Readback correct. Houston out.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston. Columbia.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Columbia on high gain.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility Base.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia. Columbia, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Columbia in the high gain.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Reading you loud and clear on the high gain, Columbia.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Going to P52 attitude. You want a crew status report?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again, Columbia?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I say again, I am maneuvering to the P52 attitude, and do you want a crew status report?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And go ahead with your crew status report.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. No medication. Radiation 100.16.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Houston. We copy.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility Base.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, Tranquility.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. The weight of the RCU was 12 ounces. That was by itself without the bag, and the weight of the water from the CDR's PLSS was 12-1/2 ounces. That's reading zero with the bag on.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. We copy. And, for your information, the new LM weight after jettison of equipment including lithium hydroxide canister is 10837. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Columbia. Did you copy the P52?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, this is Houston. Affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. In the flight plan configuration, we show that the stability control circuit breaker ATCA on panel 16 should be open at this time. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility. Say again which one should be closed?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Panel 16, row 2, STAB control ATCA, that is At-To-Cc-At, and it should be open at this time. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Coming open.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Housquin - Houston, Tranquility. Do you have a way of showing the configuration of the engine arm circuit breaker? Over. The reason I'm asking is because the end of it appears to be broken off. I think we can push it back in again. I'm not sure we could pull it out if we pushed it in, though. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We copy. Stand by please.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Our telemetry shows the engine arm circuit breaker in the OPEN position at the present time. We want you to leave it open until it is nominally scheduled to be pushed in, which is later on. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility Base. The CDR's FRED reads 11014.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. 11014 for the CDR.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. LMP reads 09018. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. 09018.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Columbia. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, this is Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Bruce. When you get a few minutes could you give me some words on tomorrow's activities - when they're going to start?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, Columbia, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. Couple of quick flight plan updates here. First off, we'd like to get an O2 fuel cell purge at time 113 30. You - Are you copying? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. And copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Secondly, we will return to the nominal timeline with your scheduled wakeup of 121 hours and 12 minutes. We sort of slipped by lithium hydroxide canister change number 9 during the EVA and EVA PREP. We'd like you to accomplish that now. The COMM for sleep will be the normal lunar COMM configuration, the RCS configuration. We're requesting you use quads Alfa and Bravo. A DAP data load for R2 should be 01111. Readback. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Oxygen fuel cell purge at 113 30. Return to the nominal timeline at 121 hours wakeup. Lithium hydroxide change number 9 right now. Normal lunar COMM sleep configuration, I'm in that now. On the RCS, I understood before you wanted to load the DAP register 2 011000 which made sense, and then later to pitch only
on quad A, enable all on quad B, and C and D off. But you don't want to do that any more, huh?
Columbia. This is Houston. On your DAP loud in R2, we're requesting a 0 and four 1's, that is, 01111. Over.
blocks.speaker: CC
CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And you --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Load's going in right now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And you'll be enabling quads Alfa and Bravo on the AUTO RCS select switches. Disable Charlie and Delta.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we have a little less than 2 minutes to LOS. If you're still up, AOS next time around will be 114 04. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, Columbia, if it's agreeable with you, we'd like you to stay awake until we have one successful reacquisition on the high-gain antenna. And I guess you can plan on turning in shortly after AOS this next pass. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Radio check. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead. Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Reading you loud and clear. Just wanted to make sure we still had COMM.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. We just finished up - we're just finishing up our eat period. Be ready to go back into PREP for DEPRESS.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.
BEGIN LUNAR REV 20

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. On your next depressurization, it's acceptable to use the overhead hatch dump valve in addition to or instead of the forward hatch dump valve to speed up the depressurization of the cabin. I have a P13 update for you, and if you could, sometime here, give us P00 and DATA. we'll uplink you a new CSM state vector. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: All right.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: You've got the DSKY.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Your P13 time is 124 22 02. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. It's P13, 124 22 - is that 02? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative. That is 02. And do you have a time estimate for us until you're ready to start cabin DEPRESS? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Fifteen minutes, maybe?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Uplink complete. The computer's yours, and you can go out of DATA.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead. Tranquility Base, here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Just want to let you guys know that since you're an hour and a half over your timeline and we're all taking a day off tomorrow, we're going to leave you. See you later.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I don't blame you a bit.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's a real great day, guys. I really enjoyed it.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you. You couldn't have enjoyed it as much as we did.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It was great.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sure wish you'd hurry up and get that trash out of there, though.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes. We're just about to do it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. We show the suit relief valve still in the AUTO position. It should be closed. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Columbia. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We've successfully reacquired high-gain antenna. Unless you have some other traffic with us, I guess we'll bid you a good night and let you get some sleep, Mike. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Sounds fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And we're going to power down the voice sun-carrier part of our uplink to you in order that we don't disturb you while we're talking to Tranquility Base. If you need us, just give us
a call, and we can respond with a time lag of about a minute to a minute and a half in getting reconfigured. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And good night.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Good night, Bruce. Thanks a lot.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, Columbia, this is Houston. We'd like you to ENABLE the thrusters in Bravo 1 and Bravo 2, AUTO RCS SELECT. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Bravo 1 and Bravo 2 ENABLE.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility, this is Houston. For a reference, which dump valve are you using? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We used the forward dump valve until about 2 psi, and we're using the overhead now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: They're both - they're both open now.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility Base. REPRESS complete.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Tranquility. We observed your equipment jettison on the TV, and the passive seismic experiment recorded shocks when each PLSS hit the surface. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You can't get away with anything anymore, can you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: No, indeed.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And of course, when you get ready to turn in, go back into caution and warning, ENABLE, and we'd like to say from all of us down here in Houston and really from all of us in all the countries and in the entire world, we think that you've done a magnificent job up there today. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you very much.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: It's been a long day.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes, indeed. Get some rest there and have at it tomorrow.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Tranquility. Did you all come up with any other solution that we might try to the mission timer problem? Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by, Tranquility. We'll be back with you in just a minute.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: And, Houston, Tranquility. Have you had enough TV for today?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility, this is Houston. Yes, indeed. It's been a mighty fine presentation there.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Signing off. See you again tomorrow.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, Columbia, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Sorry to bother you, Columbia. Two things: we request that you select 10-degree deadband in your DAP in accordance with the procedures on For to 9-7 in your checklist; and secondly, we'd like to leave a display on the DSKY that is not one that's cycling, being continuously updated. What you have when you get through widening the deadband will be a static display, and that'll be satisfactory. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Goodnight again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. On your mission timer, we wanted to pull the circuit breaker and let it cool down for an hour and a half to 2 hours. I believe the breaker is currently open. It has been off, so go ahead and reset the mission timer circuit breaker. Put the timer control to RESET and hold it in RESET for 30 seconds, and then slew it to your desired settings left to right, and place the timer control to START. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We'll try it.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, our mission timer seems to be slewing okay. You want to give us a time hack? Or can we get it off the CMC - LGC, I mean?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Tranquility. I'll give you a time hack at 114 31 00. It's about 30 seconds from now. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by for a Mark at 114 31.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. ... you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: MARK.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility, this is Houston. Did you copy my Mark at 114 31?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you, and our mission timer is running now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Very good. And, I've got a consumables update for you if you're ready to copy or listen. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. RCS Alfa is 81 percent, RCS Bravo 75 percent. Coming up on 115 hours GET, descent oxygen is 31.8 pounds or 59 percent; descent amp hours 858, and ascent amp hours 574. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. Thank you very much.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility, this is Houston. We also have a set of about 10 questions relating to observations you made, things you may have seen during the EVA. You can either discuss a little later on this evening or sometime later in the mission at your option. How do you feel? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I guess we can take them up now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. And your friendly Green Team here has pretty well been relieved by your friendly Maroon Team, and I'll put Owen on with the questions.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility -

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you, Bruce. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility, Houston. First question here is how your best estimate of the yaw on the - of the LM as compared to the nominal preflight plan. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: We got 13 degrees left on the ball, and I think that's probably about right. Looking at the shadow and so on, we prob - probably about 13 degrees left of the shadow.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's 13 degrees left of the shadow. And, next question relates to the depth of the bulk sampling that you obtained near the first part of the EVA and any changes in composition that you might have observed during the bulk sampling interval. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I'm not sure I understand that question, but we got a good bit of the ground mass in the bulk sample plus a sizable number of selected rock fragments of different types.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. One of the implications here is the depth from which the bulk sample was collected. Did you manage to get down there several inches or nearer the surface? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We got some down from as much as 3 inches in the area where I was looking at variation with depth in the bulk sample. There really wasn't appreciable difference, and I didn't run into any hard bed. Later on, or at some other times and other areas, why, I'd get down just a short distance, an inch or two, and couldn't go any further.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Believe we understand down as deep as 3 inches, did not hit any hard bed, and no significant changes in composition to that depth. Next question, the - the second SRC was packed rather hurriedly due to the time limitation, and wonder if you would be able to provide any more detailed description of the samples which were included in the second SRC. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We got two core tubes and solar wind and about half of the big sample bag full of assorted rocks which I picked up hurriedly from around the area. I tried to get as many representative types as I could.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Neil. Next topic here relates to the rays which emanate from the DPS engine burning area. We're wondering if the rays emanating from the - beneath the engine are any darker or lighter than the surrounding surface. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: The ones that I saw back in the aft end of the spacecraft appeared to be a good bit darker; of course, viewed from the aft end, why, they did have the Sun shining directly on them. It seemed as though the material had been baked somewhat and also scattered in a radially outward direction, but in that particular area, this feature didn't extend more than about 2, maybe 3 feet, from the skirt of the engine. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Understand that near the aft end out to the east that the rays did appear darker. I understand, Buzz, that these were - this was the appearance of the material which had been uncovered by the rays that appeared darker for 2 or 3 feet extending outward. Is that correct?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No. I wouldn't say it was necessarily material that had been uncovered. I think some of the material might have been baked or in some way caused to be more cohesive and perhaps flow together in some way, I don't know. Now, in other areas, before we started trampling around out front, why, we could see that small erosion had taken place in a radially outward direction, but it had left no significant mark on the surface other than just having eroded it away. Now, it was different back in the - right under the skirt itself. It seems as though the surface had been baked in a streak fashion, and I think a couple of pictures on film will show this. But that didn't extend out very far. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Tranquility. And this baked appearance that you described, at least the suggestion is that it was due to the heat of the engine at any rate. Next subject, did -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I believe so.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Next subject, did either of the solar panels on the PSE touch the surface of the Moon during deployment? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I think that two corners did touch, since when it was deployed, both of them didn't come out at the same time. It unfolded a little unevenly, and of course, the terrain that it was on was a little bit - not quite as level as it was - as I would like to have it. And I think that two corners did touch to about 1 inch - no, three-quarters to a half an inch deep; and maybe along the bottom, it might have been maybe 3 inches, leaving a small triangular coating on two of the corners; and I think these are on the western ones. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Understand the description there. And the next subject, on the two core tubes which you collected, how did the driving force required to collect these tubes compare? Was there any difference? Over

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Not significantly. I could get down to about the first 2 inches without much of a problem, and then as I would pound it in about as hard as I could do it, and the second one took two hands on the hammer, and I was putting pretty good dents in the top of the extension rod, and it just wouldn't go much more than - I think the total depth might have been about 8 or 9 inches. But even there, it didn't - For some reason it didn't seem to want to stand up straight. In other words, I'd keep driving it in and it would dig some sort of a hole but it wouldn't - just penetrate in a way that would support it and keep it from falling over, if that makes any sense at all. It didn't really to me. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Buzz. I think I've got the picture. You indicate that little difference between the two samples and that in each case you got down about 2 inches without any problems and then had to continue hammering rather vigorously in order to continue driving it in to a total depth of 8 or 9 inches, and even at that point the rods did not want to stay vertical, that they'd tend to fall over on you even after pounding in that far. Is that correct?

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. That's about it. It wasn't a rapid change in resistive force. And also I noticed when I took the bit off that the material was quite well packed, a good bit darker, and it - The way it adhered to the core tube gave me the distinct impression of being moist. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Understand the general impression of being moist as it packed in the core tube. Next question: we did copy your comments prior to the EVA of your general description of the area. We wonder if either of you would have any more lengthy description or more detailed description of the general summary of the geology of the area. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes let's - we'll - We'll postpone our answer to that one until tomorrow. Okay?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes, indeed. That'll be fine. Just a couple more here, and I think these may not be quite as lengthy as number 7 there. Can you estimate the stroke of the primary and secondary struts? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Well, I could do it like this, Owen. About all the struts are about equally stroked, and the height from the ground to the first step is about feet, huh?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Understand, Neil. Next topic, as - just after landing, you pointed out that there was a hill to the west along the plus-Vz axis from the LM. Are there any large rocks in that direction that might block the solar ray during the sunset - as sunset approaches in your locality - Are there any large rocks that might tend to obscure the ray? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: No. I don't believe so. I think that it's - It's about as level as any other areas that we chose.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I -

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: There's nothing large, anyway, that's going to get in the way.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. That's also the way it appeared from the television, I think. And now the final question. You commented, Neil, that on your approach to the landing spot, you had passed over a football field-sized crater containing rather large blocks of solid rock perhaps 10 to 15 feet in size. Can you estimate the distance to this football-sized crater from your present position? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I thought we'd be close enough so that when we got outside we could see it rim back there, but I couldn't. But I don't think that we're more than a half mile beyond it. That is, a half mile west of it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. So you estimate your present position less than half a mile approximately west of this large crater. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's correct.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Well, that takes care of the questions from our geologists for tonight, and unless you have something else, that'll be all for - from us for the evening. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, Houston. We've now collected all the ranging data that we can use, and you can go back to caution and warning ENABLE. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Will do.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility Base, Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Two more verifications, here. Can you - will you verify that the disk with messages was placed on the surface as planned, and also that the items listed in the flight plan - all of those listed there were jettisoned. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That's - All that's verified.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you, and I hope this will be a final good night.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.
END OF TAPE
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS
AIR-TO-GROUND VOICE TRANSCRIPTION

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, Columbia, good morning from Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Hi, Ron.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, Mike, how's it going this morning?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How goes it?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, real fine. While you're --

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I don't know yet, how's it going with you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Real fine here. Columbia, request POOR and ACCEPT. We'll shove the state vector in for you right away.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. It's coming up now, Columbia. We're going to keep you a little busy here. As soon as we get the state vector in, we'd like you to go ahead and do a P52 option 3 on this night pass, and then when you come on around the other side there, we'll give you some landmark tracking information on prime 130.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And, Houston, Tranquility Base is going to give you a few comments with regard to the geology question of last night. We are landed in a relatively smooth crater field of elongate secondary - circular secondary craters, most of which have rims irrespective of their - raised rims irrespective of their size. That's not universally true. There are - There are a few of the smaller craters around which do not have a discernable rim. The ground mass throughout the area is a very fine sand to a silt. I'd say the thing that would be most like it on Earth is powdered graphite. Immersed in this ground mass are a wide variety of rock shapes, sizes, textures, rounded and angular, many with varying consistencies. As I said, I've seen plain - what looked to be plain basalt and vesicular basalt. Others with no crystals, some with small white phenocrysts, maybe one to less than 5 percent. And the bould - we are in a boulder field where the boulders range generally up to 2 feet with a few larger than that. Now, some of the boulders are lying on top of the surface, some are partially exposed, and some are just barely exposed. And in our traverse around on the surface and particularly working with the scoop, we've run into boulders below the surface - it was probably buried under several inches of the ground mass.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Tranquility, Houston. Roger. Very fine description.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I suspect this boulder field may have some of its origin with this large sharp-edged rocky rim crater that we passed over at final descent. Now yesterday I said that was about the size of a football field, and I have to admit it was a little - little hard to measure coming in. But I thought that it might just fit in the Astrodome as we came by it. And the rocks in the vicinity of the - of this rocky rim crater are much larger than these in this area. Some are 10 feet or so and perhaps bigger, and they are very thickly populated out to about one crater diameter beyond the crater rim. Beyond that, there is some diminishing, and even out in this area the blocks seem to run out in rows with irregular patterns, and then there are paths between them where there are considerably less surface evidence of hard rocks. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: And I thought I'd just take about 5 seconds here and see if I could get 000 gone, since we're fairly close to gimbal lock right now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Eagle, Houston. That's fine.

blocks.text: Columbia and Eagle, Houston. About 5 minutes to LOS. Your IM jet time will be 131 plus 52, and I have the rest of the maneuver PAD if you want it now, or I can give it to you on the next time around.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Columbia, Houston. It looks like you guys are so speedy on us that we're thinking about moving up jettison time to about a GET of 130 plus 30, if that's okay with you all. Over.

blocks.text: Roger. We want to talk to you about that. Mike, we can - for your druthers, we can do it either way. We can either let you do it in the jettison in P30 - correction P47, or we can send you a P30 target load up and then you - let you call P41, whichever you want to do. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Looks like it's going to be pretty relaxed time here for the next couple of hours. We'll have you a PAD, of course, the next REV or so, and we'll keep you posted on TEI. Looks like nominal time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you, Charlie.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And your little maneuver back here a moment ago will put you about 20 miles ahead of the LM at TEI.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Imagine that place has cleared out a little bit after that rendezvous. You can find a place to sit down almost, huh?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Our MOCR's about empty right now. We're taking it a little easy. How does it feel up there to have some company?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Damn good, I'll tell you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: I'll bet. I bet, you'd almost be talking to yourself up there after 10 REVS or so.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Well, they were with you in spirit.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Let them see what they're getting for their money.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Well, they were with you in spirit anyway, at least that many. We heard on the news today, 11, that last night - yesterday after you made your landing, New York Times came out with a - headlines, the largest headlines they've ever used in the history of the newspaper.

blocks.speaker: CMP

blocks.speaker: CDR

blocks.text: It was great.
