blocks.text: Roger. Apparently it pays to hurry.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I usually do.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The visibility through the telescope has been very poor. It's, I would say, even worse than the simulator is right now. It requires long periods of dark adaptation which most times are most inconvenient; so it's really a tremendous asset to keep the platform powered up at all times and to keep it tweaked within the capability of the sextant field of view

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Understand, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Checking your temperature sure, it does look like the spacecraft may have cooled down perhaps 2 or 3 degrees in the last 24 hours, and that sounds to be consists with your report on the comm rt leave the. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Is that lmp-off phenomenon?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. It looks like we'll have to think a little more about that, as to whether it's lmp-off or some effect of being out of Lunar orbit. We don't know, so we'll have to puzzle before we can give a better answer.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, if the systems guys have anything they want chased down, we'll be happy to give you any readings or reports or what have you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll think about that and see if there aren't some other tests to be usefully performed here.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. I'll be turning things over to the Green CAP COMM at this time, and see you on the ground tomorrow.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Owen. I want to thank you and the whole Purple/Maroon group there for a good job helping Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thank you, sir.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Thanks from us to all of you. It was really appreciated.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Great job, you guys.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston. Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. With reference to your subjective evaluation that it felt cooler in side the spacecraft last night, we reported earlier that we did indeed see a drop of about 3 degrees over the previous night. Looking back, it appears the crew of Apollo 10 reported similar feelings during the translunar and transearth coast phases. We're wondering if you could give us any indication of the relative amounts of free or condensed water in the cabin last night and the night before from which we could infer humidity. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. That might be a little bit difficult to do. We'll take a look at the tunnel now. It does seem as though, between the last, we had a little bit more moisture in the tunnel. Of course, the LM hadn't been vented when we did translunar.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We were more curious about the relative amount of moisture between, say, last night and the night before, both of which would have the LM missing.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: There's more moisture in the tunnel now than there has been at any previous time. Subjectively we have been unable to determine any change in - any buildup in humidity. There appears to be no moisture any other place in the spacecraft. For example, the windows are not fogging or - and various other cool spots around the spacecraft - all of them appear to be completely dry.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How are all the "Greens" today, Bruce?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, the Greens are in good shape. The actual Green Team has been here for several hours. We're dogging the watch down here to position Ron for entry. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Understand. Did Dave Reed get to explain the lunar ... at the press conference?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: No, but your comments about Bill Shaffer and the explanations were quoted in the paper last night.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Oh, oh.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Do you want to say anything more while you're on the line?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: He's right. He's absolutely right.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How's old White, Bruce? Did he ever let you go get a cup of coffee when we were over on the back side?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, things have been going pretty smoothly down here. He's really not that hard to get along with.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Oh, he must be mellowing.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: We've only got two of them back here right now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: He always used to make me sit at the console through the back-side passes, just for training.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, the word we have here is - that was because whenever you came back, you had to be retrained.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Touch.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Out of curiosity, on those 70-mm cameras, we figure we exposed around 300 in the IM and around a thousand in the command module; and both cameras - or all the 70-mm cameras worked just fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Very good. Thank you.
END OF TAPE
Apollo 11, this is Houston Over.
blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.
blocks.speaker: CMP
CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Do you all have 'Change Lima" for your entry operations check.st dated July 23?  Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Dated when?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: July 23.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: I'm not sure that we hung around long enough to pick that one up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. If you've got the entry operations checklist handy, then I'll pass it up to you.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: How can you make changes after lift-to??

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You sure you don't mean June?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative. It just came up today. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: So, you're the first to get to us. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. On page 6-1 of the entry-out checklist down toward the bottom after "MAIN DEPLOY pushbutton," we have three additional steps we'd like you to accomplish.  The intent of this is to reduce the oxygen pressure in your manifold and to eliminate the oxygen bleed flow through the potable and waste-water tanks during descent. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We've got 6-1 out. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Down at the bottom, you've got "10 000 feet MAIN PARACHUTE DEPLOY, MAIN DEPLOY pushbutton, PUSH within 1 second."  And after that step, we'd like you insert "SURGE TANK O2 valve, OFF, RE- PRESS PACKAGE valve, OFF, and DIRECT O2 valve, OPEN."  Do you copy?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Down at the bottom, after "MAIN DEPLOY pushbutton, PUSH; SURGE TANK O2, OFF; and RE- PRESS PACKAGE VALVE, OFF, DIRECT O2, O1."  Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And then down at the very bottom of page 6-2 where you see "DIRECT O2, OFF VERIFY," delete that step completely. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And for record purposes, this will be "Change Lima." Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. We've got it. How far open do you want this the DIRECT O2 valve to be opened at this point? I guess you want it - just leave it open from that point on?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It should go all the way open, and you can just leave it on from that point on. The intent is to completely depressurize the oxygen manifold. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. For your information the All Star game has just ended with the National League winning 9 to 3 over American. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And I have a message here for Mike that says "All the chinch bugs are gone." Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Having done their job I guess.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Well, along with one tree, it turns out.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. I heard about that. That was right before the flight.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Right. That big storm.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Are you still up there? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Yes, we are. But not quite so far as we were a while ago.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We concur. We just wanted to make sure that we had good COMM with you.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Trace 113/2

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: For general information, 11, you are now 95 970 miles out from the Earth. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Right in our own back yard.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Right in our own back yard.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger that.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Trying to come down hill a little bit now. What's our velocity?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Your velocity is 5991 feet per second.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And you are indeed coming down hill.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: (Go ahead, Houston.)

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. I've got a flight plan update for you to give you an optimum attitude for the Earth in the number 1 window and the Moon in number 5 window.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Your attitude will be roll 12 degrees, pitch 270 degrees, yaw 0 degrees.  High-gain antenna angles, pitch plus 14, yaw 263.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. I copy. Roll 012, pitch 270, yaw 0. High-gain antenna, pitch plus 14 and yaw 263.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And when coming out of PTC, you might be advised that your deadband has been collapsed, so follow the checklist items.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're receiving a black signal from you right now, but we are getting TV.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: From signal strength indications, it appears that we may be locked up on a side lobe with high-gain antenna.  We'd like you to go into wide bandwidth for about 15 seconds and then back to narrow.  Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You have good Is-band signal strength now, Houston?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You all set for TV?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We're all set whenever you're ready to send.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. You're coming through loud and clear now, 11, with your patch.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Good evening. This is the Commander of Apollo 11. A hundred years ago, Jules Verne wrote a book about a voyage to the Moon. His spaceship, Columbia, took off from Florida and landed in the Pacific Ocean after completing a trip to the Moon. It seems appropriate to us to share with you some of the reflections of the crew as the modern-day Columbia completes its rendezvous with the planet Earth and the same Pacific Ocean tomorrow. First, Mike Collins.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We have an LOS here.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We'll be right back with you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: In the interim, you may be interested in knowing that Jan and the children and Pat and the youngsters and Andy Aldrin are down here in the viewing room watching this evening.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We're glad to hear that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. You're back on, with Mike in the middle of the screen there.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. This trip of ours to the Moon may have looked, to you, simple or easy. I'd like to assure you that has not been the case. The Saturn V rocket which put us into orbit is an incredibly complicated piece of machinery, every piece of which worked flawlessly. This computer up above my head has a 38 000-word vocabulary, each word of which has been very carefully chosen to be of the utmost value to us, the crew. This switch which I have in my hand now, has over 300 counterparts in the command module alone, this one single switch design. In add tone to that, there are myriads of circuit breakers, levers, rods, and other associated cone rolls. The SPS engine, our large rocket engine on the aft end of our service module, must have perform red flawlessly, or we would have been stranded in lunar orbit. The parachutes up above my head must work perfectly tomorrow or we will plummet into the

ocean. We have always had confidence that all this equipment will work, and work properly, and we continue to have confidence that it will do so for the remainder of the flight. All this is possible only through the blood, sweat, and tears of a number of people. First, the American workmen who put these pieces of machinery together in the factory. Second, the painstaking work done by the various test teams during the assembly and retest after assembly. And finally, the people at the Manned Spacecraft Center, both in management, in mission planning, in flight control, and last, but not least, in crew training. This operation is somewhat like the periscope of a submarine. All you see is the three of us, but beneath the surface are thousands and thousands of others, and to all those, I would like to say, thank you very much.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're getting a good picture of Buzz now, but no voice modulation. And would you open up the of-stop on the TV camera; try 22, please?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That appears to be a lot better now. We're still not receiving Buzz's audio.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Good evening. I'd like to discuss with you a few of the more symbolic aspects of the flight of our mission, Apollo 11. As we've been discussing the events that have taken place in the past 2 or 3 days here on board our spacecraft, we've come to the conclusion that this has been far more than three men on a voyage to the Moon, more, still, than the efforts of a government and industry team, more, even, than the efforts of one nation. We feel that this stands as a symbol of the insatiable curiosity of all mankind to explore the unknown. Neil's statement the other day upon first setting foot on the surface of the Moon, "This is a small step for a man, but a great leap for mankind," I believe sums up these feelings very nicely. We accepted the challenge of going to the Moon, the acceptance of this challenge was inevitable. The relative ease with which we carried out our mission, I believe, is a tribute to the timeliness of that acceptance. Today, I feel we're fully capable of accepting expanded roles in the exploration of space. In retrospect, we have all been particularly pleased with the call signs that we very laboriously

chose for our spacecraft, Columbia and Eagle. We've been particularly pleased with the emblem of our flight, depicting the U.S. eagle bringing the universal symbol of peace from the Earth, from the planet Earth to the Moon; that symbol being the olive branch. It was our overall crew choice to deposit a replica of this symbol on the Moon. Personally, in reflecting on the events of the past several days, a verse from Psalms comes to mind to me. "When I consider the heavens, the work of Thy fingers, the moon and the stars which Thou hast ordained, what is man that Thou art mindful of him."

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: The responsibility for this flight lies first with history and with the giants of science who have preceded this effort, next with the American people, who have through their will, indicated their desire, next, to four administrations, and their Congresses, for implementing that will, and then, to the agency and industry teams that built our spacecraft the Saturn, the Columbia, the Eagle, and the little EMU, the space suit and backpack that was our small spacecraft out on the lunar surface. We would like to give a special thanks to all those Americans who built the spacecraft, who did the construction, design, the tests, and put their - their heart; and all their abilities into those crafts. To those people, tonight, we give a special thank you, and to all the other people that are listening and watching tonight, God bless you. Good night from Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. We're getting a zoom view out the window now.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Apollo 11, signing off.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Do you want to crank up PTC again, do you have some reason to hold its attitude, or what's your pleasure?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: You can crank up PTC again, Mike, any time you like. And I might add I thought that was a mighty fine TV presentation. There's certainly nothing I can add to it from down here

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. I've got a few small items here. one flight plan update and some entry photography information, if you are ready to copy. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. At 180 hours 50 minutes GET, we should like to delete your oxygen fuel cell purge.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And on the entry photography, if you are going to use a fresh magazine of color interior film, we recommend the following exposure settings full at 1/250, six frames per second, focus on 7 feet for the fireball, 102 00 01 60 of a second, six frames per second, focus on 50 feet when the chutes open. If you are using a magazine, part of which has already been used for interior shots, we recommend f16 at 1/500 of a second, six frames per second, focus on 7 feet for the fireball; 102 08 01 60 50 feet when the parachutes open. And we would like to know the magazine number that you are intending to use if you have a chance. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. I think we got those. We will be using a fresh one and it will be color interior. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. When you get - get it out, we would like to have the number of the magazine and the letter of the magazine relayed down.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. And we're thinking that we might want to run some of that at 12 frames per second. And I think we can get everything from 00 05 00 05g down, that will only give us about 7.8 minutes and ... frames ... double that. I guess maybe just an occasional burst to 12 frames would be what we want and the rest of it at six Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. That plan sounds fine with us, Neil.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And lastly, we would like to know if your stowage configuration for entry is going to conform to
the nominal. The RETRO's down here are anxious to get an accurate c.g. computed for you, and in particular, where the LEVVA's are being stowed. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We think we are going to put the LEVVA's and helmets in the hatch bag, and we'll let you know any other nonstandard stowage locations that we complete this evening.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Houston. Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. The magazine we'll be using for entry tomorrow is magazine M. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Understand. Magazine M as in Mike.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thank you. Out.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Your friendly Green Team going off for the night, and going off for the last time. We wish to bid you a good night and Godspeed.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you. We appreciate all that fine work done by the Green Team, and we'll be thanking you in person when we get back.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll see you on the ground.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Really enjoyed working with all of you. Thanks very much. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: As usual, all you Greenies.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: They're all smiles down here, even the trench.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. How's our thruster firing activity? We're about ready to crank up PTC if you are.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, we'd like you to shift to an OMNI antenna configuration at the present time. We're requesting the Is-band antenna OMNI switch to Bravo and OMNI. The high-gain antenna track in MANUAL. Pitch minus 50, yaw 270. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. I'll do that right now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And if Mike has a minute, we'd like to do a little bit of troubleshooting. It seems he's either flat-chested or something because we've lost respiration rate on the BIOMED telemetry. That is, the ZPN trace down here is flat.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: He was shaving a little bit ago. He might have just let it slip. Hold on a moment.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All the blasted wires are all connected, is all I know.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, Mike. We had a request that you disconnect the yellow connector from the signal conditioner and verify that it looks okay, reconnect it and then, if you would, check the two electrodes that are placed one on each side of your lower rib cage. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I bet you there's a smile on Charlesworth's face

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Cliff is not on right now. Gene Kranz just relieved him a few minutes ago.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger that.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All those wires and things look normal up here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We could see variations on our traces. You've connected and disconnected, but the medics still don't have a signal.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Looks like you're sending us a message of some sort.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, I promise to let you know if I stop breathing.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Apollo 11, this is Houston broadcasting in the blind. Request OMNI Bravo. Request OMNI Bravo. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Communication reestablished.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Will you confirm you're in OMNI Bravo? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. That ought to give it to you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Out.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Mike, we're still getting a flat trace on you for the impedance pneumograph. Before you turn in this evening, you might try putting some fresh paste in the sensors, and if that doesn't work, the medics have agreed to forget about it. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Mike's off the loop right now. I'll convey that message.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Say again.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. The trace on your respiration rate is still flat. If you have time this evening before turning in, we would suggest that you try putting some fresh paste in the two electrodes that go on the side of your lower rib cage; and if that doesn't work, just give up on it.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: SC
blocks.text: (Sound of Train)

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hey, 11, this is Houston. You might tell Buzz not to exercise quite so strenuously. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: What's the problem?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: What's the problem?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. That's one - that's one on us. (Laughter)

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Seriously, that comment was just aimed at your musical selection.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: SC
blocks.text: (Sound of train)

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Come on Neil, not so fast.

blocks.speaker: SC
blocks.text: (Sound of train)

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You have an ergometer up here.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: What was that? Real time exercise?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Just trying to be your ergometer.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, this is Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: REST PERIOD - NO COMMUNICATIONS

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We're going to probably stick with the flight plan pretty much. We are going to - 1. - check the lights in the northwest corner of the U.S.
and southwest corner of Canada. If we can see up that high into the northern hemisphere. Other than that, we'll be on the flight plan.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. For your information, the laser from McDonald Observatory in West Texas will be up from about 181 hours and 30 minutes, on for 1 hour. You should be able to spot the earth out of the number 1 window every time you pass roll 357 degrees and then, of course, you're in West Texas. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: How about the number 5 window?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Stand by a minute.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. For the number 5 window. That'll be - every time you pass 230 degrees in roll.. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Beautiful. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You guys are on your toes down there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. --

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You have a new, new star chart. You must Huh?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Oh, we got a fresh, fresh FAO here.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. How much longer do you want us to keep charging battery B?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. Nominally we're looking for about another hour and a half, but what we'd like to do is continue charging until shortly before you turn in for the night. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That'll be fine. Are you going to want to charge A again at all?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Negative, 11.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, this is Houston. At about 180 45, we'll be handing over from Goldstone to Honeysuckle, and I'm handing over to Charlie. See you when you get back. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Bruce. Good night. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Good night.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you very much, Bruce. It's been a pleasure working with you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Have a nice trip down.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. For RETRO, I have the anticipated location of all the entry stowage, and I suggest you pull out the entry checklist, and we'll go through those maps in the front of it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Could you stand by just a few minutes? Charlie and Flight are out getting a weather briefing. They'll be back shortly.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Is this Ken?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Say again?

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Is this Owen?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: No, this is Chuck Lewis. Charlie Duke is out with Flight getting a weather briefing right now.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. They're out drinking coffee. I know.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: They'll be back momentarily.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger, Houston. Apollo 11. Did you get the word on the entry checklist?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We sure did. We're ready to talk about it, if you are. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I think the quickest thing is to go through page by page, the first part of the entry checklist where it has a map. Starting on the page with compartment L2 and L3. Are you with me?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. With you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. L2 is as shown. L3 is as shown, there is about half the food remaining in L3.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Where it says - where it says "And note," the CMP PGA is located in the Lm-shaped bag with the other two PGA's. The IM held was jettisoned with the - Correction, the CMP's helmet held was jettisoned with the IM, and his helmet and gloves, instead of being in the sleep restraint, are in the hatch bags.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Let's see now. Your PGA is in the Lm-shaped bag with the other two PGA's, and your helmet and gloves are in the Lm-shaped ags instead of the sleep restraint.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The helmet and gloves are in the hatch bag, the great big bag that's underneath the left-hand couch that you put the hatch in.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. I thought I - That's what I copied. Okay. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. The next page is identical except want-picking point. out R1 we got the entry check-list. Other than that it is identical, and the third page has got some changes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: In Al - Are you with me? I'm over there in compartment Al, now.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Go ahead, Mike. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: In compartment Al, the 16-millimeter magazine will be located in window number 4 instead of 5. Tissue dispensers, there is only one of them left. And compartment U3, the 16-millimeter bracket is on window 4, and the PGA bag - add the CMP's PGA, plus add two LCG's. And compartment A8 delete two LCG's, and one PPK, making a total of four, and add 10 pounds of IM miscellaneous equipment. We told you five the other day. We think ten is probably closer. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Copy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: And that's all the changes on that page Ready for the next page?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Go ahead, Mike.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: On your next page, in compartment B1, we estimate about 15 percent of that food is remaining. In B2 we took PPK out of there and put trash in it. In B3, the 16-millimeter cable, the millimeters lens, and the right-angle mirror are on window number 4. And that there brings you all cup-two-date.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. How about the LEVVA's, Mike? Where did you put those? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: They're in the hatch bag.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Stand by. Our only concern, l., is with the stuff you got in the hatch bag. T at's pretty big bulk between you and A8, an we'd like to talk about moving that over to the sleep restraint. If you will stand by. I'll verify that. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Our recommendation on the gear you got in the helmet bag - correction hatch bag, would be to remove that stuff and put it in the sleep restraint under the right couch. The reason is that the hatch bag straps are only configured for zero g, and it is a pretty difficult job getting it lashed down. With the gear in the sleep restraint, it's a pretty standard lash-down procedure, and you could also use the Beta cord that you have on board. You concur? Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Yes. We'll look at it, Charlie, and let you know.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. And I got a couple of other things, Mike. We need to terminate battery B charge a. this time, and also, the weather is clobbering in at our targeted landing point due to scattered thunderstorms. We don't want to tangle with one of those, so we are going to move the - your aim point uprange. Correction, it will be downrange, to target for 1500-nautical-mile entry so we can guarantee uplift control. The new coordinates are 13 degrees, 19 minutes north, 169 10 minutes west. The weather in that area is super. We got 2000 scattered, 8000 scattered with 10 miles visibility and 6-foot sea and the Hornet is sitting in great position to get to that targeted position. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Some of the general last minute updates here. On the entry, we had told you on the camera to set it at 50 feet. It turns out the biggest number on the camera is 25 feet, so just set it at infinity. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. Infinity.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Hello, Apollo 11. Houston. We're ready to put you to bed and say good night, if you give us your crew status report and verify that you changed out the CO2 canister a moment ago. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. Crew status report follows: CDR 11023, CMP 10025, LMP 09027. Canister change complete.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you very much there.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: All men okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Thank you. Could you give us an onboard readout, please, sir?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Stand by. Okay. BAT C 37, PYRO BAT A 37, BAT B 37, RCS A 51, B 63, C 62, D 58.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Copy. Thank you much.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. It's good night from the White Team for the last time. We'll be off when you wake up in the morning. It's been a pleasure working with you guys. It was a beautiful show from all three of you. We appreciate it very much, and we'll see you when you get out of the LRL. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay, Charlie. Thanks to you and all the White Team for a great job down there all the way through. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Outstanding.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: ... very much, Charlie. Thanks.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Thanks to you guys, too.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And, 11, Houston. Mike, you get your chance at landing tomorrow. No got-around.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Roger. You're going to let me land closer to Hawaii, too, aren't you?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's right, sir.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. We got some word just a moment ago that the McDonald Observatory is - said they had picked up the spacecraft in their telescope. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Outstanding. We have been looking for their laser but haven't had much luck yet.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We'll pass it on to them, Neil. Thank you.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Hello, Houston. Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Go.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger. Good morning. What's the status on midcourse 7?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We were going to let you sleep in until about 190 hours. Midcourse 7 is not required.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11. Good morning from Houston. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Good morning, 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We saw you up stirring around, and we thought that you were probably eating our breakfast there. Just in general, we'll probably start coming up with the uplink of the state vectors and the target loads and what have you at about 190 50, somewhere in that area, and get you started to work.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And in the meantime, while you're eating your breakfast there, I've got the Maroon Bugle all standing by here to give you the morning news.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Glad to hear it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Apollo 11 remains the prime story with the world awaiting your landing today at about 11 49 a.m. Houston time. In Washington, House tax reformers have fashioned a provision which would make it impossible for wealthy individuals to avoid income tax entirely through tax-free investments or special allowances. Under the proposal tentatively adopted by the House Ways and Means Committee, everyone would pay taxes on at least half of their income.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Hang on a minute.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Standing by.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Okay, Ron. We're ready to go again. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Continuing with the Maroon Bugle. President Nixon surprised your wives with a phone call from San Francisco just before he boarded a plane to fly out to meet you. All of them were very touched by your television broadcast. Jan and Pat watched from Mission Control here. The launch of Intelsat from the Cape was postponed for the fourth time last night. The problem was said to be a malfunctioning nitrogen regulator in the second stage of Delta. A new attempt will be made to launch it tonight. The research submarine Ben Franklin, which is studying the Gulf Stream, set a record by drifting 24 hours from 10 to 100 feet above the ocean floor in 1300 feet of water off the Georgia coast. The mission is led by Jacques Picard. Wally Schirra has been elected to a 5-year term on the board of trustees of the Detroit Institute of Technology. He will serve on the Institute's development committee. Air Canada says it has accepted 2300 reservations for flights to the Moon in the past 5 days. It might be noted that more than 100 have been made by men for their mothers-isn-law. And finally, it appears that rather than killing romantic songs about the Moon, you have inspired hundreds of song writers. Nashville, Tennessee, which probably houses the largest collection of recording companies and song publishers in the country, now reports it is being flooded by Moon songs. Some will make it. The song at the top of the best sellers list this week is, "In the year 2525." Morning Bugle. Out.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Thank you very much, Ron.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, crew status report. .5.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Roger. We copy. And I have your consumables update, if you're ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. GET 189 plus 00; RCS total minus 1 percent, Alfa minus 11; Bravo plus 10, Charlie minus 1; Delta minus 1; H2 total minus 0.76 pounds, oxygen total plus 17.6 pounds. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. It doesn't look like we're going to be able to get quite back on the flight plan.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Not quite; just about though.
END OF TAPE

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Request POOR and A'CREPT, and we'll send your REFSMMAT, state vector, and entry target load. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: You have it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. It'll be coming up.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Can you tell us where the visor assemblies ended up, there?

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: We're going to follow your suggestion and stow them under right-hand couch.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Mighty fine. Break. The weather forecast in the landing area right now is .000 scattered, high scattered, 10 miles. The wind about 080 at 18 knots. You'll have about two 6-foot waves. Your Delta-The is plus 10 feet. And it looks like you'll be landing about 10 minutes before sunrise. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. Sounds good.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. All three loads are in. The computer is yours. Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And Mike, if you're on loop there, to extend the range and the constant g reentry, here, I've got a little procedure, if you would like to listen to it.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Stand by one.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: I'm right in the middle of my orange juice. Be with you in about 5 minutes.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Sure, no problem, standing by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Hey, Ron, I wonder if you could give us a good Navy explanation for this Delta-The time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Let me think about it, and I'll come back.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: You too, huh?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Right.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Collins has got one, but I'm not sure I buy it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, 11. We don't have to worry about it any more. The altimeter out there is now standard, 29.92, but basically what it means is that if I give you a plus 10 feet, for instance, that means that you will hit the water with the altimeter reading 10 feet. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: All right.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Ah, Collins was wrong.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. I have your entry PAD. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Stand by.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Standing by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay, I'm ready to copy.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Entry PAD area is the mid-Pacific, roll 000, 152, 001, GET 194 46 06, 267, latitude plus 1332, minus 16917, 064, 36194, 649, range to go 14045, 36275, 195 , IL max 154, 084, 22400, 1800), DO 400, , , sextant star 45 0189, 277, boresight star, none available, lift vector up. Comments: GDC align, Vega and Deneb, roll 078, pitch 223, yaw 340. Additional comments: Use nonexit EMS pattern, EI minus 30, horizon check GET 194 33 06. Pitch 298. You'll ge P65, but no P66. , , 45, 0189, 277, none available, lift vector up, GDC align, Vega and Deneb, roll 078, pitch 223, yaw 340. Use nonexit EMS. EI minus 30, horizon check 194 33 06, pitch 298. Initial bank angle in P67 may not be full lift, and we will get P65 but no P66.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Roger. On your GDC align pitch, it should be 233, 233 in the pitch. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. I've got a P23.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Also your DL and MAX and MIN, I'm sure, are 22 400 and 18 000. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Yes. That's right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. If you'll dig out your entry checklist there on page E6-1, I'll update your RETRO times there for the various altitudes. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. On page E6-1, your RRT is 07 20 your 50K is 08 16, 40K is 08 30; your 24K is 09 02, and your 10K is 09 51. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. RRT, 07 20, 50 000, 08 16. That's - 07 20 is - is the time of steam pressure peg from RRT, and 40 000, 08 30, 24 000, 09 02, 10 000, 09 51.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. You started out right, and then the numbers you read back were correct, but I didn't get your comment in between there.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: I assume that - all I wanted to know is that first time, 07 20, that's the time of steam pressure peg. Right?

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. One, I'm ready to copy your message about the constant drag level.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, Mike. Of course, this is in the event the G&N and the EMS quits and you have to fly the constant g; and what we're trying to do is extend the constant g range from 1100 to 1500 miles. We've run this procedure in the simulator, and it works fine. Basically, I'll go through it - just go through it, and then if you have any questions come back. But it's the same lift vector up until MAX g, and then lift vector down, and then modulate the lift vector until g dot goes to zero. Okay. This procedure is essentially the same so far. And then hold g dot zero until you pass the RETRO elapsed time of V circular; and then after you pass this RETRO elapsed time of V circular, roll to a gimbal angle of 45 degrees, and then hold this constant bank angle of 45 degrees until you come to the RETRO elapsed time of drogues. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. It sounds straightforward enough. Understand constant g backup backup procedure, lift vector up until MAX g and then lift vector down, then modulate until bank angle until g dot equals zero. Maintain g dot equals zero until subcircular, then roll 45 degrees and hold until drogue time. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC END CF TAPE
blocks.text: Okay. That's mighty fine, Mike. That's correct.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: This entry time line is my kind of time line. Nice and slow.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay, 11. Houston. Roger. It sure is. EECOMM is anxiously awaiting his big moment here for the logic sequence check whenever you're ready.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay. We'll be ready for that in just a flash.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead, Ron.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: This is Jim, Mike. Backup crew is still standing by. I just want to remind you that the most difficult part of your mission is going to be after recovery.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Well, we're looking forward to all parts of it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Please don't sneeze.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Keep the mice healthy.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: The Earth is really getting bigger up here and, of course, we see a crescent.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Yes.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We've been taking pictures and we have four exposures to go, and we'll take those hard then pack the camera.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. We're ready for the logic check whenever you are. We're standing by to arm the logic. We've got YES logic on, YES AUTO, and all the circuit breakers in.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Roger. You can press on with the SECS logic.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Okay. Logic 1 coming on.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: MARK it.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Logic 2 coming on.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: MARK it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Logic checks good. You're GO for PYRO ARM.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you, sir.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11 has got VHF A Simplex on whenever you want to make a COMM check.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Roger. You faded out a little bit there, Buzz. I understand you have the VHF Simplex A on now. Is that correct? Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: That affirmative. VHF Simplex A and we're TR on VHF.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Mighty fine. We'll watch it as you are coming on in and let you know when the interference is up. We'll make a voice check with you at that time.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. I've been holding here in SCS control MINIMUM DEADBAND RATE LOW with the limit cycle on, just as a matter of curiosity, if you guys wanted some fuel numbers from that.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: 11, Houston. Roger. We copy and we've been figuring it out.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's a pleasure to be able to waste gas.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. That's affirmative.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston with a little recovery force information. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. The Hornet is on station just far enough off the target point to keep from getting hit. Recovery 1, or the chopper, is there; they're on station. And Hawaii Rescue 1 and 2, the C-130's, are within 40 minutes of your target point. Over.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Sounds good. Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Just to get a little downlink here to check out our VHF: I show us about an hour and 37 minutes, approximately, from entry interface. Over.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. That's about right.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Okay. Looks like we're together on that, and I guess we're standing by for you to whip into the entry attitude.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay. We've just been taking a couple of last minute pictures. We've finished the RIMS entry check, primary water EVAP activation.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Mighty fine.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Mike. We recommend the left OFF antenna for VHF.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: And this is your friendly backup CMP. Have a good trip, and may - remember to come in BEF.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: You better believe. Thank you kindly.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: We can see the Moon passing by the window and it looks what I considered to be a correct size.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Houston, Apollo 11. Like to switch to 3-band OMNI C. I just did a minute ago, and noticed a loss of signal strength, over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger, Apollo 11. Go ahead and try it again now that you're in attitude.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Roger. Going OMNI C.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Recommend antenna Bravo. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Recommend antenna Bravo, or at least a better one. Over.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: Go ahead, Ron.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. Faces are red here. We lost data with you there for a while. Did you do the P52? Over.

blocks.speaker: CDR
blocks.text: That's affirmative, we completed the P52. We'll give you the data from it in just a second. We passed our sextant star check at entry attitude, and right now we're maneuvering to our first horizon check pitch attitude of 98 degrees.

blocks.text: Roger. Copy that, 11.

blocks.text: You better believe. That old service module has taken good care of us. We want to take good care of it.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: It sure has, hasn't it.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: It's been a champ.

blocks.text: Thank you.

blocks.speaker: CC

blocks.text: Go ahead, Houston. Apollo 11.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. We have our update at the state vector out there for you. Request POOR and ACCEPT. Over.

blocks.text: )okay. You've got it.

blocks.text: )okay. Here it comes.

blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Go ahead.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Roger. The computer is yours now. Looks like you're in VHF range, here. So we'll try a VHF check for you. We'll just send VHF up to you. Stand by.

blocks.speaker: LMP
blocks.text: Okay.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. VHF check on Simplex Alfa. Over.

blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Backup Is-band now, and we're standing by for command module RCS activation.

blocks.text: Okay. We're just about there.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston, you're GO for PYRO ARM.

blocks.speaker: CMP
blocks.text: Thank you, Houston.

blocks.speaker: CC
blocks.text: Apollo 11, Houston. Your command module pressurization looks mighty fine to us.

blocks.speaker: LMP
